<HEADLINE> Clinton to Visit U.S. Troops in Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- United States President
Bill Clinton will make a Christmas visit to American troops in
Bosnia next week.
</P>
<P>
The president said on Monday said that his trip is to thank
American troops for the sacrifices they contribute to the peace.
</P>
<P>
"The main thing I'm doing is going to Bosnia to thank the
American military personnel for being there and for spending their
Christmas there, and for the sacrifices they've made to bring
peace to Bosnia and to tell them why it's important," Clinton told
reporters Monday.
</P>
<P>
Clinton is expected to leave on Sunday and most likely go to
Tuzla and Sarajevo on Monday to meet U.S. troops and leaders of
the Bosnian federation government, White House spokesman Michael
McCurry said Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The president has been with his advisors, thinking about the
future of Bosnia, thinking how much better positioned the future
will be because of the current Stabilization Force mission that's
deployed there," said McCurry.
</P>
<P>
However, the spokesman told reporters that no decision has been
made on whether to extend the U.S. mission in Bosnia. But he
reaffirmed that there is "a developing consensus" that an
international presence should be in Bosnia beyond June next year.
</P>
<P>
The Stabilization Force (SFOR), including 8,000 American
troops, is scheduled to leave Bosnia next June, but Washington and
its allies are considering a follow-on force beyond the deadline.
</P>
<P>
Asked on Monday if his trip signals his intention to keep
troops in Bosnia, Clinton said: "I'm going to have several
opportunities to talk to you over the next few days and I'll have
a statement about that soon."
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration has been caught between pressure
from Congress wanting a timely pullout and Europeans saying peace
will collapse if all the troops get out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
