<HEADLINE> Symposium on Periodicals for Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUILIN, December 16 (Xinhua) -- China's publishers are urged to
improve the work of newspapers and periodicals that cater to
children.
</P>
<P>
This was the result of a seven-day national symposium on
children's periodicals, which was attended by more than 40
officials from 20 publishing houses. The symposium ended today in
Guilin in southwest China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Current problems for children's periodicals involve circulation
systems, an incomplete market, neglect by officials and the low
status of editors, participants said.
</P>
<P>
While trying to raise the quality of children's periodicals,
publishing houses should also pay attention to adding more special
features of ethnic minorities in the publications, they said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
