<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait to Grant Total Foreign Ownership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait is to grant foreign
investors 100 percent ownership in private companies if a new
draft law is approved.
</P>
<P>
The draft, prepared by Kuwaiti Finance Ministry, will be
submitted to the Council of Ministers and the National Assembly
for approval.
</P>
<P>
According to an official source here today, the draft raises
the proportion of foreign ownership of private companies from the
present maximum of 49 percent to complete control, and exempts
those companies from taxes, in a bid to attract more foreign
capital.
</P>
<P>
The oil-rich Gulf emirate is striving to diversify its economy
and introduce more sophisticated technologies. Permitting foreign
investors to set up independent, fully-owned companies is regarded
as the first step toward a more open and liberal economy.
</P>
<P>
More steps will be taken to increase foreign investors' shares in
Kuwaiti companies, the source said. But for this end, amendments
to some other existing laws are also required.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwaiti government has formed a special committee in charge
of reviewing proposed projects of foreign investors to decide
whether to grant facilities or tax exemptions.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti Finance Minister Nasser Abdullah Al-Roudhan said last
month that the existing Tax Law of Kuwait hampering the inflow of
foreign capital has been amended by the ministry and is due to be
endorsed by the cabinet shortly.
</P>
<P>
He said the Kuwaiti Corporate Law which bans foreigners from
owning shares of Kuwaiti share-holding companies will be amended to
have the ban lifted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
