<HEADLINE> China, Republic of Korea Combat Illegal Immigration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Chinese police have
repatriated Korean Lee Sang Ho, who illegally ferried 95 Chinese
citizens into the Republic of Korea (ROK). They have vowed to join
hands with their Korean counterparts to further investigate the
case.
</P>
<P>
In May and July, Korean police sent two official letters to the
China National Bureau of the International Criminal Police
Organization (ICPO-Interpol) seeking cooperation in the case of
Lee Sang Ho.
</P>
<P>
Lee was caught on Aug. 9 in Shanghai soon after he entered the
city.
</P>
<P>
Investigation shows that from February of 1996 to July of 1996,
Lee and two brothers along with an uncle illegally smuggled 95
Chinese citizens into the ROK, charging 35,000 yuan (4,200
U.S. dollars) for each person.
</P>
<P>
His uncle and one brother were caught by ROK police in July of
last year when they were illegally ferrying 36 Chinese citizens
into Korea. Lee then fled Shanghai to Jiangsu Province in east
China, among other places.
</P>
<P>
On June 8 this year, an ROK court signed a warrant and with the
help of Interpol requested that the Chinese arrest Lee.
</P>
<P>
A senior official with the Ministry of Public Security pointed
out that Lee's action of organizing illicit immigration for
personal profit violated Chinese law and should be punished.
</P>
<P>
However, the official added, to strengthen cooperation between
the police forces of China and the ROK, Chinese police authorities
repatriated Lee.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
