<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cohen Refuses to Abandon Two-War Strategy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary
William Cohen has rejected a congressionally chartered defense
panel's recommendation that the Pentagon abandon its two-war
strategy.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that maintaining a capability... to fight and win
two major theater wars in overlapping time frames remains central
to credibly deterring opportunism and aggression," Cohen said
Monday in a letter to leaders of House and Senate committees that
oversee the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
This was Cohen's formal response to a report issued December 1
by the Congressional National Defense Panel.
</P>
<P>
The panel said that the Cold War era was over and the
probability of the United States facing two major regional wars at
the same time was very low. The U.S. military should change the
strategy and turn its focus on needed improvements.
</P>
<P>
The Pentagon has been making decisions on the overall size of
the military and its approach to modernizing forces on the basis of
the strategy that U.S. forces should be prepared to fight two
major regional wars at nearly the same time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
