<DOCNO> XIE19971217.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO FMs Meet to Do Year-End Review </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 16 (Xinhua) -- North Atlantic Treaty
Organisation foreign ministers met here Tuesday to ponder possible
future NATO missions in Bosnia, and review the progress their
alliance made during the past year.
</P>
<P>
The NATO Secretary General, Javier Solana, said that the North
Atlantic Council meeting at foreign ministerial level first
discussed the issue of Bosnia and then that of NATO internal and
external adaptations.
</P>
<P>
He said that the most interesting topic was the
political-military guidance to be given to NATO military
authorities for planning the mission after the current United
Nations peace-keeping mandate for Bosnia expires next June.
</P>
<P>
The military authorities will possibly start planning a
post-SFOR force in Bosnia with the guidance.
</P>
<P>
But the secretary general said that a final decision is not
expected until March 1 next year -- after thorough considerations
of the current situation in Bosnia during January and February.
</P>
<P>
All NATO foreign ministers, according to Solana, agreed that
Tuesday was a significant moment for the western military alliance
in that Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic were slated to sign
their protocols of accession later in the day after the foreign
minister meeting.
</P>
<P>
The NATO chief said that all the foreign ministers praised the
progress the three invitee countries had made during the accession
talks which lasted a little more than two months from September to
early November.
</P>
<P>
At today's meeting, Solana described 1997 as a truly remarkable
year in the history of the military alliance in that the meetings
held earlier in the year had laid the foundation of an inwardly
and outwardly renewed NATO.
</P>
<P>
"The new NATO is ready to meet the challenges of the 21st
century," he said.
</P>
<P>
When asked if the Turkish row with the European Union (EU)
would eventually spill over to affect inter-NATO relations, Solana
said the Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem had made it clear at
the meeting that NATO and the European Union are two different
institutions.
</P>
<P>
"In no case will the internal and external adaptation will be
affected," said Solana at a post-meeting press briefing.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, the Turkish foreign minister told the press
that the EU's decision on not inviting his nation to join was a
disappointment.
</P>
<P>
Cem said: "The EU summit decision, on a certain point, was
unfair, sometimes biased and sometimes with the connotation of
double standards. Sometimes it was based on exaggerated
allegations."
</P>
<P>
The European Union at its last weekend summit in Luxembourg
decided to invite Poland, Hungary, the Czech Republic, Estonia,
Slovenia and Cyprus to start accession talks early next year.
</P>
<P>
Five other nations -- Bulgaria, Latvia, Lithuania, Romania and
Slovakia -- were put on a slower negotiating track by the
15-nation union, leaving Turkey, a long-time applicant for 34
years, completely in the cold.
</P>
<P>
After hearing two reports on the latest developments in Bosnia,
the NATO foreign ministers discussed four options concerning the
possible follow-on force in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
The options ranged from total withdrawal of the NATO-led
stabilization force to a deterrent force with different force
levels and with different military tasking, according to a NATO
official.
</P>
<P>
A NATO-led ground force was described by the official as a
compliment and not a supplement to the United Nations
International Police Task Force (IPTF).
</P>
<P>
But no figures were discussed at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The size of the follow-on force was to be decided by the NATO
Military Committee, said the official who asked not to be
named. 
</P>
</TEXT>
