<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading US Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
news items in leading U.S. newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The New York Times
</P>
<P>
-- After the President of Iran's conciliatory remarks toward
the United States, President Clinton said he "would like nothing
better than to have a dialogue with Iran," but that his
administration was still committed to isolating the country as
punishment for a series of unacceptable activities.
</P>
<P>
-- The chief prosecutor of he Balkan war-crimes tribunal
complained to officials in Paris that war-crimes suspects in the
French-patrolled zone of Bosnia could feel "perfectly safe"because
French peacekeepers did not even try to pursue them. French
officials rejected the allegations and said their troops followed
NATO directives.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post
</P>
<P>
-- Moving to end a political stalemate over affirmative action,
President Clinton Monday installed Bill Lann Lee in the Justice
Department's top civil rights post on an acting basis instead of
waiting for the outcome of a confirmation battle that
administration officials acknowledged Lee had little prospect of
winning.
</P>
<P>
-- The Pentagon announced plans Monday to vaccinate all U.S.
military personnel against anthrax bacteria, marking the first
time that American troops will receive routine inoculations
against a germ warfare agent. The decision by Defense Secretary
william S. Cohen followed several years of internal Pentagon
argument over the need for the vaccine and the best way of
administering it to U.S. forces.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal
</P>
<P>
-- South Korea let the won float against the dollar Tuesday and
said it may issue bonds to raise money overseas. The country's
currency and stock markets rebounded strongly. but the permanence
of the won's comeback remains uncertain: Investors may be
disappointed by Thursday's presidential election because the three
main candidates and the government have flip-flopped repeatedly on
policy in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
-- Japan's ruling Liberal Democratic Party leaked a draft of a
plan to stabilize the country's teetering financial system that
includes the injection of 77 billion dollars in public money. But
the plan will give bureaucrats wide powers of discretion over how
that money is used. 
</P>
</TEXT>
