<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Hopes to Iron out Differences with Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
said today the Egyptian-Iranian relations which are now witnessing
positive signs have yet to see significant development.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters while touring the Obour city, east of
capital Cairo, the president said "nothing happened" except the
fact that Foreign Minister Amr Moussa visited Iran
recently. Moussa attended the eighth Islamic summit in Tehran on
December 9-11.
</P>
<P>
However, he expressed hope for improving bilateral ties. "I
hope existing differences would be eliminated as Egypt is keen on
sharing good ties with all countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
This is the first public reaction from Mubarak to Iranian
President Mohammad Khatami's optimistic remarks that "the most
appropriate climate" for better Iranian-Arab relations has been
created.
</P>
<P>
"The two major countries on the Islamic arena are Iran and
Egypt and nothing should stand between their relationship,"
Khatami told a press conference in Tehran on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Khatami hoped that through dialogue, Iran could "get closer to
our Egyptian brother, restore relations and set all our
differences aside."
</P>
<P>
Iran cut off ties with Egypt after it signed peace with Israel
in 1979. Presently represented only by interest sections at each
other's capital, the two countries have yet to resume full
diplomatic relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
