<DOCNO> XIE19971217.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Housing Starts Increase 0.8 percent in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. nation-wide
housing starts surged 0.8 percent in November to the highest level
in nine months this year, the Commerce Department reported here
today.
</P>
<P>
Construction of new homes and apartments totaled 1.53 million
at a seasonally adjusted annual rate, up from a revised 1.52
million in October, according to the department. The October rate
originally was estimated to be 1.53 million.
</P>
<P>
It was the strongest pace since a 1.55 million rate in February
and the first time in nearly nine years it remained above 1.5
million for three consecutive months. The September rate was 1.51
million.
</P>
<P>
Some market analysts had predicted a drop to a 1.49 million
rate in November. However, housing starts during the first 11
months of 1997 remained 1.1 percent below those of the same period
last year. For all of 1996, starts totaled 1.48 million, an
eight-year high.
</P>
<P>
Analysts believe that housing construction remains strong due
to job and income growth and mortgage rates near a two-year low.
</P>
<P>
A builders association survey in early December suggests that
housing will remain strong into 1998. The Housing Market Index
pegged to the survey rose to 59 from 56 in November, also showing
optimism about prospects for next year.
</P>
<P>
But applications for building permits, another barometer of
future housing construction activity, slipped 2.6 percent in
November to a 1.45 million rate from 1.49 million a month earlier.
It was the biggest decline since a 3 percent drop in October 1996.
</P>
<P>
Single-family starts, which are sensitive to mortgage rates,
rebounded 2.5 percent to a 1.17 million rate after falling 3.6
percent in October. They represent about 80 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, construction of apartments and condominiums, fell
4.2 percent to 365,000, failed to keep up the 16.9 percent pace
the previous month.
</P>
<P>
Regionally, the 41 percent starts surge in the Northeast, to a
165,000 rate, reversed October's 16.4 percent drop. The 9.2
percent advance in the West boosted the rate to 416,000, highest
since 418,000 in February 1996. However, those gains were offset
by a 13.7 percent decline in the Midwest, to a 270,000 rate, and a
4 percent decrease in the South, to 680,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971217.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
