<HEADLINE> World Output to Grow 3 Percent in 1998: U.N. Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 16 (Xinhua) -- World output is
estimated to have grown 3.2 percent in 1997 from 3 percent in
1996, and a growth of 3 percent is forecast for 1998, United
Nations Department of Economic and Social Affairs said today.
</P>
<P>
The financial turmoil in some Asian countries is expected to
"result in an inflexion in world economic growth, with the
slow-down in the more seriously affected countries and its impact
on their major trading partners being partially offset by
strengthened momentum elsewhere," the Department said.
</P>
<P>
It said per capita output in 1998 is expected to increase in 131
of 143 countries regularly monitored by the U.N., compared to 120
countries in 1997 and 67 in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Developed economies are expected to expand 2.6 percent in 1997,
against 2.4 percent in 1996 and 2.5 percent is forecast for 1998.,
the Department said in its annual report The World Economy at the
Beginning of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The major features of developed economies in 1997 are the
relative weakness of Japanese and strength of the United States
economies, with the U.S. estimated to expand 3.7 percent and Japan
to grow 0.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Developing economies are to maintain the 1996 growth pace of
5.7 percent in 1997, with a 5 percent predicted for 1998.
</P>
<P>
African GDP is to go up 3 percent in 1997, less than 4.4
percent in 1996 while a 4 percent growth is forecast for 1998.
</P>
<P>
Growth in Latin America and the Caribbean is to reach 5.2
percent in 1997, higher than 3.7 percent in 1996 while the 1998
figure is forecast to slow to 3.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
East and Southeast Asian economies excluding China is estimated
to grow 6.5 percent in 1997 against 7.4 percent in 1996 and a 6.25
percent is forecast for 1998.
</P>
<P>
Among the 15 largest developing economies, China is estimated
to grow 9.3 percent in 1997 compared to 9.7 percent in 1996 and a
further 10 percent growth is forecast for 1998.
</P>
<P>
Economies in transition are estimated to have grown as a whole
in 1997 for the first time since the cease of central planning
regimes, with a growth of 0.5 percent in Russia which is forecast
to further grow 1.5 percent in 1998, the report said.
</P>
<P>
For the whole economies in transition, figures are listed as
1.7 percent for 1997, minus 0.3 for 1996 and 3.25 for 1998.
</P>
<P>
The report said world trade staged a major recovery from its
sharp growth slow-down of 5.3 percent in 1996 with estimated
growth of 9.4 percent for 1997 and 7 percent forecast for 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971217.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
