<HEADLINE> Developed Economies to Grow Steadily: U.N. Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Economic growth in the
developed countries is proceeding at a relatively steady rate with
GDP having risen by 3 percent or more in 11 countries in 1997, a
report of the United Nations said today.
</P>
<P>
The countries listed are Australia, Canada, Finland, Greece,
Ireland, Malta, the netherlands, Portugal, Spain, Britain and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
Four countries namely France, Denmark, New Zealand and Sweden
are expected to join the group in 1998 while Britain and the
United States are expected to see their growth rates drop to
about 2.5 percent, the U.N. Department of Economic and Social
Affairs said in its annual report.
</P>
<P>
The World Economy at the Beginning of 1998 said developed
economies have undergone persisted or strengthened growth with
little inflation but with concern about limited progress in
reducing unemployment and Japan's difficulty in returning to solid
growth.
</P>
<P>
Consumer prices in the developed economies rose only 2 percent
on average in 1997, a record low since 1961. The average is
forecast to remain at 2 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The report said the continuing economic expansion is not
expected to have more than a modest impact on unemployment in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The European Union is expected to see its sixth consecutive
year of double-digit unemployment, with the 1997 figure standing
at 10.5 percent against 10.8 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Japan, which has undergone six years of economic growth
averaging only 1 percent a year, is forecast to enter a weak
recovery path in 1998, "although even this is uncertain", said the
report.
</P>
<P>
Japan, estimated to score a 0.8 percent growth in 1997 and
forecast to go up 1.25 percent in 1998, is some important trading
partners in Asia, which would further depress Japanese exports,
the report added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
