<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Trade Unions Threaten Another National </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwe Congress of Trade
Unions (ZCTU) today gave the government an open-ended ultimatum
to immediately scrap the recently imposed increase on sales tax
or face another devastating nationwide mass action by workers.
</P>
<P>
Meeting in Harare to review last Tuesday's unprecendented
national stayaway by workers, the General Council of ZCTU
resolved that "we will go back to the streets" if the 2.5 percent
increase on sales tax is not scrapped immediately.
</P>
<P>
The ZCTU also wants Home Affairs Minister Dumiso Dabengwa and
police commissioner Augustine Chihuri to resign from their
positions immediately as a conditon for workers not to go again
on strike.
</P>
<P>
Last week the ZCTU led mass demonstrations by workers
throughout the country protesting against arbitrary increases by
the government in taxes on fuel, electricity and goods and
services to raise revenue to finance payment of the former
freedom fighters' gratuities and pensions.
</P>
<P>
The increases on fuel and electricity have since been dropped
as well as a proposed five percent war veterans levy on
individual taxpayers and companies. But the sales tax increase
still remains.
</P>
<P>
ZCTU president Gibson Sibanda said, "if that remaining sales
tax increase is not removed without further delay we will be back
in the streets." 
</P>
