<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Signs Accession Protocols With Three Nations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 16 (Xinhua) -- NATO foreign ministers, in
the presence of their counterparts from the Czech Republic,
Hungary and Poland, today signed the protocols of accession to the
military alliance.
</P>
<P>
NATO Secretary General Javier Solana said at the signing
ceremony that the signing of the accession protocols had set the
tone for the western military alliance for the new millenium.
</P>
<P>
NATO will become one with new missions, new partners and new
structures, said the NATO chief.
</P>
<P>
It was the fourth time that NATO expanded in its 48-year
history. Greece, Germany and Spain joined NATO in the previous
three accession moves respectively.
</P>
<P>
The signed protocols will first be ratified by the parliaments
of the 16 NATO member states early next year and will then be
ratified by the parliaments of the Czech Republic, Hungary and
Poland prior to April 1999 when the trio can expect to become full
members of the alliance.
</P>
<P>
Solana said: "Today's ceremony is a profound sign of NATO's
transformation and how far we have overcome the divisions of
Europe.
</P>
<P>
"We are setting the tone for the new millenium -- a tone of
confidence and optimism for all the peoples of our Euro-Atlantic
area."
</P>
<P>
The NATO chief said that the western military alliance was very
different from the one of the first 40 years of its existence. "No
longer are we threatened by a confrontional East-West divide. No
longer are we subject to a threatening arms race," he said.
</P>
<P>
The signing of the accession protocols came at the end of a
two-month, five-round accession talks which lasted from September
to early November.
</P>
<P>
Solana said that the three invitees had firmly committed
themselves to meeting the obligations and responsibilities under
the Washington Treaty.
</P>
<P>
"You have expressed your wish to participate in NATO's new
military structure and you have undertaken to carry out the
necessary reforms," he added.
</P>
<P>
Polish Foreign Minister Bronislaw Geremek said at the signing
ceremony: "For over two hundred years, when foreign leaders put
their signatures under documents concerning Poland, disasters were
sure to follow.
</P>
<P>
"Today, I am to witness Poland's friends sign a document which
is a source of joy, pride and hope for me and my compatriots."
</P>
<P>
Hungarian Foreign Minister Laszlo Kovacs said that the signing
of accession protocols is a milestone both in the process of
Hungary's Euro-Atlantic integration and in the enlargement of NATO
that greatly contributes to the emergence of a new united Europe.
</P>
<P>
"Hungary considers the enlargement as a historic step that will
expand the zone of stability and security to the benefit of all
the countries of the Euro-Atlantic region," said Kovacs.
</P>
<P>
United States Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said that
the three nations were one step closer toward regaining their
place in Europe they lost 50 years ago.
</P>
<P>
"We are one step closer to having three more good, dependable
allies who are prepared to accept responsibility for the security
of others.
</P>
<P>
The 16-nation alliance decided to invite the Czech Republic,
Hungary and Poland to start accession at its Madrid summit. Prior
to Madrid, however, Romania and Slovenia had been hailed as
possible candidates for the first wave of NATO enlargement.
</P>
<P>
NATO Secretary General Solana reassured time and again after
Madrid that the door of NATO remains open to other potential
candidates and NATO enlargement will not be confined by simply
geographical division but will be gauged by common values and
interests. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971217.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
