<HEADLINE> Mozambique Denies Border Dispute with Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Felicio Zacarias, governor of
Mozambican central province Manica has denied border disputes
between his province and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
According to a report today by the Mozambique News Agency, the
governor made the statement on Sunday at a press conference held
in Sussundenga, Manica.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, both Eduardo Gimo, chief of Mossurize county in the
province, and Jose Amoda, the county's frontier commander said
some Zimbabwean farmers had been destroying or moving boundary
markers in an attempt to expand their farm land to the Mozambican
inland for planting tea, coffee and eucalyptus.
</P>
<P>
This is only an individual incident, Zacarias said, adding "I
don't think there are any actual border disputes between the two
countries in the Mossurize area."
</P>
<P>
The provincial government will restore the boundary tablet and
order in the region, since "there are still maps to resort to and
to clear the fact," Zacarias added.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that the issue could also be referred to the
Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Cooperation for settlement.
</P>
<P>
There is a border line of 150 km between Mossurize county,
Mozambique and Chipinga county, Zimbabwe. People living along
the border have long enjoyed friendly economic and trade ties.
</P>
