<HEADLINE> East Asian Summit Reaches Consensus on Issues: Qian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier and
Foreign Minister Qian Qichen said today that leaders at the
informal summit between ASEAN and China, Japan and South Korea and
that between ASEAN and China had reached consensus on a number of
issues.
</P>
<P>
The leaders shared the view that peace, development and
cooperation have become the main trend in the region, Qian told a
press conference he held here at the end of the summits today.
</P>
<P>
The consensus among East Asian countries is to maintain
long-term peace and stability, vitalize the nations through
economic and technological development and enjoy joint prosperity,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of the 12 countries agreed to further strengthen
cooperation in the economic and financial fields and in
international and regional affairs, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Qian said Chinese President Jiang Zemin put forth the
principles governing cooperation in East Asia, namely, mutual
respect, equal participation, mutual benefit and joint
development.
</P>
<P>
"We should intensify economic and technological cooperation,
especially hi-tech cooperation, set up a rational economic
structure in the region and bring about a non-exclusive and
non-discriminative model of economic cooperation which can help
countries make up for their deficiencies by drawing upon others'
advantages and strike a balance among different interests," he
quoted Jiang as saying. "We should engage in friendly dialogues
and consultations to build up confidence, broaden agreement, seek
common ground while putting aside differences, address differences
properly so as to ensure regional peace and stability."
</P>
<P>
Qian noted that in the joint statement issued after their
meeting, President Jiang and the ASEAN leaders laid out the
guidelines for bilateral relations and he called this joint
statement an important achievement of the China-ASEAN summit.
</P>
<P>
He said Jiang also had fruitful talks with the ASEAN leaders on
how to promote concrete cooperation in economic, trade and
technological fields, to which the leaders agreed to give priority
in order to turn the potential of the mutually beneficial
cooperation into the reality of joint development.  
</P>
