<HEADLINE> French PM Calls Charges of International Tribunal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 16 (Xinhua) -- French Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin today called the charges against France made recently by
the general prosecutor of International Tribunal hearing
war-crimes in Bosnia as "unacceptable" and "scandalous"".
</P>
<P>
The prosecutor, Canadian Louise Arbour, said in interviews with
French press recently that the Serb war criminal suspects feel
"absolutely safe" in the zone under the control of French troops
in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
She also accused France of refusing to cooperate by banning
French officers from making testimonies at the hearings of the
Hague-based tribunal.
</P>
<P>
When answering a question at the National Assembly, Jospin said
that France is "resolved" to see to it that no war criminals in
Bosnia escape justice and that all war crimes be punished.
</P>
<P>
"France is resolved to work in this direction, with its allies
and the prosecutors of the TPI (International Tribunal)," she
said, adding that France is ready to discuss with Arbour the
methods of cooperation "on the basis of a relationship of
confidence."
</P>
<P>
But he said that France will not accept "being designated
unjustly to public criticism."
</P>
<P>
French troops serving in the NATO Stabilization Force are in
charge of southeastern division of Bosnia, one of the three
sectors separately under the control of French, American and
British troops.
</P>
<P>
The French section includes Sarajevo and Mostar, as well as a
part of the Serb-controlled area, where live two men most searched
by the International Tribunal, former Bosnian Serb leader Radovan
Karadzic and former commander of Bosnian Serb force, Ratko Mladic.
</P>
