<HEADLINE> Current Account Deficits to Fall in Some East Asian Nations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 16 (Xinhua) -- With stronger exports
and slower import growth due to higher local currency prices of
imports, the current account deficits in some East Asian nations
are expected to shrink, a U.N. report said today.
</P>
<P>
The current account deficit in Thailand is forecast to fall to
about 3 percent of GDP in 1998, against 8 percent in 1996 and the
figure for Malaysia is estimated at 6 percent in 1997 and forecast
at 3 percent in 1998, the World Economy at the Beginning of 1998
said.
</P>
<P>
The annual report, launched by the United Nations Department of
Economic and Social Affairs, said the smaller deficits in
Indonesia, the Republic of Korea and the Philippines are expected
to be reduced further.
</P>
<P>
Countries such as Thailand, Indonesia and ROK are struggling to
get rid of the impact of the financial turmoil under an
international rescue package which has surpassed 100 billion U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Thailand's economy is estimated to
fall 1.5 percent in 1997 against a growth of 6.4 percent in 1996,
with 1998 forecast to see a 2 percent recovery.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia is to have a 6 percent growth in 1997, compared to
7.8 percent in 1996 and 3.5 percent forecast for 1998.
</P>
<P>
ROK is to go up 6 percent in 1997 compared to 7.1 percent in
1996 and 3 percent predicted for 1998.
</P>
<P>
The currency depreciations forced by the financial markets have
been helping the region to rebuild the export competitiveness
which some countries had lost.
</P>
<P>
The trend might raise fears that adjustment will come at the
expense of workers in developed countries who will not be able to
compete with the new low-cost imports, the report noted, adding that
some developed nations might even raise protectionist barriers to
these imports.
</P>
<P>
However, the U.N. Department said this fear seems exaggerated,
especially in the developed nations where employment has been
growing strongly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971217.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandela Woos IFP Again at Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAFIKENG, South Africa, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The outgoing
president of South Africa's ruling African National Congress
(ANC), Nelson Mandela, today did not hide his intentions of
wooing the Inkatha Freedom Party (IFP) for a possible merger.
</P>
<P>
The IFP was the only opposition party to be spared from
Mandela's attacks at the 50th national conference of the ANC.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said in his presidential speech that opposition
parties, non-governmental organizations and the media, even some
ANC members have formed a "counter-revolutionary" network to
derail South Africa's democratic process and development.
</P>
<P>
He said the ANC and the IFP, the biggest black opposition,
should not allow issues they disagreed on to stand in the way of
cooperation to achieve the "genuine emancipation of our people."
</P>
<P>
"Further, our two organizations are involved in a joint effort
to consolidate peace in the country and to encourage a culture of
tolerance and non-violent political competition among our
respective members and supporters."
</P>
<P>
More fundamentally, he noted, the two organizations had a
responsibility to cooperate to ensure the objectives of the
Reconstruction and Development program were achieved.
</P>
<P>
"We share the same constituency, especially the rural and
urban poor," Mandela said.
</P>
<P>
Lionel Mtshali, the IFP representative to the conference, was
the only person Mandela welcomed.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said there were good people in all political
organizations and that one of them was Mtshali, who is the first
IFP representative ever sent to an ANC national conference.
</P>
<P>
Mtshali was sent in after IFP leader, Mangosuthu Buthelezi,
declined a personal invitation from ANC Deputy President Thabo
Mbeki.
</P>
<P>
The ANC and the IFP were involved in a bitter struggle in the
1980s and early 1990s and clashes between them caused more than
20,000 deaths.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said in a televised interview on Sunday that the ANC
would welcome a merger with the IFP as a very progressive
development, because South Africans needed to speak with one
voice.
</P>
<P>
He had held talks with Buthelezi on the question of unity on
several occasions, and would be happy if Buthelezi were offered
the position of deputy president.
</P>
<P>
However, it is still not known whether the proposal will be
accepted by the IFP.
</P>
<P>
Buthelezi said earlier this month that his party wanted to be
at peace with the ANC.
</P>
<P>
"We can no longer afford divisions and we must realize that in
the end, if our country is to succeed, we must stand together,
failing which we are doomed to fall together," the IFP leader
said at the launch of 31 new IFP branches.
</P>
<P>
But the IFP said Monday that it had not been approached
officially by the ANC on a merger and that it was not considering
this matter because it was busy preparing for the 1999 general
elections.
</P>
<P>
Other opposition parties unanimously attacked the idea of an
ANC-IFP merger, saying that would give the ANC too much power and
would eventually lead South Africa to a one-party state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
