<HEADLINE> OIC Urges More Greater Cooperation Among Members </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Member countries of the
Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC) were urged today to
further strengthen cooperation in science and technology for the
benefit of the Muslim world.
</P>
<P>
It is imperative for the OIC countries to join hands in the
field of science and technology to face the challenges of the 21st
century, said participants of the Eighth Meeting of the OIC
Standing Committee for Scientific and Technological Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, opened here today by Pakistan's Acting President
Wasim Sajjad, is attended by delegates from 12 Muslim countries,
according to the official Associated Press of Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The participants noted that technology is one of the most
critical factors in facilitating and promoting economic
development.
</P>
<P>
Muslim countries should move away from simple import of
consumer goods and toward enhancing production capabilities
through technology transfer, they said.
</P>
<P>
They said that in technology transfer, priority should be given
to acquiring latest technologies, know-how and the capability to
adapt technology to needs and develop it further to achieve the
intentional competitive edge.
</P>
<P>
They called on the OIC member countries to work together to
achieve qualitative excellence in science and technology and thus
survive with dignity and honor in the next century.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, they also proposed to create an International
Scientific and Technical Center for Oil and Gas for the benefit of
the member countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
