<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Global Car Production Forecast to Rise 3 Per Cent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 16 (Xinhua) - Despite financial crisis in
ASEAN countries, car production all over the world in 1997 is
forecast to rise an impressive 3 per cent.
</P>
<P>
The increase is driven by the "Italian effect" in Europe, the
continued strong growth in Latin America and Eastern Europe and an
export-led rise in Japanese output, according to the World Car
Industry Forecast Report.
</P>
<P>
However, the report by Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI said that Growth
in global car production is expected to slow down in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Western European car production is likely to outperform the car
market in 1998, with strong stock build and export growth
following a record year for new model activity.
</P>
<P>
Although the European market is still some 200,000 units below
its all time peak, the European export base has expanded
significantly and imports are much lower than in the early 1990's.
</P>
<P>
In North America, total light vehicle production is forecast to
reach 15.4 million units this year. While U.S. sales are expected
to be flat this year, stronger demand in Canada and Mexico will
keep production humming along.
</P>
<P>
Japanese car output is benefiting from boosts in exports thanks
to a weaker yen, new product activity and healthy overseas playing
fields.
</P>
<P>
Brazilian car production for the first ten months of the year
is estimated to be 19 per cent higher than last year. Argentina is
matching Brazil's export growth. Auto makers continue to announce
new investment plans in the region.
</P>
<P>
Standar &AMP; Poor's DRI is the world's leading provider of
economic consulting and information services. It provides data,
analysis forecasts and expert advice to more than 2,000 business,
financial and government organizations world-wide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
