<HEADLINE> Cypriots Urged to Keep Cool by UN Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 16 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Resident Representative
in Cyprus Gustave Feissel today urged the Cypriots to keep cool
following a European Union (EU) decision on Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after a meeting with Cypriot President
Glafcos Clerides, Feissel said they reviewed the current
developments relating to Cyprus following the EU decision to go
ahead with Cyprus' accession talks.
</P>
<P>
He stressed his adherence to the primary objective of solving
the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
The EU on Saturday decided to begin accession talks with Cyprus
in March and rejected Turkey as a candidate for EU membership.
This move has angered Turkey and the Turkish Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash said Monday the
inter-communal talks of Cyprus are "dead," and that he will no
longer discuss the subject with the U.N. and the Cypriot
government.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. representative said Denktash is "upset" by the EU
decision, pointing out that "we have to keep our eye on the ball,
that is to solve the Cyprus problem."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the Mediterranean
island after a failed coup by Greek Cypriots seeking union with
Greece.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared in 1983 a breakaway "Turkish
Republic of Northern Cyprus" recognized only by Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
