<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey Indicates Most Britons Remain Opposed to EMU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- More than half of the British
people remained opposed to joining the European single currency,
according to a survey released today.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted by the Royal Institute of International
Affairs (RIAA), revealed that six out of 10 people polled
expressed opposition to the European Monetary Union (EMU) due to
be formally launched in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Among the 1,400 people survey, the RIAA report said: "Sixty-one
percent oppose British membership of a single currency, with
opposition fairly consistent across age groups, regions and party
identification."
</P>
<P>
"While this opposition undoubtedly reflects sovereignty
concerns, there are also fears that membership would increase
unemployment and result in EU tax policies," the report said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the report also pointed out that Britain would
eventually lose its influence in Europe unless it joined the
single currency.
</P>
<P>
"European Union policies and institutions will change radically
over the next 15 years as a result of enlargement and Britain can
and should play an influential role," the RIAA report said.
</P>
<P>
"Britain will lose influence unless it joins EMU by 2002. It
should act to ensure the right conditions exist to do so," the
report added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
