<HEADLINE> World Oil Price Forecast to Be Influenced by Saudi Output </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- World oil prices in 1998 is
expected to depend mainly on the level of Saudi Arabian oil
production next year, the Financial Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
Citing a report by the London-based Center for Global Energy
Studies (CGES), the newspaper said that the price of oil in 1998
"will depend crucially on the Kingdom's output stance".
</P>
<P>
It was reported that as a result of the recent decision by the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries to boost output by
10 percent, the Kingdom will be able to increase its production
from eight million barrels a day to 8.7 million b/d on January 1,
1998.
</P>
<P>
However, the big question is that no one knows whether Saudi
Arabia, the world's biggest oil exporter, will insist on producing
up to its quota ceiling or it will trim its output to prevent
prices from crashing.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper cited another report by the Oxford Institute for
Energy Studies as saying that Saudi Arabia has relatively little
financial room to manoeuvre as its finances will be undermined by
a relatively small slide in average oil prices in 1998.
</P>
<P>
It estimated that only a 1.65 U.S. dollars fall in average oil
prices next year will make Saudi Arabia to reap no financial
benefit from its increased output, and any bigger fall will result
in lower export earnings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
