<HEADLINE> France, Britain, Germany to Build Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 16 (Xinhua) -- France, Britain and Germany will
build a military satellite telecommunications system baptized
"Trimilsatcom" which is expected to enter service in 2005, the
French armament authorities, Delegation Generale pour Armement
(DGA), said today.
</P>
<P>
The three-nation joint project is aimed at replacing the
Syracus 2 telecommunications system of the French armed forces and
the Skynet system of the British royal armed forces, said DGA.
</P>
<P>
A protocol of agreement has been signed by the three nations on
the project, which is expected to cost 13 billion francs (2.2
billion U.S. dollars) and has been planned for several years.
</P>
<P>
The French Alcatel Alsthom telecommunications group and the
British-French group Matra Marconi Space are designated by the
three governments to elaborate their technical and financial
proposals on the project in two years' time.
</P>
<P>
The type and number of the satellites for the future system are
unknown yet, but the Trimilsatcom is most likely to be based on
several big geostationary satellites so that France and Britain
can continue to use their networks of ground satellite stations,
said experts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
