<HEADLINE> WFP to Provide 18,000 Tons of Food for Flood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. World Food Program
(WFP) will provide 18,000 tons of food in the next six months for
more than 600,000 Somalis hit by flood.
</P>
<P>
In a news release issued here today, WFP said that flood
victims would need about 30,000 tons of food to survive from
January to July when the next harvest was due.
</P>
<P>
The balance of the needs are expected to be met from food
stocks already in the pipeline for an on-going Somalia emergency
operation, the release added.
</P>
<P>
WFP estimated that the heavy rain beginning from the second
half of October had destroyed 31,000 tons of household food
reserves and expected crops.
</P>
<P>
The release quoted WFP agronomist Renato Murai as saying that
"these people have lost everything and have nothing to turn to
but food aid."
</P>
<P>
The torrential rains in the past two months have caused
flooding along the Shebelle and Jubba, two main rivers in the
Horn of African country.
</P>
<P>
A recent report by relief agencies said that more than 1,800
people have been killed and 230,000 rendered homeless by floods
duing the past two months in the country which has a population
of some six million.
</P>
<P>
As the floods began just after farmers had planted the Deyr
crop which is expected to be harvested in January, WFP
anticipated total crop failure in the country, especially in the
southern part.
</P>
<P>
WFP noted that "what is even more frightening is that the
seasonal rains in April could set off more flooding because the
flood waters may not have reduced sufficiently, and the damaged
embankments will not yet be repaired."
</P>
<P>
Somalia has no central government since Said Barre was ousted
in January 1991 and is ruled by a number of clan-based militia
leaders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
