<HEADLINE> Liberia Reopens Airport, Demanding ECOMOG to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The Liberian government has
reopened the Robertsfield International Airport and
demanded the west African peacekeeping force (ECOMOG) to move
military equipment away.
</P>
<P>
The airport, one of the largest in west Africa located 40 km from
Monrovia, the Liberian capital, was seriously damaged during the civil
war and closed since July 1990.
</P>
<P>
It was later turned into a military base of ECOMOG, whose jet
fighters over the past several months took off for neighboring Sierra
Leone to launch waves on the military junta there.
</P>
<P>
With the official reopening of the airport to commercial
airlines, the Liberian government has changed its policy towards
the presence of ECOMOG, the British Broadcasting Corporation
reported today.
</P>
<P>
At the ceremony to celebrate the reopening Monday, Liberia's
Vice-President asked ECOMOG to move its military equipment out of the
newly renovated airport in order to create a more attractive
environment for foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
The ECOMOG removal would help create confidence of businessmen
hoping to resume flights to Liberia, he said.
</P>
<P>
The statement is seen to clearly buttress an earlier commitment by
President Charles Taylor when he took exception to ECOMOG using
Liberian soil as a base from which to pressurize the Sierra Leonean
junta to relinquish power.
</P>
<P>
A delegation from the Ghana Airways attending Monday's reopening
ceremony said it would make its flight this Friday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
