<HEADLINE> Israel's Unemployed Hold Demonstration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of laid-off workers
in Israel today staged protests against unemployment in the
southern town of Ofakim, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Angry workers burnt tires, blocked roads and clashed with the
police, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
The municipal employees of the town also joined the
demonstration protesting against delayed payment of their wages of
last month.
</P>
<P>
The demonstration came after the release of national
statistical figures Monday, which showed that 14.3 percent of the
residents of Ofakim are out of work, the highest rate in Israel.
</P>
<P>
In response to the demonstration, Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu today appointed a committee to deal with rising
unemployment.
</P>
<P>
He assured a solution to Ofakim's unemployment problem in 30
days.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli opposition parties demanded that budget
deficit be increased to combat unemployment.
</P>
<P>
The left-wing Meretz Party had presented to the Israeli Knesset
(parliament) a no-confidence motion against the Likud government
over the unemployment issue.
</P>
<P>
Leader of the Israeli Trade Union Amir Peretz had said he would
lead an unwavering battle against unemployment.
</P>
<P>
He called on the government to establish an emergency fund
with 1 percent of the national budget, or 1 billion shekels (about
290 million U.S. dollars), to fight unemployment. 
</P>
