<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Trade Growth to Slow Down to 7 Percent in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 16 (Xinhua) -- World trade, estimated
to stage a surge of 9.4 percent in 1997 from 5.3 percent in 1996,
is forecast to slow down to a growth of 7 percent in 1998,
according to a U.N. report.
</P>
<P>
The annual report of the World Economy at the Beginning of 1998
released today by the United Nations Department of Economic and
Social Affairs said the trend largely reflects changes in the trade
growth of developed economies which make up over two thirds of
world trade.
</P>
<P>
The 1997 upturn was very much occasioned by the double digit
growth of imports of the United States fed by the strong growth of
incomes and the appreciation of the U.S. dollar, it said, adding
that there was also some modest pick up in imports in Japan and
Western Europe.
</P>
<P>
In addition, import volume is estimated to have grown about 10
percent or more in Canada and Australia, in several Latin American
countries particularly Argentina, Brazil, Mexico and Venezuela,
in Poland and in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Asian economies also provided their traditionally strong intake
of imports mainly in the first half of the year for East Asian
countries. while African imports grew at a moderate pace.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, the growth of world import demand is forecast to be
more evenly spread, with the U.S. import surge slowing, while
Japan's import growth slowly increases.
</P>
<P>
Slow import growth in East Asia and Latin America will not be
matched by more sharply rising imports into China and India, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
Coupled with slower increase in imports in Africa, the growth
of developing country imports is forecast to decelerate to a rate
of 7.25 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Major developed economies are expected to face export slowdown
in the adjusting Asian economies' markets where currency
depreciations are to help local export drive.
</P>
<P>
The dollar index of the prices of non-fuel commodity exports
by developing countries fell by almost 1 percent in the first three
quarters of 1997 and the general trend is expected to continue in
1998.
</P>
<P>
Crude oil prices declined by about 8 percent in 1997, averaging
about 18.5 U.S. dollars a barrel.
</P>
<P>
Barring major supply disruptions and assuming Iraq continues to
export oil as in 1997, oil prices in 1998 are expected to remain
within a range of 17 to 20 dollars a barrel, averaging about 18
dollars a barrel for the year, the report added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971217.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cold Snap Hitting Moscow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 16 (Xinhua) -- A cold snap recently has
claimed five people's lives and another 45 were hospitalized with
frostbite, the Itar-Tass news agency reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The cold spell in the Capital of Russia has caused record low
temperatures for the second day running. The temperature in
northeastern Moscow plunged to minus 28.8 degrees Celsius this
morning, making it the coldest december 16 here in more than 100
years. The previous record, minus 28 degrees Celsius, was
registered in 1902.
</P>
<P>
According to spokesman for the hydrometeorological committee
Anatoly Yakovlev, temperatures in Moscow districts and suburbs
varied from minus 31.1 to minus 34.1 degrees Celsius.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the air pressure rose to 774 millimeters of the
mercury column, compared with the December norm of 750
millimeters.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that other parts of Russia's European region
were hit even harder by the cold. Temperatures dropped to minus 40
Celsius in the central Vologda region, minus 42 in Arkhangelsk and
minus 45 in the Komi Republic.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said Tuesday is the last day of the current cold
snap. The mercury is predicted to rise to 20-22 below zero at
night, and further to 15-17 below zero during the day on
Wednesday. By Wednesday night, temperatures are expected to reach
7-9 degrees Celsius below zero. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971217.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> VW Plans to Produce Six Million Cars Annually by 2003 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Germany's largest carmaker
Volkswagen AG is planning to expand its annual output worldwide to
six million by the year 2003, a company spokesman confirmed today.
</P>
<P>
The Volkswagen AG, also the No.1 carmaker in Europe, is
expecting an output of about 4.2 million cars in 1997, up about 8
percent from the level of 1996.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2003, the company would expand its annual output
and turnover by about 40 percent from the 1997 level, with the
output to break the six-million mark, the German news agency DPA
quoted a Volkswagen spokesman as saying.
</P>
<P>
The company already announced in November that it would
increase its worldwide investment in the coming five years to 43
billion German marks, or about 24.4 billion U.S. dollars. By the
year 2000, the company would be able to offer a total of 50 car
models worldwide instead of the current 38. 
</P>
</TEXT>
