<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian President Vows to Remove Corrupt Police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian president Benjamin
 Mkapa said today that all corrupt elements in the police force should be
removed and made to suffer from their evil deeds.
</P>
<P>
"By making the corrupt officials pay heavily for their deeds,
every one in the police force will know that the practice is not
unprofitable, and its costs unbearable, " Mkapa said.
</P>
<P>
Opening the annual conference for commanders at the police college
in Moshi, the president said he repeatedly spoke against
corruption because the scourge threatens the survival of the nation.
</P>
<P>
"Corruption leads to miscarriage of justice," he said, adding that
people may be forced to lost their rights.
</P>
<P>
When the police, an institution where people turn for justice
also becomes corrupt, then the public will lose confidence in the
government, the president noted.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa said he is pleased to learn that efforts have already made
to cleanse the force, with some officials sacked in connection
with corruption and other malpractices.
</P>
<P>
The president urged officials in the police force to work closely
with the authorities, like the Prevention of Corruption Bureau (PCB), the
Permanent Commission of Enquiry, the Controller and Auditor General
and the Chief Government Verifier.
</P>
<P>
The PCB Acting Director of Research, Training and Public Education,
Augustine Buluda, told reporters last weekend that corruption is
rampant in most government institutions. He said the judiciary is on
the top list of corrupt institutions followed by the police force.
</P>
<P>
The government has flexed its muscles in combating
corruption over the past two years. PCB, in collaboration with other
institutions, has recovered 1.5 billion shillings (about 2.4 million
US dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
