<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian PM Meets Chinese Leader Wei Jianxing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister Inder
Kumar Gujral met here today with Wei Jianxing, member of the
Standing Committee of the Political Bureau and member of the
Secretariat of the Central Committee of the Communist Party of
China (CPC).
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Wei said that as the two most populous
developing countries in the world, China and India have much more
common interests than differences.
</P>
<P>
To maintain stable, long-term good-neighborly relations and
friendship between China and India is not only in the fundamental
interests of the two countries but also conducive to peace,
stability and development in Asia and the world as a whole, Wei
said.
</P>
<P>
Wei came here on Sunday for a nine-day goodwill visit at the
invitation of Indian Vice-President Krishna Kant.
</P>
<P>
He appreciated the Indian government's principled stand that
there is only one China in the world and Taiwan is an inalienable
part of Chinese territory while Tibet is an autonomous region of
China.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of Sino-Indian economic and trade ties, Wei pointed
out that the improvement of political relations has provided a
favorable environment for further increasing exchanges in the
fields of economy and trade, culture, and science and technology
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Gujral said Indian-Chinese relations have made progress in both
quality and quantity following President Jiang Zemin's visit to
India last year which opened a new chapter in bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that India and China should deepen mutual
understanding and strengthen friendship for the future of the two
countries and for peace, stability and development in Asia and the
world at large.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister also reiterated the Indian government's
principled stand on Taiwan and Tibet.
</P>
<P>
As to the situation in South Asia, Gujral said his country is
willing to improve relations with all neighboring countries
including Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Wei said that because both India and Pakistan are China's
friendly neighbors, China sincerely hopes that Indian-Pakistani
relations will be further improved and peace and stability
maintained in the region.
</P>
<P>
During the past two days, Wei also met with some other Indian
leaders including opposition party leader Atal Behari Vajpayee,
Lok Sabha (the lower house of the Indian Parliament) Speaker P. A.
Sangma and Congress Party President Sitaram Kesri to discuss
issues of mutual concern. 
</P>
</TEXT>
