<HEADLINE> Britain Hails Kyoto Agreement on World Climate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- British Deputy Prime Minister
John Prescott described here today the Kyoto agreement on tackling
climate change as a "political breakthrough".
</P>
<P>
Speaking at British parliament on the UN conference on global
climate held in Kyoto, Japan, last week, Prescott said the final
agreement "demonstrated beyond doubt that genuine political will
did exist in all these countries, and a political breakthrough was
achieved".
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, a cut of over five percent in greenhouse
gas emissions would be made by the developed countries by 2010
compared with 1990.
</P>
<P>
Prescott, head of British delegation at the Kyoto conference,
said: "I believe that Kyoto will be remembered in future as the
place where the world, in a United Nations forum, faced a crucial
decision and made the right choice."
</P>
<P>
Prescott stressed that Britain, due to take over the European
Union (EU) presidency early next year, faced a new challenge in
ensuring that the 15-nation bloc agrees to greenhouse gas emission
targets for each EU member. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
