<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraqi, Libyan Pilgrims Allowed to Enter S. Arabia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia said today it
will allow pilgrims from Iraqi and Libya, both under
U.N. sanctions, to enter the Kingdom during the next Haj season.
</P>
<P>
A government statement carried by official Saudi Press Agency
said that Riyadh authorities would take necessary measures so that
pilgrims from Libya and Iraq can perform religious rituals in a
calm atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia would reschedule flights to enable those pilgrims,
in accordance with authorized quotas, to be airlifted by third
part.
</P>
<P>
Haj is one of the five pillars of Islam and every Muslim who is
able, and can afford, to perform it should do so at least once in
his or her life time.
</P>
<P>
Haj usually takes place in December of the Islamic calendar
during which several million Muslims from every corner of the
world assemble in the holy cities of Mecca and Medina in Saudi
Arabia to perform pilgrimage. The next Haj season falls in March.
</P>
<P>
The statement said EgyptAir has been named by the U.N. Security
Council to ship Libyan pilgrims to the Saudi Red Sea coast city of
Jeddah from Tripoli and Benghazi airports.
</P>
<P>
It did not disclose a solution of the issue of Iraq, which
under the 1 per 1,000 quota system is allowed to send up to
20,000 pilgrims to the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-led Western countries imposed a "no-fly" zone over
southern Iraq in the wake of the Gulf War which evicted Iraqi
troops out of Kuwait. However, Iraq broke the ban last year with a
jetliner carrying 104 pilgrims on board touching down at Jeddah
Airport after permission from the Saudi authorities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
