<DOCNO> XIE19971217.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Confirms Fifth Execution of Jordanian by </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, December 16 (Xinhua) - The Jordanian government today
confirmed that Iraq authority on December 10 executed a Jordanian
prisoner on charge of murder, which has been the fifth this month.
</P>
<P>
Mohammad Ali Mohammad Sabbah, an Egyptian national with
Jordanian citizenship, was executed after he had been found guilty
in killing an Iraqi citizen, said Minister of State for
Information Affairs Samir Mutawi at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi authority did not inform the Jordanian Embassy in
Iraq or Sabbah's family members before and during the day of his
execution, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's embassy in Baghdad was told about the execution on
December 14, he added.
</P>
<P>
Sabbah was not linked to the four Jordanian students executed
on December 8 on charge of smuggling car spare parts worth about
800 U.S. dollars, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Mutawi mentioned that continuous contact were being
made by the government with the Iraqi authority to secure the
release of Jordanian detainees in Iraqi jails as soon as
possible.
</P>
<P>
He said that Jordan's strong reaction to the December 8
execution had not been intended to create a crisis with Iraq
but to express Jordan's condemnation to what had happened.
</P>
<P>
Jordan expelled seven Iraqi diplomats in retaliation of the
execution of the four Jordanians. It also called back its
charge d'affaires to Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, King Hussein repeatedly condemned the execution,
saying that Jordan would not make bargains with Iraq on the rights
of the Jordanians even if it cut off oil supply to the kingdom.
Iraq is the sole oil supplier for Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's government, House of Representatives and the Senate
all released statements, condemning the execution as inhumane and
unjust.
</P>
<P>
Jordan has made efforts to prevent Iraq from executing the
four Jordanians, but all of them, including those exerted by King
Hussein, failed.
</P>
<P>
Amid wide accusation from the kingdom, Iraqi Vice President
Taha Yassin Ramadan promised to secure the release of 140
Jordanian prisoners jailed in Iraq on Jordan's demand.
</P>
<P>
Later, Iraq declared that it commuted the death sentence on a
Jordanian prisoner named as Ammar Ghaleb Shehabeddine, who was
originally charged of smuggling car spare parts from Iraq.
</P>
<P>
There were over 100 Jordanian prisoners serving their
prison terms in the jails across Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Jordan and Iraq used to be firm allies before and during the
Gulf War. But after that, the bilateral ties suffered a setback
as Jordan was eager to distance itself away from Iraq to end
international isolation.
</P>
<P>
King Hussein gave asylum to top Iraqi defectors in August 1995
when the bilateral ties hit the lowest level in years.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Jordan expelled three Iraqi diplomats on charge of
espionage. The current expulsion has been the second in history.
</P>
<P>
However, the ties has been picking up in recent years as Iraq
begins to provide the kingdom with more oil at discount prices and
keeps increasing the volume of imports from Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Iraq provided Jordan with oil worth 625 million dollars
this year, a 7 percent increase over the previous year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
