<DOCNO> XIE19971217.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Electoral Commission Warns Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December (Xinhua) -- Kenya's Electoral Commission
today warned candidates against encouraging pre-polls violence
during their campaign for the December 29 general elections.
</P>
<P>
Samuel Kivuitu, Chairman of the Electoral Commission, told a
press brief here that some presidential and parliamentary
candidates are encouraging violence, adding that "they condemn it
during the day but preach it at night."
</P>
<P>
He called on Kenyan people to report incidents of violence or
intimidation and harassment to the commission which will instruct
the police to investigate and take action.
</P>
<P>
Following talks held between the commission and Kenyan police
today, a senior police officer said that so far two people had
been killed, 63 injured and 50 arrested in campaign violence.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued Monday, Kenyan police warned Kenyans
against carrying dangerous weapons at public meetings during the
electioneering period.
</P>
<P>
Incidents of people carrying dangerous weapons have increased,
it said, adding that "this increase has assumed some worrying
levels at this time of electioneering."
</P>
<P>
It was reported that youths of the ruling Kenya African
National Union (KANU) fought with the supporters of the
opposition National Development Party in Nymira over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
Reports from West Pokot said that youths of the opposition
Ford-Kenya interrupted KANU's civic campaigns and turned the
function into their own.
</P>
<P>
During the presidential, parliamentary and civic nominations,
candidates were required to sign the Electoral Code of Conduct
which is designed to regulate the behavior of all political
parties and candidates.
</P>
<P>
It is mandatory that every political party and candidate
intending to contest the elections must subscribe to the code.
</P>
<P>
Under the code worked out by the Inter-party Parliamentary
Group last month, parties and candidates are required to condemn
violence and intimidation, avoid using or publishing inflammatory
language to ensure that no weapons of any kind are carried to
political meetings.
</P>
<P>
The code provides that infringement of the code can bring
penalties ranging from suspension, disqualification and stopping
of candidates from participating in the elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
