<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Urges Afghan Parties to Settle Disputes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The Security Council of
the United Nations today issued a presidential statement, calling
on the Afghan warring parities to abandon military confrontation
and settle their disputes through political dialogues.
</P>
<P>
In the statement, the Security Council reiterated its grave
concern at the continued military confrontation in Afghanistan,
which had caused human suffering and material destruction and
threatened to lead to the disintegration of the country.
</P>
<P>
Deploring the unwillingness of the Afghan warring factions to
lay down their arms and cooperate with the United Nations for
peace, the Council stressed the continued military confrontation
in the country had posed a great threat to the regional and
international peace and security.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council also stressed the Afghan conflict had no
military solution and that the primary responsibility for finding
a peaceful settlement lied with the Afghan parties themselves.
</P>
<P>
It urged all Afghan parities to take genuine
confidence-building measures, to agree immediately on a
cease-fire, and to engage without precondition in a political
dialogue aimed at achieving national reconciliation, a lasting
political settlement of the conflict and the formation of a
broad-based, fully representative government that would protect
the rights of all Afghans.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council deplored the fact that foreign military
support to the Afghan parities continued through 1997 and
reiterated its call to all states to end immediately the supply of
arms, ammunition, military equipment, training or any other
military support to all parties to the conflict in Afghanistan,
including the involvement of foreign military personnel.
</P>
<P>
The Council insisted that the United Nations, as a universally
recognized and impartial intermediary, must be given all necessary
support so it can continue to play a pivotal, central role in
coordinating international efforts towards a peaceful solution to
the Afghan conflict.
</P>
<P>
The Council supported the efforts of the Secretary-General
aimed at the establishment of a solid international framework in
order to address the external aspects of the Afghan question and,
in this context, welcomed the convening of meetings of countries
concerned as well as those of the immediate neighbors and other
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971217.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Minister Supports to Implement Agreements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 16 (Xinhua) -- An Israeli cabinet minister
said today that he supports full and honest implementation of the
agreements between Israel and the Palestinian National Authority
(PNA).
</P>
<P>
Israeli Public Security Minister Avigdor Kahalani said he
opposes that one people control the fate of another, according to
Jerusalem Media and Communication Center (JMCC).
</P>
<P>
Kahalani made the remarks at a meeting here with PNA chief
negotiator and Minister of Local Government Saeb Erekat.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, they exchanged views on bilateral security
cooperation, but made no decisions, the JMCC said.
</P>
<P>
Kahalani has asked the Palestinian side to cooperate in
cracking down on car theft, which is rampant this year.
</P>
<P>
He said that a total of 43,371 cars have been stolen in Israel
since last January, 25 percent more than in 1996.
</P>
<P>
According to the estimate of Israeli police, 60 percent of the
stolen cars have been transferred to PNA self-rule territories.
</P>
<P>
Israel ordered 15,000 Israeli troops last November to work
alongside the police to prevent the stolen cars from being
transferred to PNA territories. 
</P>
</TEXT>
