<DOCNO> XIE19971217.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Cabinet Debates Pullback, Permanent Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Cabinet reconvened
late today to further discuss the planned second-stage
redeployment in the West Bank and guidelines on permanent talks
with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The crucial meeting was held on the eve of the Thursday
meeting between Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and
United States Secretary of State Madeleine Albright in Paris. The
cabinet was trying to formulate a final map over the planned
redeployment and final-status talks with the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA).
</P>
<P>
But the Prime Minister's Office made it clear today that
Israel would not announce a final map on the further pullback and
permanent talks until mid-January.
</P>
<P>
The office added that Netanyahu would update Albright on the
latest Israeli internal consultations when they meet Thursday,
but would not give a specific percentage of the second-phase
redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reported that Netanyahu would also present
Albright a 12-page report on what is called the PNA's
antisemitism and incitement against Israel in violation of signed
agreements.
</P>
<P>
The radio said Netanyahu is gaining understanding from the
U.S. that he needs more time to delay the second-phase
redeployment until mid-January after winning the Knesset
(Parliament) approval of the 1998 budget, which is facing strong
opposition from both the ruling and opposition camps due to
massive budgetary cuts.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu has to rely on the right-wing parties' support to
get the budget through the Knesset at the end of the month,
otherwise his government will fall. If he pushes hard now for the
approval of the controversial redeployment, the rightists will
take advantage of the budget vote to pressure Netanyahu to cancel
it.
</P>
<P>
During the first session held Sunday, the cabinet already
reviewed different maps of Israeli interests presented by Defense
Minister Yitzhak Mordechai and National Infrastructure Minister
Ariel Sharon. The two ministers differed on the width of two
proposed security zones to be created along the Green Line and
the Jordan Valley.
</P>
<P>
Sharon proposed creating a 10-15 kilometer security zone east
of the Green Line to divide Israel and the Palestinian self-rule
areas, and another 20-kilometer zone along the Jordan Valley.
Sharon calls for retaining control over the water sources and all
Jewish settlements in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai presented two maps, one on Israel's strategic
interests and another on the national interests. He proposed
narrowing the security zones along the Green Line and Jordan
Valley to three-six kilometers and seven to 10 kilometers
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Both Mordechai and Foreign Minister David Levy insisted that
Israel's holding on to less territories would help promote the
chance of advancing the peace process. Both favored earlier
withdrawal in order to win diplomatic points for Israel to get
out the international isolation caused by the stalemate in the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the PNA is increasingly losing patience with the
Israeli government, as shown in recent statements made by senior
Palestinian officials who warned against renewed violence and
confrontation.
</P>
<P>
PNA Communication Minister Imad Falouji told a PNA newspaper
Monday that "Israel is going to pay a high price if violence
reignites." PNA Cabinet Secretary Tayeb Abdel Rahim warned last
week that "our options are not closed if we feel we've reached a
dead end."
</P>
<P>
But Nabil Sha'ath, PNA Minister of Planning and International
Cooperation, said Monday in Paris the PNA is willing to wait
until mid-January to see whether Israel will make a concrete
decision on further redeployment.
</P>
<P>
He added that the U.S. supports the PNA in its demand that
Israel must agree to a time-out of its settlement expansion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
