<HEADLINE> Canada's Home Resales Down in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Sales of existing homes in
Canada's 25 major markets tumbled 10.4 percent last month, the
largest monthly drop since March, reports said today.
</P>
<P>
In November, a total of 17, 525 dwellings changed hands in the
country, according to the Canadian Real Estate Association.
</P>
<P>
On a year-over-year basis, November resales were 24 percent
lower than in November, 1996. Areas that were hit hard included
Victoria, Vancouver, Calgary, Toronto and Montreal.
</P>
<P>
Real estate agents attribute the slowdown to a lack of new
listings, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
"Too much should not be read into one month's data," the
association warned, noting that the markets will see a rebound
this month.
</P>
<P>
"Job growth continues to trend high, and a rise in short-term rates
often draws potential buyers into the market before financing costs
rise further," the association said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
