<HEADLINE> Ottawa Unveils Energy-Efficiency Programs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian government
unveiled new energy-efficiency programs that will cut the
country's green-house gas emissions by one percent, reports said
today.
</P>
<P>
The 60-million-dollar (42 million USD) initiatives would be
implemented over the next three years, and would help reduce
Canada's carbon-dioxide emissions by one million tons by 2010.
</P>
<P>
Canada needs to cut its emissions by 138 million tons to meet
its Kyoto commitments, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
"It's a small part of the solution; it is by no means the be
call and the end all," said Natural Resources Minister Ralph
Goodale while announcing the programs.
</P>
<P>
The programs involves financial incentives to encourage
energy-efficient designs for new commercial buildings and the
retrofitting of existing structures. 
</P>
