<HEADLINE> Syrian-Israeli Talks Not on Agenda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Assistant Secretary of
State Martin Indyk stressed here today the U.S. peace mission is
focusing on the Israeli-Palestinian track while the Lebanese and
Syrian tracks have to be taken up afterwards.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. hope that all tracks make progress, but now we
concentrate our efforts on the Palestinian track because some
agreements have been observed," he told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
He added that the U.S. is doubling its efforts to seek all
agreements on this track fulfilled.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Lebanese and Israeli-Syrian peace talks have been
frozen since December 1995 as Israeli current Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu refused to abide by promises made by late
premier Yitzhak Rabin for a complete withdrawal from the Syrian
Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon, whose 15 percent area has been occupied by Israeli
troops since 1985, insists that negotiations with Israel must
take place at the same time when Syria starts talks with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Indyk said on the basis of his experience, the Israelis want
to withdraw form south Lebanon and at the same time it asks its
north border security be guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
Indyk said all this should be put into the negotiation
process. But he didn't specify when the negotiation will start
and if the U.S. would to make more efforts toward that.
</P>
<P>
Indyk, who arrived in Lebanon this morning for a day-long
visit, had held talks with the country's leaders, including the
president Elias Hrawi, Prime Minister Rafik Hariri, House Speaker
Nabih Berry, Foreign Minister Fares Boueiz and Defense Minister
Mohsen Dalloul.
</P>
<P>
His talks with them focussed on bilateral relations and the
situation in the region, especially south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Before coming to Lebanon, the last leg of his regional
tour, he has visited Jordan, Israel, the Palestinian Territories
and Syria accompanied by U.S. peace process coordinator Dennis
Ross. 
</P>
</TEXT>
