<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Consensus on Continued Presence in Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 16 (Xinhua) -- NATO reached a consensus
today on the need for a military presence to continue beyond June
next year to further consolidate the peace process in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
NATO foreign ministers, who met for their annual North Atlantic
Council meeting, endorsed a politico-military guidance to the NATO
military authorities for the development of options for a NATO-led
military presence in Bosnia-Herzegovina following the end of
SFOR's mandate.
</P>
<P>
NATO military authorities will provide these options to the
NATO council in permanent session no later than mid-January 1998
to allow for the early selection of an option, following
consultations with non-NATO contributors and a careful assessment
of the likely security situation in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
The final communique of the meeting said that the military
alliance remains committed to the full and unconditional
implementation of the Dayton peace agreement and to the
establishment of that country as a single, democratic and
multi-ethnic state.
</P>
<P>
NATO foreign ministers also endorsed the conclusions of last
week's Peace Implementation Conference held in Bonn that are
intended to achieve further progress in implementing the peace
accord.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers discussed four options of continued
military presence in Bosnia. The options ranged from total
withdrawal of ground forces to a deterrent force with different
force levels and with different tasking, according to a NATO
official.
</P>
<P>
But no figures were discussed at today's meeting. The same
official, who demanded not to be named, said that the size of the
post-June follow-on ground force will be decided by the NATO
Military Committee.
</P>
<P>
A final decision concerning the follow-on force is expected to
be taken before March 1 next year, the official said.
</P>
<P>
NATO has contributed to consolidating the peace progress in
Bosnia by organizing and leading a Stabilization Force (SFOR) with
the participation of all 16 allies and 20 non-NATO countries
including Russia.
</P>
<P>
At its defense minister meeting held in the week before last,
NATO decided to keep SFOR at its current force levels (about
34,000) in Bosnia until next June instead of planned phase-out
withdrawal after local elections in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
The communique issued after today's meeting said that following
consultations last week with the non-NATO contributors, NATO
confirmed that SFOR would continue at its present force levels
until otherwise directed.
</P>
<P>
NATO Military Committee Chairman Klaus Naumann and NATO
European Theater Commander-in-Chief Wesley Clark briefed the
foreign ministers about the latest development and general
situation in the Balkan state.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers agreed that much more could have been
achieved had the authorities in Bosnia contributed their full
share.
</P>
<P>
"Peace, and the institutions of civil society to uphold it,
remain fragile," the communique said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971217.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GA Adopts International Convention for Suppression of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The General Assembly of
the United Nations today adopted an International Convention for
the Suppression of Terrorist Bombings, which was recommended by
the Sixth Committee (Legal).
</P>
<P>
The 24-article Convention defines a terrorist bomber as a
person who unlawfully and intentionally delivers, places,
discharges or detonates a bomb, explosive, lethal or incendiary
device in, into or against a place of public use, a state or
government facility, a public transportation system or an
infrastructure facility, with the intent to cause death or serious
bodily injury or the destruction of such a place resulting in
major economic loss.
</P>
<P>
The Convention specifies crimes which are extraditable under
treaties which states parties sign among themselves. it
explicitly does not govern the military activities of states in
armed conflict or in exercise of their official duties.
</P>
<P>
States which ratify the Convention must take steps to establish
their jurisdiction over terrorist bombings committed in their
territories. They can also have jurisdiction when the offences are
committed against their nationals or facilities abroad.
</P>
<P>
The convention will be open for signature from 12 January 1998
to 31 December 1999, and will enter into force thirty days after
the twenty second state party has ratifies it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
