<HEADLINE> Efforts on State-Enterprise Reform Paid Off (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government this
year has accelerated the pace of state-enterprise reform' and the
firms have initially rebounded in terms of overall economic
returns, according to Wang Zhongyu, minister of the State Economic
and Trade Commission.
</P>
<P>
Wang made the remarks at a three-day annual state economic and
trade conference which closed here today.
</P>
<P>
According to a commission report, China's state industrial
enterprises earned a profit of 22.5 billion yuan in the first nine
months of this year, up 66.7 percent over the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
State-enterprise losses for the year are estimated at 72
billion yuan, slightly lower than last year. "The downward trend
with increasing losses and lower profits has initially been
halted," Wang said.
</P>
<P>
Fourteen of China's 30 provinces, municipalities and autonomous
regions made a net profit through September, and another 12
entities reduced their losses compared to last year.
</P>
<P>
For 89 enterprises who registered more than 50 million yuan of
losses each in 1996, their total loss between January and
September was 2.27 billion yuan less than the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
Wang said the economic recovery could be attributed to reform
measures taken by the Chinese government in recent years,
including establishing a modern-enterprise system, optimizing the
capital structure and following the principle of "focusing on
reform of the large enterprises while allowing flexible operations
for smaller ones."
</P>
<P>
According to Wang, 100 enterprises will increase their efforts
to establish a modern system, which includes a limited liability
system, a legal-person property management system and a
legal-person management mechanism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
