<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Efforts on State-Enterprise Reform Paid Off  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The number of pilot cities undertaking reform of the capital
structure has increased from 58 to 110. The enterprises that
qualify for state priority support have increased from 300 to 512,
and the enterprise groups from 57 to 120. Of the country's total,
these corporations account for 73.1 percent of assets, 74.6
percent of sales turnover, and 85.1 percent of profits and taxes.
</P>
<P>
To support their development, the state this year has allocated
30 billion yuan to write off non-performing and bad
accounts. Chinese enterprises this year also raised 130 billion
yuan through domestic and overseas stock markets, providing large
capital back-up.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government also offered preferential policies for
large state enterprises and enterprise groups such as
self-controlled import and export rights, loan allocations and
other funds for technical innovations. Meanwhile, small
enterprises were also given more rights to restructure their
management systems.
</P>
<P>
More state enterprises have merged or gone into bankruptcy. By
the end of September, 380 enterprises with total assets of 14.8
billion yuan went out of business and 623 others with assets of 50
billion yuan were taken over by other firms. A total of 1.13
million employees were laid off in the process.
</P>
<P>
To ensure a smooth transition for reform, the number of
re-employment centers has been increased to 1,333 nationwide, at
which 760,000 laid-off workers were registered. A total of 2.45
million laid-off workers have found new jobs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
