<HEADLINE> China to Produce Generators for Three Gorges Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, December 17 (Xinhua) -- A contract was signed Monday
with Dongfang Electric Machine Co. Ltd. for production of two
turbogenerators for the Three Gorges Project at the middle reaches
of the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese company in southwest China's Sichuan Province is a
major subcontractor of the VGS group, a combination of Voith Hydro
GmbH, General Electric Hydro and GE International Inc, and Siemens
AG.
</P>
<P>
The VGS group, which was awarded the bid last year, has been
given the right to supply six of the 14 turbogenerators that will
be installed on the northern bank of the Yangtze River for the
Three Gorges Project.
</P>
<P>
An Anglo-French consortium, consisting of GEC Alsthom and the
Swedish-Swiss ABB, was awarded 420 million U.S. dollars worth of
contracts on eight other generators. China's Harbin Electric
Machine Co. Ltd. and Norway's Kvaerner ASA are major
subcontractors of the Anglo-French consortium.
</P>
<P>
Before this, Dongfang Electric had developed generators with a
capacity of 550,000 kilowatts in cooperation with the Canadian GE
Company for Ertan Hydropower Station of Sichuan Province.
</P>
<P>
According to earlier reports, the Three Gorges Project will
have 26 generators with a total installed capacity of 18.2 million
kilowatts. Another 12 generators and turbines will be built in
China.
</P>
<P>
The Three Gorges project -- the world's biggest of its kind --
is expected to cost about 30 billion U.S. dollars by its
completion in 2009. By then, the project will be able to generate
84.7 billion kilowatts/hour of electricity a year.
</P>
</TEXT>
