<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Plans Major Reform of Textile Industry (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government has
selected the financially troubled, worker-redundant textile sector
to be the prime target for state-enterprise reform in the next
three years. Successful breakthroughs in reforms in the textile
industry could set an example for other large and medium-size
state enterprises.
</P>
<P>
"China has set the target to resolve problems within three
years for state enterprises operating in the red. The textile
industry is the main target in 1998," said Wang Zhongyu, minister
of the State Economic and Trade Commission at a three-day national
economic and trade conference which ended today.
</P>
<P>
Wang told the conference that China has determined to make the
textile industry profitable again, to divert 1.2 million workers
to other job opportunities and to reduce 10 million old spindles
before 2001.
</P>
<P>
Data from the State Statistical Bureau indicates that China now
has 4,031 state textile enterprises with a workforce of more than
4 million, or 10 percent of China's total industrial employees.
</P>
<P>
The sector has registered losses for three consecutive
years. Some 1,031 large and medium-sized textile enterprises
posted losses of 9.63 billion yuan in 1996, accounting for 19.6
percent of the country's total. Both the number of enterprises
running in the red and the loss volume were the biggest among
all industrial sectors.
</P>
<P>
One of the main reasons behind the losses is an excessive
number of spindles. To reduce the number of spindles and encourage
cost-efficient production, textile mills have been offered
incentives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
