<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading US Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 17 (Xinhua) --The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The New York Times
</P>
<P>
-- President Clinton, ruling out nothing, warned Saddam Hussein
that he would consider other options for United States actions if
the Iraqi president continued to obstruct United Nations
inspectors, who have been barred from so-called Presidential sites
in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
-- A team of United Nations investigators, looking into reports
that more than 2,000 Taliban prisoners were killed by rival
factions in Afghanistan, said they found hundreds of bodies,
including victims who had been thrown alive into wells near the
northern town of Mazar-i-Sharif.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post
</P>
<P>
-- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto Tuesday announced
a surprise tax cut to jump-start the nation's stalled economy,
sending the Tokyo stock market and the yen soaring as investors
applauded the government's new-found willingness to break with
conservative fiscal policies and help lift the battered economies
of the entire Asian region.
</P>
<P>
-- President Clinton Tuesday promised to offer an activist
agenda in his State of the Union address next month and said the
balance of his term will be devoted to long-range problems such as
global warming and ensuring the solvency of Medicare and Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal
</P>
<P>
--The South Korean currency soared 9.7 percent in its first day
of unfettered trading, but economists and bankers warn a risk
remains of international-loan defaults by South Korean companies.
</P>
<P>
-- NATO foreign ministers worked to design a force that will
stay in Bosnia after the current mandate expires in June, and
Secretary of State Albright said the peacekeeping mission is "far
from over." Meanwhile, Hungary, Poland and the Czech Republic
signed agreements beginning the formal process of becoming NATO
members in 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
