<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Enterprises Urged to Set Up Collective Contract System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The All-China Federation of
Trade Unions (ACFTU) has urged the establishment of collective
contract system between management and labor.
</P>
<P>
The system should cover 70 percent of the country's state-owned
enterprises and 40 percent of its foreign-funded enterprises in
1998, the federation says.
</P>
<P>
Under the collective contract system, collective bargaining
agreements are signed between trade unions, on behalf of
enterprise employees, and enterprise managers. The aim is to
safeguard the legal rights of both sides and stabilize the labor
relationship, ACFTU officials said. The practice is widespread in
market economies.
</P>
<P>
The contracts involve salary, hours, working conditions,
insurance, welfare, labor disputes and employee duties.
</P>
<P>
Latest statistics from the ACFTU show that more than 187,000
enterprises have already signed collective contracts, covering
more than 54 million people.
</P>
<P>
Included are 141,000 state-owned and collective businesses,
18,000 foreign-funded enterprises, and more than 6,000 private
enterprises, according to the statistics.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
