<HEADLINE> Kim Dae-jung Makes Last-ditch Effort for Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 17 (Xinhua) -- With less than 24 hours left before
the South Korea's presidential election, Kim Dae-jung, presidential
candidate of the National Congress for New Politics (NCNP), today made
his last-ditch effort for support on the eve of the election.
</P>
<P>
"I am standing making my last presidential bid. I want to
devote my 40 years of preparation and experience to successfully
managing the state, bringing hope to the people," Kim read an
emotional message at a press conference. He is making his fourth
presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
The veteran opposition leader, 72, quit politics after losing
the 1992 presidential poll. But he resumed his political career by
establishing his No.1 opposition NCNP in September 1995.
</P>
<P>
Kim said he was completely positive that he will win the
election barring any last-minute campaign irregularities by the
Grand National Party's Lee Hoi-chang. The campaign will end at
Wednesday's midnight.
</P>
<P>
If he fails, Kim said, he will humbly accept the election
result and cooperate with the new President in leading the nation
in the right way.
</P>
<P>
"By voting for a change of power from the ruling party to the
opposition, you voters should show that Korea is a democracy," Kim
said.
</P>
<P>
If elected, Kim said, he will have those people who caused the
current economic crisis take political and administrative
responsibility for their misdeeds.
</P>
<P>
He reaffirmed that he will faithfully honor the agreement with
the International Monetary Fund (IMF) on its bailout loan terms.
</P>
<P>
However, he added, he will meet with Michel Camdessus, the IMF
head, to have additional talks aimed at preventing massive layoffs
and bankruptcies of corporates.
</P>
<P>
The opposition candidate also said he will grant a special
amnesty to the imprisoned former Presidents, Chun Doo-hwan and Roh
Tae-woo, to achieve reconciliation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
