<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hun Sen Opposes Delaying Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Cambodian Second Prime
Minister Hun Sen said today his government opposed a parliamentary
proposal that elections be postponed beyond the May schedule.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia's National Assembly (parliament) is considering
postponing the polls by at least two months to allow better
preparation for the elections.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen said his government insisted that the general elections
be held on May 23 as scheduled. If it was to be put off for
technical problems, it should be no more than one month.
</P>
<P>
But he said it was up to the parliament to make the final
decision.
</P>
<P>
Co-Interior Minister Sar Kheng, who is overseeing the election,
told members of parliament on Tuesday that the planned date was no
longer feasible as preparations, including voter registration, had
not yet begun.
</P>
<P>
He said at least 11 months was needed to have everything
prepared and the electoral committee itself would require 17 weeks
for training.
</P>
<P>
He suggested two alternative dates -- July 31 and October 18 --
for the election. Parliamentarians were expected to vote on the
dates today, officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
