<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank, ADB to Deliver Loans to Seoul Next Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank is likely to
deliver the first part of its promised 10 billion U.S. dollars of
loan to South Korea next Tuesday at the earliest, about a week
ahead of the original schedule, sources of the Ministry of
Finance and Economy said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The amount of the bank's first installment has not been finally
decided, but may be set between 2.5 billion to 3 billion
U.S. dollars, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank, ending two weeks of working-level negotiations
over the loan conditions with South Korean officials here, plans
to announce the results Thursday, they said.
</P>
<P>
As part of its loan conditions, the bank has reportedly asked
the Korean government to upgrade transparency of corporate
governance, reinforce fair competition policies and improve the
managerial soundness of financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the International Monetary Fund is scheduled to
extend an additional 3.53 billion U.S. dollars to Seoul Wednesday
in the second batch of its 21- billion- U.S-dollar rescue package.
</P>
<P>
The Asia Development Bank, which signed an accord of a
4-billion-U.S-dollar loan with the country last week, will also
send 2 billion U.S. dollars as its first installment next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Successive infusion of dollars this and next week is expected
to greatly contribute to normalizing the nation's foreign exchange
flows," said a ministry official.
</P>
<P>
However, the government will continue to persuade Washington
and Tokyo to extend loans to Seoul as soon as possible, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
