<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ramos Tells Police to Get Results in Fighting Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 17 (Xinhua) -- President Fidel Ramos Wednesday
challenged the Philippine National Police (PNP) to "get results"
in their anti-crime drive, telling PNP officers and men to leave
the service if they can not do their job as expected.
</P>
<P>
In his speech at a ceremony held for outgoing PNP Director
General Recaredo Sarmiento and his successor, Santiago Alino,
Ramos asked for a new creative effort on the part of every police
officer, regardless of rank and station, "to focus on the crime
categories that have shown a pattern of increase."
</P>
<P>
The president identified these crimes as kidnap-for-ransom,
drug trafficking, car jacking and rape.
</P>
<P>
"I tell you now to bring results, results, results," Ramos
said, adding every police officer must now stretch his imagination
and reach into his wits.
</P>
<P>
"Are you willing and capable enough to investigate a crime when
it is reported, hunt the offender, coordinate with all the pillars
of the criminal justice system and help convict the accused beyond
reasonable doubt?" he asked.
</P>
<P>
"If these questions do not bother you at all, it is time to
abandon policing your way of life and leave the service. The
community expects no less," Ramos said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the president appealed to legislators to pass into
law a five-year PNP modernization program so that the PNP can
respond to the needs of the times.
</P>
<P>
Sarmiento resigned for the PNP's failure to stop the high
incidence of kidnap-for-ransom cases in the country. Alino took
the oath to replace him during today's ceremony.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
