<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seizinger Wins World Cup Downhill for Fifth Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 17 (Xinhua) -- World Cup leader Katja Seizinger
of Germany shaked off her first-leg defeat to win for the fifth
time in a row in a women's downhill in Val d'Isere, France, on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The 25-year-old German trailed Norwegian Ingeborg Marken by
0.02 seconds in the two-leg downhill, but she came back to win in
the second leg, and the race.
</P>
<P>
Seizinger, who has won two downhills and two Super-Gs before
today's racing, timed two minutes and 1.82 seconds in combination,
while fellow Hilde Gerg second with half a second behind.
</P>
<P>
Marken finished third with 0.62 seconds behind the German.
</P>
<P>
The defending downhill Olympic champion tops the World Cup
overall standings with 643 points after winning all the speed
events this season, leading second Gerg by 214 points.
</P>
<P>
Former World Cup champion American Picabo Street finished 10th
with 2:03.85.
</P>
<P>
Strong wind forced the race to a shortened two-leg event.
</P>
</TEXT>
