<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Slams US Policy, War Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi official spokesman said
today that U.S. President Bill Clinton is again fooling himself
about the world's position vis-a-vis U.S. military threats to
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Clinton's statement at a news conference
Tuesday, the spokesman said Clinton has for the first time
admitted that there are parties willing to see the seven-year-old
U.N. sanctions on Iraq lifted.
</P>
<P>
Clinton reportedly said the number of states sympathizing with
U.S. firm position towards Iraq has increased recently more than
ever before.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi spokesman said that Clinton and his administration
have realized the isolation the United States had been driven
into as a result of its anti-Iraq policy.
</P>
<P>
The world public opinion has adopted a stand opposing
U.S. threats, having perceived the facts in relation to Iraq's
legitimate demands in defense of its sovereignty, security and
interests of its people, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
He said three permanent U.N. Security Council members, all
European nations except Britain, and the entire Arab countries
have objected to the logic of aggression and sabre rattling
pursued by the United States.
</P>
<P>
Iraq threatened on October 29 to expel U.S. weapon inspectors
with U.N. Special Commission on charge of espionage and put the
threat into reality a week later. This led to a crisis in which
Washington threatened war against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Under Russian mediation, Iraq agreed on November 21 to allow
U.N. inspectors to return to Baghdad to resume their work.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. sanctions imposed after Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait
can only be lifted when the weapon inspectors verify that the
country is free from powerful weapons.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
