<DOCNO> XIE19971217.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: Good Start for Hong Kong's New Era (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Almost everyone here agrees
that everything in Hong Kong has gone well since July 1, when it
finally threw off the 156-year-old British rule and came back to
the embrace of China.
</P>
<P>
As the year 1997 is going out, the gloomy prediction that "Hong
Kong is over" has not come true. On the contrary, the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (SAR) has shown the whole world its
vitality in its new era of development.
</P>
<P>
Just a week ago, Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa paid his first
duty visit to Beijing, where he made "a full report" to President
Jiang Zemin and Premier Li Peng on what had happened in Hong Kong
after the handover.
</P>
<P>
The two Chinese leaders and vice-premiers Zhu Rongji and Qian
Qichen recognized that the SAR government has done a good job in
dealing with internal socio-political and economic affairs,
keeping in line with the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
Similar views are shared by a number of national and world
leaders, who traveled to Hong Kong in the past few months.
</P>
<P>
Both President of the World Bank (WB) James Wolfensohn and
Managing Director of the International Monetary Fund (IMF) Michel
Camdessus said at the WB/IMF annual meetings here in September
that Hong Kong enjoyed high-degree autonomy and maintained its
prosperity, stability and lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
Choosing Hong Kong as the venue of the meetings was a vote of
cheer and confidence of the world for the SAR, they said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971217.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: Good Start for Hong Kong's New Era (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Britain's Lord Chancellor, Lord Irvine of Lairg, said at the
end of his five-day Hong Kong trip in September that he "looked
forward to the success" of the SAR under the "One Country, Two
Systems" principle.
</P>
<P>
A few important facts might be worth mentioning about the
success story of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
First, the rule of law has remained unchanged in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
With the power of final adjudication vested in the SAR's Court
of Final Appeal, which is now functioning fully and independently,
Hong Kong has gained a fully integrated system of courts for the
first time in its history.
</P>
<P>
A ruling of the Appeal Court on July 30 upheld the legitimacy
of the Provisional Legislative Council (PLC) and put the validity
of all laws it passed after June 30 beyond any doubt. The PLC has
adopted a great number of bills up to now, providing legal grounds
for the SAR.
</P>
<P>
Another important event in Hong Kong's legal affairs was the
election early this month of 36 Hong Kong's representatives to the
9th National People's Congress (NPC), the nation's supreme organ
of power. This was the first time for Hong Kong to elect deputies
to the NPC as an independent constituency.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, voter registration for the first Legislative Council
elections scheduled for next May is going on in full swing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971217.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: Good Start for Hong Kong's New Era (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Secondly, the SAR government has been functioning smoothly.
</P>
<P>
The government led by Chief Executive Tung has done a lot of
work in creating a good business environment, extending the mass
transit system and expanding infrastructure development, improving
education and promoting the well-being of the Hong Kong people.
</P>
<P>
For example, the government has speeded up housing supply, with
the objective of building 85,000 flats a year and achieving a home
ownership rate of 70 percent in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Tung visited a number of Asian and European countries to brief
foreign leaders and businessmen on the good situation in Hong
Kong, the southern gateway to China and an international
financial, trade and shipping center.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's 180,000-strong civil service remains "dedicated,
honest and efficient" within the framework of a small government
with less public expenditure.
</P>
<P>
Thirdly, the economy has maintained its vitality in the SAR.
</P>
<P>
The gross domestic product is estimated to have grown by around
5 percent in the July-September period year-on-year, and to
increase by 5.5 percent this year as a whole against 1996, despite
the effects of the financial turmoil which has swept some Asian
countries.
</P>
<P>
Though the performance of tourism, Hong Kong's top hard
currency earner, has been weak mainly due to the effect of the
financial turmoil and relatively high prices here, the overall
external trade has maintained its trend of growth in general.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971217.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: Good Start for Hong Kong's New Era (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As the IMF said in its recent assessment, the SAR, with high
foreign exchange reserves, fiscal reserves, a strong banking
system and solid economic fundamentals, not only succeeded in
beating back speculators and defending the l4-year-old linking
system between the Hong Kong dollar and the U.S. dollar in the
financial turbulence which affected almost all the main stock
markets in the world, but also withstood the effects of the global
financial market volatility.
</P>
<P>
Fourthly, the way of Hong Kong people's life has remained
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
In any teahouse here, the noise-level equals any New York bar,
Tokyo pub or Moscow cafe.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday evenings and Saturdays, tens of thousands of local
residents swarm to the Happy Valley and Sha Tin Racecourse to bet
on horse races.
</P>
<P>
The local media enjoy freedom of expression and say what they
want to as before, and protests are not forbidden even in front of
the building of the legislature.
</P>
<P>
The results of the latest survey by the American Chamber of
Commerce (AmCham) in Hong Kong reflected a positive outlook for
Hong Kong's business environment against the backdrop of the
recent economic slowdown in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
More than 96 percent of the survey respondents had a "very
favorable" or "favorable" view about Hong Kong's business
environment over the next five years, while over 55 percent of
AmCham member companies intended to expand their business and 89
percent said they will retain Hong Kong as their regional
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
The high level of confidence is related to Hong Kong's smooth
transition and political stability, sound economic fundamentals
and the overall rapid development in China.
</P>
<P>
In his policy address issued in early October, Tung Chee Hwa
outlined the priorities of the SAR government in the coming years
including moving forward in the high value-added direction in both
 services and industrial sectors. He also voiced determination to
strengthen Hong Kong's competitiveness and ensure its future
prosperity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
