<HEADLINE> European Union Expects to Expand Dialogue With China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) will
continue to strengthen and expand its dialogue with China,
diplomats from Luxembourg and Britain told a press conference here
today.
</P>
<P>
The press conference was jointly held by Pierre-Louis Lorenz,
Ambassador to China of Luxembourg which holds the current rotating
EU presidency, Anthony Sprake, minister of the British embassy in
Beijing, Jan Pieter Kleiweg De Zwaan of the Netherland's embassy
in Beijing, and Endymion Wilkinson, ambassador of the Delegation
of the EU European Commission (EC) to China.
</P>
<P>
In a briefing about the work that Luxembourg has done during
its rotating EU presidency from July to December this year, Lorenz
said that in the past six months the EU has insisted on conducting
more dialogues with China. He said the dialogues were positive and
that the EU will continue to conduct dialogues with China in
political and economic fields as well as security and human rights.
</P>
<P>
Sprake said Great Britain will make its own efforts to push
China's membership in the World Trade Organization (WTO) when he
holds the rotating EU presidency from January to June,
1998. 
</P>
