<HEADLINE> 27,000 Ethiopians to Have Access to Telephone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, December 17 (Xinhua) -- About 27,000 people
residing in eastern Ethiopia will get access to telephone service
this year when the installation and expansion works on telephone
lines are completed, a report said here today.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Ahmed Hussien, acting general manager of the
Dire Dawa region telephone office, as saying that the
installation and expansion of telephone lines are now in progress
in Dira Dawa, Harar, Jijiga, Asebe-Teferre and Gode Towns.
</P>
<P>
Ahmed said residents of the stated towns will be able to
receive both local and long-distance calls easily when the
expansion of automatic digitals and the installation of radio
receivers are completed.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he said, the installation of radio receiver meant
the establishment of telephone communication between Milso,
Asebeteferre, Gursum and Harar towns is underway.
</P>
<P>
Statistics showed that the Ethiopian Telecommunication
Corporation has currently 160,000 telephone lines, of which 70
percent is concentrated in Addis Ababa alone. The corporation has
a plan to raise the number of existing lines to 600,000 in coming
three or four years, expanding the services to 4,300 rural towns.
</P>
</TEXT>
