<HEADLINE> Indonesia Not to Ask for Rescheduling of Debt Repayment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government will
not ask for rescheduling of the repayment of the country's foreign
debts, a senior official said here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We've never thought of rescheduling the repayment of our
foreign debts. Indonesia is striving to meet its debt commitment,"
Minister/State Secretary Moerdiono said after meeting with
President Soeharto at his Jalan Cendana residence here.
</P>
<P>
Moerdiono made the statement when replying to questions on the
possible rescheduling of foreign debt repayment due to the fall of
the rupiah (national currency).
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's foreign debts stood at 117.3 billion dollars as of
September this year. Of the figure, the government's debt was 52.3
billion dollars and the private sector's debt was 65 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
At least 9.6 billion dollars of the total private debt would
mature by March 1998, Bank Indonesia, the central bank, said
earlier.
</P>
<P>
Some economists here said the huge private debt was one of the
most important causes for the devaluation of the rupiah as many
people rushed for dollars at the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
The value of the rupiah has dropped by more than 100 percent
against the US dollar since the beginning of this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
