<HEADLINE> British Veterans Campaign for Syndrome Recognition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 17 (Xinhua) -- British Gulf War veterans are
to gather at the Defense Ministry on January 17 in a co-ordinated
protest marking the seventh anniversary of the start of the air
war in the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
"Some families of Gulf War veterans who have already died will
lay wreaths on the steps of the ministry and the Gulf veterans
will lay their medals around them and walk away," campaign
co-ordinator Tony Flint told the Independent newspaper on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The mass protest is believed to be unprecedented in the history
of the armed forces and will underline the sense of abandonment
felt by many of those who have become ill since serving in the war.
</P>
<P>
Veterans, campaigning for official recognition of "Gulf War
Syndrome", believe the illnesses result from a cocktail of
chemicals given to the troops.
</P>
<P>
They say 140 have died in Britain since returning from the Gulf
and up to 6,000 are sick.
</P>
<P>
The symptoms include asthma, chronic fatigue, depression and
skin ailments.
</P>
<P>
About 51,000 British troops served in the Gulf war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
