<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Leader Li Ruihuan Meets With Australian PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Sydney, December 17 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese leader said here
Wednesday that Sino-Australian friendship and cooperation will
enjoy new prospects in the next century if the two countries
earnestly draw lessons from the history of their ties and keep the
overall situation and future in mind.
</P>
<P>
Meeting with Australian Prime Minister John Howard, Li Ruihuan,
chairman of the Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference
(CPPCC) National Committee, said that despite some setbacks,
Sino-Australian relationship in general has been developing
relatively smoothly.
</P>
<P>
Li, who is on a six-day goodwill visit to Australia on the
occasion of the 25th anniversary of the establishment of
diplomatic ties between the two countries, stressed that since
1990 the bilateral ties have been progressing in a relatively
healthy, rapid and all-round way.
</P>
<P>
He noted that high-level exchanges between the two sides have
been increasing, their economic and trade relations have been
enhanced and their exchanges and cooperation in such fields as
culture, education, science and technology have been expanding.
</P>
<P>
On some major international and regional issues, the two
countries have held consultations and cooperated with each other,
he added.
</P>
<P>
"China is satisfied with the development of the bilateral
ties," Li said, adding that China always attaches importance to
its relations with Australia.
</P>
<P>
"Although they are different in social system, China and
Australia bear no historical grudges against each other and no
conflict of fundamental interests exists between them," he said.
"Rather, as both countries are located in the Pacific rim and
their economies are supplementary to each other, there exists vast
potential for cooperation between them."
</P>
<P>
"The rapidly growing economic and trade relations have long
played a positive role in promoting the development of the
bilateral ties in various fields," he noted.
</P>
<P>
He told the prime minister that China appreciates the
Australian government's "one China policy," under which Taiwan is
part of China.
</P>
<P>
The CPPCC chairman said that at its 15th National Congress held
earlier this year, the Chinese Communist Party pledged to
unswervingly promote the policy of reform and opening up to the
outside world.
</P>
<P>
Li also conveyed the sincere regards of Chinese Premier Li Peng
to Prime Minister Howard.
</P>
<P>
Howard extended his warm welcome to the CPPCC chairman, saying
Li's visit indicates the importance China attaches to its ties
with Australia.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister stressed that the bilateral ties are built
firmly on the basis of mutual benefit and the Australian
government is satisfied with the development of the relations.
</P>
<P>
It is encouraging that people-to-people exchanges and exchanges
at the state or provincial level have been increasing rapidly, he
said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that such exchanges would continue.
</P>
</TEXT>
