<DOCNO> XIE19971217.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jospin Tour Seeks New African Partnership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 17 (Xinhua) -- French Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin began a tour of three African countries Wednesday in a bid
to reform the traditional model of Franco-African relations and
seek a new partnership with Africa.
</P>
<P>
Jospin, accompanied by several government ministers and a
delegation of French businessmen, will visit Morocco, which is a
major economic partner of France in Africa, before going to
Senegal and Mali.
</P>
<P>
Immigration and drug trafficking will be two major issues to be
raised in Jospin's meeting with King Hassan II and Prime Minister
Albellatif Filali of Morocco.
</P>
<P>
Morocco is expected to ask France to provide aid to the Nord
region of the country, where 30,000 tons of cannabis and hashish
were produced each year, and three-quarters of the drug were
smuggled and sold in Europe.
</P>
<P>
The Nord region is also the home area of one-third of the
720,000 Moroccan immigrants living in France, who left home
because of poverty and under-development.
</P>
<P>
In Senegal, Jospin will raise the issue of reforming the French
military deployment in Africa and discuss with Senegalese leaders
the training of a pan-African peace-keeping force by France and
other Western countries.
</P>
<P>
France also plans to hold joint military exercises with
Senegal, Mauritania and Mali in February next year as part of the
program to train a future African peace-keeping force.
</P>
<P>
In Mali, Jospin will discuss the reform of France's cooperation
practise with black-African countries. It will be characterized by
the establishment of a common aid program by European Union
countries instead of France alone for Africa.
</P>
<P>
Mali has complained about the disparity in aid by France to
different African countries.
</P>
<P>
France sends an average of 632 francs (105 U.S. dollars) each
year to each inhabitant of Gabon, a big oil producing country for
the French oil group Elf, while only donating 48 francs (8
U.S. dollars) to each inhabitant of Mali. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
