<HEADLINE> Inflation Low, Growth Steady in Guangdong in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Guangdong Province, an
economic powerhouse, is expected to achieve a GDP growth of 10.6
percent while holding inflation at 0.3 percent this year,
provincial Governor Lu Ruihua said today.
</P>
<P>
"The effective control of inflation is a key to ensuring social
stability," the governor told a meeting of the standing committee
of the Guangdong Provincial Committee of the Chinese People's
Political Consultative Conference.
</P>
<P>
The governor attributed the province's low inflation rate to
bumper grain harvests for four consecutive years. Construction
controls were another important factor, he said.
</P>
<P>
The province in recent years has successfully controlled
investment at 240 billion yuan (28.915 billion U.S. dollars) per
ye, Lu said.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the steady growth, the governor gave credit to
high-tech developments and industrial reorganization.
</P>
<P>
The province has also been successful in expanding markets,
selling one-third of its products to other parts of the country
and another one-third overseas.
</P>
<P>
The governor believes that if the province's economic growth
rate remains at around 10 percent in the coming 13 years, it will
be able to hit its goal of realizing modernization by 2010.
</P>
<P>
"Since we've achieved an average annual growth of as high as
16.7 percent for the past seven consecutive years, we'd better let
the economy advance steadily, to avoid big ups and downs," the
governor stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
