<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leonean Govt Forces Engaged in Renewed Clashes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Heavy fighting and intensive
military manoeuvres are going on today in south eastern Sierra
Leone as government troops fought a pitched battle with Kamajor
militiamen on four fronts, military sources in Freetown told
Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
"Our men are engaged in Makpele, Fairoh, Wonday and Zimmi, all
small-sized towns along the Sierra Leone-Liberia border," said
the sources.
</P>
<P>
He said casualty figures are high on both sides since the
fighting erupted on Monday. He said ECOMOG troops stationed in
Liberia have moved about four tanks to the border to prevent the
fighting from spilling into the Liberian territory.
</P>
<P>
Sam Dumbuya, a Kamajor leader attending disarmament talks with
the junta delegates in Freetown, accused government forces of
"provoking the Kamajor into fighting as they constantly attack
the positions they now hold in the south east."
</P>
<P>
"Government troops are using helicopter gunship to pound our
areas and setting fire to houses and rice farms in the area. We
resorted to action as we cannot sit by and let the atrocities
continue," he told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Major John Milton, director of defense information, rejected
the charges saying "This is nonsense."
</P>
<P>
"How can we do that when we keep asking the Kamajor to drop
their weapons and join us in finding a workable solution to the
political problem now facing us," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, travellers arriving in the capital have been
speaking of deaths due to starvation which has gripped parts of
the south, with women and children feeding on garri, salt and
pepper.
</P>
<P>
A medical officer who came to the capital to sensitize medical
officials of the plight said, "people are dying at about 10 a
week because there is no food."
</P>
<P>
According to Dr Boise Williams, there are no medicines and
people are now using local herbs to cure themselves.
</P>
<P>
Colonel Kis Kamara, former Minister of Health who has now been
transferred to the Ministry of Internal Affairs as a result of
Monday's cabinet reshuffle, said in an interview that "much
needed drugs are running out because of the sanctions and
embargo."
</P>
<P>
"This means that more people are at the risk of dying if the
situation continues as the hospitals are all seriously affected,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
A nurse at the central hospital in the capital said, "many
patients would have to die at an alarming rate if the situation
continues as it is." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
