<HEADLINE> Justice Minister: China Making Progress in Judicial Work (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Judicial groups must play a
bigger role in carrying out the law, offering legal services and
publicizing the law in the process of building a socialist
country, Minister of Justice Xiao Yang said today.
</P>
<P>
Those working in the judicial sector should emancipate their
minds and update their views to implement the basic principle of
governing the country in accordance with the law, Xiao told a
national conference.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, held in the capital of east China's Shandong
Province, was attended by directors of provincial judicial
departments.
</P>
<P>
Reviewing the last five years' work, the minister said 20 model
prisons and 15 model re-education-through-labor centers had been
awarded by the Ministry of Justice.
</P>
<P>
"No more than 8 percent of those released from the prisons and
centers committed crimes again. In this sense, China is one of the
countries in the world with a low repeat crime rate," Xiao said.
</P>
<P>
In addition to improving the work in prisons and re-education
centers, China's judicial groups also have made great efforts to
develop legal aid services.
</P>
<P>
The number of lawyers has increased from 40,000 five years ago
to more than 114,000, and the number of law offices has grown from
3,600 to 8,300. In 1996, lawyers across the country handled more
than 700,000 cases.
</P>
<P>
Lawyers are serving as legal consultants for 250,000
institutions and companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
