<HEADLINE> Winnie Declines Nomination For ANC Deputy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Winnie
Madikizela-Mandela today declined to accept nomination for the
deputy presidency of the African National Congress (ANC), leaving
the post to Jacob Zuma, South African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
Madikizela-Mandela was nominated today from the floor at the
50th national conference of the ANC in Mafikeng after failing to
secure nomination by any of the provinces.
</P>
<P>
Madikizela-Mandela, ex-wife of South African President Nelson
Mandela, is now president of the ANC Women's League and a member
of the policy-making National Executive Committee (NEC).
</P>
<P>
Her decision to refuse nomination is in line with a request
from the NEC that she should not make herself available.
</P>
<P>
However, some of Madikizela-Mandela's detractors said they
believed she did so to avoid possible humiliation should she be
defeated in the contest against Zuma.
</P>
<P>
Zuma's victory effectively confirms him as successor to Thabo
Mbeki in the deputy presidency of South Africa when Mandela steps
down from the presidency after the 1999 elections.
</P>
<P>
Zuma is currently national chairman of the ANC. 
</P>
