<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment in China Up 27 Percent in Jan-Nov Period </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Foreign investment in China
rose 27 percent in the first 11 months of 1997 despite a decline
of new investment, statistics from the Chinese Ministry of Foreign
Trade and Economic Cooperation show.
</P>
<P>
By the end of November this year, China has used a total of
46.959 billion US dollars of overseas capital, including 40.007
billion US dollars directly invested by overseas businesses.
</P>
<P>
During the period, China had approved 18,644 overseas-funded
enterprises, with a total contractual volume of capitals
reaching 48.462 billion US dollars. The figures were 15.34 and
27.14 percent lower, respectively, than those of the same
period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Among the newly approved overseas-funded enterprises, the
number of equity joint ventures and contractual
ones decreased remarkably, while that of solely overseas-funded
ones rose 4.12 percent to 8,484, and the capial actually used
was up 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
In this period, China has also approved 13 projects for joint
development with overseas enterprises, as against 10 last
year. They involve 205 million US dollars in investment used and
311 million US dollars in contractual capital, a jump of 14.53
percent and 61.98 percent over last year's figures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
