<HEADLINE> Information Technology Going to Hong Kong Schools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 17 (Xinhua) -- A pilot scheme was launched
here today in 30 Hong Kong secondary schools to explore how to
apply information technology in teaching and learning.
</P>
<P>
The Education Department today signed an agreement with
Hongkong Telecom IMS on the Intranet/Internet pilot scheme, which
is expected to involve 5 million HK dollars (640,000 U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
During the nine-month period between now and August 1998,
Hongkong Telecom IMS will provide the 30 schools with computer
hardware and software, along with support in networking, training
and customer services. Intranet and Internet sites will also be
set up for users to share all educational resources.
</P>
<P>
Dr. William Lo, managing director of the Hongkong Telecom IMS,
said at the signing ceremony: "We are delighted to be able to
participate in the meaningful project as we always recognize the
importance of information technology and computer networking in
education sector."
</P>
<P>
The pilot scheme aims at evaluating the Intranet and Internet
requirements for teaching and learning, so that Hong Kong can map
out its information technology strategies for schools in the
coming five years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
