<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Receives 4 F-16 Fighters from US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Jordan today received four
F-16 jet fighters as part of the 300 million U.S. dollars
aid pledged by the United States government.
</P>
<P>
Amid rain and thin fog, the F-16's landed in Azraq, about 80
kilometers southeast of Amman, where King Hussein and some top
military officials attended the ceremony to mark the event.
</P>
<P>
This is the first batch of altogether 16 F-16 fighters that are
expected to be delivered to Jordan by the United States. The
other 12 jet fighters will arrive in Jordan in the next two
months, Jordan's official news agency, Petra, reported.
</P>
<P>
Also arriving this morning was the first group of Jordanian
pilots and technicians who were sent to the United States for
training.
</P>
<P>
Last December, Jordan received 100 million dollars worth of
military equipment from the United States as the first part of the
300 million dollars aid. The remaining 200 million dollars of the
aid are spent on the 16 F-16 jet fighters.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government endorsed the aid program to Jordan in
1994 following the signing of the Jordan-Israel peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Jordan was granted non-NATO alliance status, giving
it more access to U.S. military equipment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
