<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tung Calls on HK People to Promote Understanding of Chinese Culture (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong people need to
promote their knowledge of the history and culture of China after
Hong Kong's return to the motherland, Tung Chee Hwa, chief
executive of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR),
said here today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening ceremony of an international conference
on heritage and education at the Hong Kong Convention and
Exhibition Center, Tung said that the better understanding of the
national culture can enhance the Hong Kong people's awareness of
patriotism and their pride to be a Chinese person.
</P>
<P>
The two-day conference, to mark the successful conclusion of
the "Year of Heritage", provides a forum for international
heritage and education experts to share their experience in the
field.
</P>
<P>
During the "Year of Heritage", a series of activities including
exhibitions, lectures, visit to historical spots and international
conference were jointly organized by the Antiquities Advisory
Board, the Lord Wilson Heritage Trust and the Antiquities
Monuments Office of the Broadcasting, Culture and Sport Bureau of
the SAR.
</P>
<P>
Tung said that the activities have helped arouse the interest
of the Hong Kong people, especially the young people, in the
history and culture of China.
</P>
<P>
Due to historical reasons, Hong Kong has been separated from
the motherland for a long time and the people in Hong Kong and the
people on the mainland live under different social systems and
cultural environments, Tung said.
</P>
<P>
"The Hong Kong people should know the root of the culture of
Hong Kong and strengthen our feeling of integration to Hong Kong
and the motherland," Tung said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971217.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tung Calls on HK People to Promote Understanding of Chinese Culture (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Some people think Hong Kong only has a history of 156 years,
and they think Hong Kong becomes an international city from a
small fishing island over a period of one hundred years, Tung
said.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the history of Hong Kong can be dated back to 6,000
years ago. The large number of historical relics excavated in Hong
Kong are witnesses of the history of Hong Kong, he added.
</P>
<P>
What's more, the relics demonstrated that the civilization of
Hong Kong can be traced to the same origin of the great Chinese
civilization, Tung said.
</P>
<P>
"When I visited the exhibition of Chinese cultural relics,
which is being held in Hong Kong, I was deeply moved by the
brilliant civilization of China," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Today's conference will enable us to learn the latest
development of the heritage and education of the world and promote
the work of heritage protection of Hong Kong," Tung said.
</P>
<P>
The conference aims at examining the different roles played by
various parties in heritage education. They include the
government, international organizations, schools, museums,
heritage institutions, learned societies, media, publishers and
commercial concerns.
</P>
<P>
It will also address the educational aspect of heritage
conservation through case studies and provide a forum for
international heritage workers to share their valuable experience
in the field.
</P>
<P>
The two-day conference is conducted in the form of plenary and
concurrent sessions with papers presented by about 50 speakers
from China's mainland, Hong Kong, Macao, India, Malaysia,
Singapore, Britain, the United States, Canada, Australia, Mexico,
Bermuda, and the United Nations Educational, Scientific and
Cultural Organization (UNESCO).
</P>
<P>
Exhibitions on local heritage and the work and achievements of
local and overseas institutions on heritage education are also
staged at the venue of the conference.  
</P>
</TEXT>
