<HEADLINE> Stocks Rise Sharply in Tokyo on Tax Cut News </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Tokyo stock prices closed sharply
higher Wednesday on the news that the government will cut 2 trillion yen
(about 15.7 billion dollars) in income tax and residential tax to
stimulate the sagging economy.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei average of 225 selected issues on the First Section of
the Tokyo Stock Exchange jumped 555.85 points, or 3.48 percent from
Tuesday's close to 16,541.06.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
issues on the First Section, rose 28.53 points, or 2.38 percent to
1,227.95.
</P>
<P>
Volume on the First Section came to an estimated 600 million
shares, up from Tuesday's 419.35 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Failed Yamaichi Securities was Wednesday's most actively traded
issue.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei index, which remained weak in early trading, responded
quickly to the tax cut news.
</P>
<P>
When the news was reported at midmorning and confirmed by Prime
Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto at a press conference, the benchmark index
briefly soared more than 800 points.
</P>
<P>
The tax cut decision by Hashimoto, combined with a rumor that the
Bank of Japan intervened to sell dollars, stimulated the currency
market. The U.S. dollar had plunged more than 5 yen at one point to
the 125 yen level in Tokyo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
