<DOCNO> XIE19971217.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Sino-Portuguese Friendly Cooperation Promotes Macao Stable Transition (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Sino-Portuguese Joint Liaison Group (JLG) discussed a wide
range of issues concerning Macao's transition this year. New
progress was scored in many fields.
</P>
<P>
The JLG approved the air agreements Macao signed with India,
the Philippines, Nepal and Myanmar respectively, and agreed to the
renewal of Macao's member status to a number of international
bodies. The JLG also completed discussions of the establishment of
a Portuguese consulate in Macao and China's Foreign Ministry Macao
Office.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the JLG concluded negotiations on the contract on
casinos and successfully resolved the "Oriental Foundation Issue"
after prolonged talks. It also explored new issues like the
handover ceremony in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Officials of both sides agreed that new progress had been made
in the three leading issues of transition -- the localization of
the civil service, the localization of law and the use of Chinese
as an official language.
</P>
<P>
By the end of November, about 86 percent of the lower ranking
positions of the civil service had been localized, and a first
Chinese director of a government department assumed office last
month. The Portuguese side promised earlier to have all middle and
senior ranking posts basically localized by the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
While local residents took office as judges and procurators,
the Criminal Law and the Code of Criminal Procedure were localized
and took effect. Localization of other leading laws is also being
conducted with great efforts.
</P>
<P>
And the use of Chinese as an official language has been spread
further. More than 90 percent of the government documents are now
printed in both Portuguese and Chinese.
</P>
<P>
But Chinese officials said that the workload in the three
leading issues and other related issues is still very heavy.
Greater efforts are needed to ensure a smooth handover and stable
transition.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the two countries have reiterated that it is in the
utmost common interests of both peoples to strengthen the friendly
relations between China and Portugal. They have vowed to make more
efforts to bring the relations of cooperation in a broad sphere
into the 21st century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
