<HEADLINE> Roundup: Sino-Portuguese Friendly Cooperation Promotes Macao Stable Transition (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Macao has seen another year of
stable transition in 1997 as China and Portugal maintain friendly
relations of cooperation on the question of Macao.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of both China and Portugal exchanged visits regularly
in 1997, and bilateral relations have been further expanded in the
political, economic, cultural, scientific and technological
fields.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice Premier and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen visited
Portugal in January, stressing that the Chinese Government pays
great attention to the development of a stable long-term friendly
relations of cooperation with Portugal. Later, China's State
Councilor Song Jian and Li Ruihuan, chairman of the National
Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference (CPPCC), also visited Portugal.
</P>
<P>
In return, Portuguese President Jorge Sampaio became the first
foreign head of state to visit China after Deng Xiaoping passed
away in February. While meeting with Sampaio, Chinese President
Jiang Zemin pointed out that the Portuguese president's visit
injected new vigor to the development of bilateral relations and
cooperation on the question of Macao.
</P>
<P>
Observers in Macao are of the view that the constant contacts
and exchanges of view between leaders of the two countries help
increase mutual understanding and trust, thus contributing to
further growth of the ties between the two countries, and
especially, in the settlement of the Macao issue.
</P>
<P>
Both China and Portugal held that it conforms to the common
interests of the two sides to strive for a smooth handover of
power and to keep Macao stable and growing economically. Good
cooperation in Macao helps promote good relations, they said.
</P>
</TEXT>
