<HEADLINE> Uganda Sets Limit for Companies to Go Public </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Uganda Security Exchange
(USE) has set the limit of 150 million Uganda Shillings (some
150,000 U.S. dollars) for a company which intends to be listed on
the stock exchange.
</P>
<P>
With trade at the exchange kicking off early in January, the
USE requires small companies to solicit at least 150 million
Uganda Shillings, USE chairman Onegi Obel disclosed to The
Monitor newspaper.
</P>
<P>
With the licensing of 12 brokerages and dealing firms, and two
investment advisers now in place, private companies opting to
solicit capital can contract merchant banks, he added.
</P>
<P>
A company which intends to go public must produce prospectus
to Capital Markets Authority (CMA) for a scrutiny, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
According to CMA, a company shall be expected to raise a given
amount at primary solicitation before it is allowed to go to the
market for the secondary amount.
</P>
<P>
For a commercial bank, it is the time to adjust and give
related services or be out of the market, said an official from
Nile Bank, the leading underwriter for east Africa development
bank loans for bonds worth 10 billion Uganda Shillings (some 10
million U.S. dollars), which excited many firms here opting to be
listed on stock exchange.
</P>
<P>
"Demand and supply shall govern trade, and borrowers shall be
doing that at about nil rate or according to the market, which is
a good enough deal," The Monitor quoted a CMA source as saying.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
