<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Urged to Take Initiative in Iran-US Dialog </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 17 (Xinhua) -- An influential Iranian daily
today called on U.S. President Bill Clinton to make the first move
to show sincerity about dialogs between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
If Clinton must have a dialog with Iran, he should take the
initiative to indicate Washington's sincerity and seriousness,
said the pro-government newspaper Kayhan International in an
editorial.
</P>
<P>
To mean what he has said, Clinton should accept all of Tehran's
repeated demands, including release of Iranian assets frozen in
the United States, the daily said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton Monday expressed his welcome to the remarks made by
his Iranian counterpart Mohammad Khatami Sunday on Iran's
willingness to hold dialogs with the American people.
</P>
<P>
"I would like nothing better than to have a dialog with Iran as
long as we can have an honest discussion of all the relevant
issues," Clinton told the press.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian daily said that only time will prove how far
Clinton will go for his enthusiasm to have a dialog with Iran.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the daily expressed doubts about Washington's
sincerity since Clinton reiterates his "anti-Iran rhetoric" that
Tehran is sponsoring terrorism, seeking to sabotage the Middle
East peace process and developing weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
The widely circulated paper said that Khatami's statement is
nothing new, but a repeat of Iran's policies adopted since the
Islamic Revolution in 1979.
</P>
<P>
Iran has repeatedly asserted that it does not entertain any
negative sentiments toward the people of any country, including
the people of the United States, the daily said.
</P>
<P>
The "only country at present," which is not recognized by Iran,
is Israel "because it has been established in Palestine by
usurping the natural and bona fide rights of the people of
Palestine," the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Any country, other than Israel, which respects mutual rights
and acts within the international conventions, can have normal
relations with Iran, it continued.
</P>
<P>
The United States severed its diplomatic relations with Iran in
1980 after Iranian students took over the American embassy in
Tehran and held the embassy staff in hostage.
</P>
<P>
It imposed an economic sanction on Iran in 1995 and has been
pressuring its allies to isolate the oil-rich Gulf country.
</P>
</TEXT>
