<HEADLINE> Manila to Negotiate With IMF for Standby Facility </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 17 (Xinhua) -- President Fidel Ramos confirmed
Wednesday that the Philippines and the International Monetary Fund
(IMF) will start negotiations in January for a standby fund
facility, which will serve as a buffer after the country exits
from IMF supervision.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations will commence in "the first week of January,"
the president said at a weekly press conference held in the
Presidential Palace.
</P>
<P>
However, he added that the standby fund is not a "bailout"
package inasmuch as the Philippines continues to show strong
economic fundamentals despite the current financial storm sweeping
much of Asia.
</P>
<P>
"It is not a bailout because we are not among those considered
to be bailed out," he said. "We are helping ourselves and we are
taking not only long-range steps but also short-term measures."
</P>
<P>
The standby facility is a sort of credit line or available
funds, plus the presence of an IMF team in Manila to monitor the
country's economic and financial performance, he said.
</P>
<P>
He further explained that the standby facility is "different
from the regular program" which the country has been undertaking
because the country can refuse the facility if it is not needed.
</P>
<P>
President Ramos said the presence of an IMF team is also "not a
problem" even after his country graduates from the IMF at the end
of the year as has been scheduled.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
