<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Water Quality of Huaihe River Improved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Water quality of the Huaihe
River, one of China's longest, is showing signs of improvement,
thanks to a massive pollution control campaign to clean up the river
water.
</P>
<P>
Latest sample checks indicate the organisms in industrial waste
water discharged into the river have reduced by 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of factories, the pollutants of the river, are working
round-the-clock to meet the deadline of December 31 for installing
waste water treatment facilities.
</P>
<P>
Those that fail to meet the deadline set by the central
environmental protection authorities will face production
suspension or close-down.
</P>
<P>
"The clean-up drive proceeds smoothly and I'm pretty confident
that we will attain the goal of cleaning the Huaihe River by the year
2000," said Qu Geping, chairman of the Environment and Resources
Committee under the National People's Congress, the country's
highest legislative body.
</P>
<P>
Qu, who is heading a NPC working group on an inspection tour
along the river, said the central government is determined to
clean up the river "for people's health and the sustained
development of the regional economy".
</P>
<P>
He said China has promulgated many laws and regulations on
environmental protection. "We should enhance the law
enforcement and supervision."
</P>
<P>
Local sources revealed more than 100 factory managers in
Henan Province, where the river originates, have been detained
on charges of pollution.
</P>
<P>
Qu stressed the importance to apply new and high
technology in environmental protection. "The success of cleaning
up the Huaihe River partly lies in whether we can achieve
technical breakthroughs," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Huaihe River, along which 150 million people live, spans
Henan, Anhui, Jiangsu and Shandong provinces, the country's major
grain and energy base.
</P>
<P>
As China's biggest environmental protection project, the Huaihe
River clean-up will offer experiences for other pollution control
projects in the country, noted Qu, former director of the National
Environmental Protection Agency.
</P>
<P>
He said industrial projects which cause serious pollution
should not be built along rivers and in areas which lack
environmental protection technology.
</P>
<P>
The central government is considering closing up more small
factories that pollute the environment seriously, Qu
revealed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
