<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Revive National Parks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's National Parks
Services (NPS) has disclosed plans to improve the infrastructure
facilities in the country's six national parks.
</P>
<P>
Lawan Bukar Marguba, executive director of the NPS was quoted
by the daily Champion newspaper as saying that NPS will spend
about 209 million Naira (about 2.7 million U.S. Dollars) to
connect the Yankari National Park with the National Power Grid.
</P>
<P>
New administrative blocks will be completed in the Old Oyo and
the Gashaka Gumpti national parks, the official said.
</P>
<P>
According to him, Nigeria's most famous national park Yankari
received about 97,329 tourists from 1991 to 1996. The Kainji Lake
National Park was visited by 6,348 people from 1994 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Gashaka Gumpti National Park recorded 1,390 visitors in
the last two years while the Cross River National Park saw 300
visitors in the same period.
</P>
<P>
There are no figures for the Old Oyo and the Chad Basin
national parks. 
</P>
