<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea's Presidential Race Seen Neck-and-Neck Contest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 17 (Xinhua) -- With one day left before South
Korean voters go to polls to elect a man who will lead them to
overcome a serious financial crisis ailing the country, the
presidential race is viewed as a neck-and-neck competition among
the contenders.
</P>
<P>
The three-party competition is seen to be dominated by the duel
between Lee Hoi-chang of the Grand National Party and Kim Dae-jung
of the National Congress for New Politics because Rhee In-je of
the New Party by the People remains distant from the two.
</P>
<P>
Polls conducted last month showed that Kim, a veteran
opposition leader in the past decades, was leading with a marginal
advantage over Lee and Rhee.
</P>
<P>
However, some analysts say the contest is far from giving a
prediction as undecided voters, estimated to account for 20
percent of the total voter turnout, will have a decisive impact on
the outcome of the country's 15th presidential election.
</P>
<P>
The undecided voters are classified into two groups. Those in
the first group may ultimately cast votes for either Lee Hoi-chang
or Rhee In-je as most of them are associated with the governing
party although Lee and Rhee, former members of the ruling party,
have denied any ties with President Kim Young-sam. The other group
of the undecided voters may vote either for Lee or for Kim.
</P>
<P>
Now, the three parties have been intensively campaigning in
populous Seoul and its neighboring areas, which are vital
constituencies with more than 45 percent out of the nation's 32.3
million voters.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some analysts point out that it is the people from
the Kyongsang region with 27 percent of voters, a traditional base
of the ruling party, rather than the undecided voters, who would
have a definite influence on the election.
</P>
<P>
A split in the region would be of crucial benefit to Kim
Dae-jung, who reportedly has a majority in the Cholla areas and
enjoys a stable support of about 35 percent across the country.
</P>
<P>
Unless Lee secures more than 60 percent of the eligible voters
in the Kyongsang region, he might not reverse the result of last
month's polls to beat Kim's fourth bid for the presidency, say the
analysts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
