<HEADLINE> Boeing to Cut workforce Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Boeing, the world's
largest aircraft manufacturer, said today it plans to cut its
workforce by about 12,000 next year, according to reports from the
company.
</P>
<P>
The goal, said Boeing President Harry Stonecipher, is for the
company to be back on track in the second half of 1998 and then to
start cutting back further on extra people.
</P>
<P>
Boeing chairman Phil Condit also said there may be some
layoffs, but the company hopes to reduce its employment through
attrition.
</P>
<P>
The company has a workforce of 235,000 and normally loses some
11,500 a year through retirements and voluntary resignations.
</P>
<P>
Right now, however, the company is struggling to get jetliners
out the hangar door, paying large amounts of overtime and asking
employees to work through the Christmas holidays.
</P>
<P>
The company said it is on schedule to meet its target of
producing a total of 375 to 385 planes this year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Boeing commercial airplane group president Ron
Woodard said the company expects to deliver 550 planes in 1998 and
keep the same level in 1999.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, he added, the company will be able to reduce
staff as it tapers its aggressive program of developing new
airplanes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
