<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Urges ASEAN to Crack Down Illegal Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government on
Wednesday urged the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN)
to take a tougher stance against illegal drug trafficking in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Interior and Local Governments Secretary Robert Barbers said in
a statement that ASEAN countries must exert all efforts to combat
and prevent illicit cultivation, production, distribution and
abuse of narcotic drugs and psychotropic substances.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN countries, he said, must not only focus on preventive
drug education, treatment and rehabilitation, law enforcement and
research to stem the tide of illicit drug trafficking in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Barbers' statement came on the eve of the three-day first ASEAN
Conference on Transnational Crimes to be held here, which will be
attended by interior and home affairs ministers of ASEAN member
countries.
</P>
<P>
"As part of our cooperative and collaborative efforts against
drug trafficking, ASEAN member countries must put more teeth to
the campaign by preventing and controlling the illegal production,
distribution and trafficking of narcotic drugs and psychotropic
substances," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Barbers said the ministers attending the conference may study
or even adopt the memorandum of agreement forged by the
Philippines and the Lao People's Democratic Republic last October
which expanded the two countries' cooperation against illicit drug
trafficking.
</P>
<P>
The two countries vowed in the memo to take measures to prevent
the production, distribution and trafficking of narcotic drugs and
psychotropic substances as well as the diversion of precursors and
essential chemicals that may be used in the manufacture of the
banned substances.
</P>
<P>
Barbers said the memo may serve as a model for ASEAN since it
addresses the problem of illegal drugs and trafficking from its
very core which is the production and manufacture of banned
substances.
</P>
<P>
He expressed optimism that the conference will enhance
cooperation among ASEAN members against transnational crimes,
particularly drug trafficking, terrorism, money laundering and
firearms smuggling.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar,
Singapore, Thailand, Vietnam and the Philippines.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
