<HEADLINE> Chinese Calligrapher Copying Literary Classic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, December 17 (Xinhua) -- A calligrapher in north
China's Shanxi Province has by now copied more than half of the
Dream of Red Mansions, one of the most famous Chinese literary
classics, by using a writing brush.
</P>
<P>
The 45-year-old man, Wen Qingxiu, plans to finish the rest of
the book, which has nearly one million characters, within four years.
</P>
<P>
Wen, who is a member of the Provincial Calligraphers'
Association, has written using Xiaokai, regular script in small
characters, on quality paper specially-made for the purpose.
</P>
<P>
Wen makes only about 300 yuan (about 36 US dollars) monthly and
has already spent 1,000 yuan (120 US dollars) on brushes, ink,
inkstones and paper. 
