<HEADLINE> India Opens Up Non-Banking Financial Services to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 17 (Xinhua) -- India has opened up its
non-banking financial services (NBFS) including stock-brokering to
foreign companies as part of a revised offer made to the World
Trade Organization (WTO), official sources said here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The WTO recently signed an accord on trade in financial
services in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
The Indian government is expected to allow up to 51 percent
foreign equity in five areas of NBFS, while in stock-brokering it
would be 49 percent. The five areas are financial consultancy,
factoring, leasing, venture capital and merchant banking.
</P>
<P>
India has agreed to open 12 branches of foreign banks every
year on the most favored nation basis. In 1995, India only allowed
eight branches of foreign banks to operate in the country.
</P>
<P>
India's new offer was conditional as the total share of foreign
banks could not exceed 15 percent of the total bank branches in
India.  
</P>
