<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese President Back in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
returned to Beijing by special plane this afternoon after
attending the informal summit meeting between China and the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Jiang, who left Beijing for Kuala Lumpur December 14 as guest
of Dr. Mahathir Mohammed, rotating chairman of ASEAN and prime
minister of Malaysia, had also attended the informal summit
meeting between ASEAN and China, Japan and the Republic of Korea.
</P>
<P>
Greeting Jiang today at the Great Hall of the People were
Premier Li Peng, Standing Committee Chairman Qiao Shi of the
National People's Congress, Vice-President Rong Yiren,
Vice-Chairman Zhang Wannian of the Central Military Commission,
State Councillor and Secretary-General of the State Council Luo
Gan, Vice-Chairwoman Qian Zhengying of the National Committee of
the Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference.
</P>
<P>
Jiang's entourage, including his wife Wang Yeping, Vice-Premier
and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen, special assistants Zeng Qinghong
and Teng Wensheng, were also back here aboard the same plane.
</P>
<P>
Minister Wu Yi of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation,
Director Liu Huaqiu of the Foreign Affairs Office of the State
Council, and diplomatic envoys of the Malaysian and Philippine
embassies in Beijing also went to the great hall to greet Jiang.
</P>
<P>
Local press held that to hold these summits on the occasion of
the 30th anniversary of the founding of ASEAN would not only
benefit the economic growth of east Asian nations and advance
their mutually beneficial cooperation, but also help intensify the
friendly cooperative links between China and ASEAN.
</P>
<P>
These links would serve to have an important and far-reaching
impact on the 21st century's development of east Asia and of the
China-ASEAN good-neighborly partnership of mutual trust, they said.
</P>
<P>
During the informal summit at the turn of this century, Jiang
and east Asian leaders expressed their optimism on the region's
development in the 21st century, and exchanged views on
strengthening cooperation between east Asian nations in regional
and international affairs before reaching an extensive consensus.
</P>
<P>
At this first ever top-level gathering between Jiang and the
ASEAN leaders, a joint statement had been signed as an important
fruit, which not only determined the principle to guide bilateral
relations, but also decided that the common goal in their policies
is to establish a good-neighborly partnership of mutual trust in
the forthcoming century, marking a new stage in China-ASEAN
relations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
