<HEADLINE> China Lays Out Principles for State Enterprise Reform (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, December 17 (Xinhua) -- China's State Economic and
Trade Commission described the principles behind its reform of
large and medium-sized state-owned enterprises for the next three
years at an annual economic and trade conference which ended here
in Chengdu today.
</P>
<P>
Wang Zhongyu, minister of the commission, told the three-day
conference that the problems have been made much clearer and that
reform guidelines and principles have taken shape after years of
reform efforts.
</P>
<P>
The reforms, whose goal is to set up a modern enterprise system
with these enterprises, are a cornerstone of China's economic
reform, he said.
</P>
<P>
The state has taken concrete measures like strategically
regrouping state enterprises, taking care of the reforms of big
state enterprises and letting small ones take care of the reform
of themselves, encouraging mergers, standardizing bankruptcies,
moving redundant workers to other jobs, and developing
re-employment programs.
</P>
<P>
All measures have been approved by China's highest
decision-making body and efforts have been made to provide a
foundation for accelerated reforms in the next three years, he
said, adding that the successful macro-economic readjustment
measures of the Chinese government have meant a soft-landing for
the Chinese economy.
</P>
<P>
The relatively good supply of energy, raw materials, and
produce, the improved transport conditions, the better fiscal
situation, and the more open macro-economic environment all
provide solid guarantees for future reforms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971217.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's State Enterprise Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A number of large, cost-efficient and strong state enterprises
and enterprise groups will emerge from the competitive market to
sustain China's future economic development, and continue the
enterprise reform, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Another thing that favors state enterprise reforms is the fact
that people have seen the difference of markets, competition, and
risk-prevention after years of reforms and can stand the pressure
better and can better understand, support, and participate in the
process," he said.
</P>
<P>
The state enterprise reforms in 1998 will focus on establishing
a mechanism whereby strong entities win out and weak ones fail,
and the central government will allocate 40 billion yuan, 10
billion yuan more than this year, for large and medium-sized state
enterprises to write off non-performing and bad loans.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the state plans to raise 100 billion yuan by
issuing stocks to back up reforms, with key state enterprises the
first to do this, and companies are encouraged to take over
companies that still have difficulties, he said, and the
government will continue to encourage the involvement of foreign
capital in state enterprises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
