<DOCNO> XIE19971217.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WFP Project Launched in Impoverished NW Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, December 17 (Xinhua) -- A comprehensive agricultural
project funded by the World Food Program of the United Nations has
been launched in three impoverished counties in Qinghai Province,
which is landlocked in northwest China.
</P>
<P>
Under the project, three reservoirs will be built in the
region, with a combined capacity of 7.95 million cu.m. water; a
145 km-long water channel dug; 3,454 ha. of farmland irrigated.
</P>
<P>
Also included in the project are some drinking water and road
building projects. In addition, 25,000 illiterates in the area
will receive preliminary education; 170,000 local people will
receive technical training and 2,000 drop-outs will resume
schooling.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, a WFP delegation has made an inspection tour
of China's northwestern region, where are densely populated by
ethnic minority people. The said project in Qinghai will use a WFP
preferential loan of five million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The project will benefit 262,300 people in Ping'an, Xunhua and
Hualong counties, with 77 percent of them being ethnic minority
people. After it is completed, the per-capita annual income in the
three counties will exceed 860 yuan and the local people will get
rid of poverty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
