<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Desert Control Project in Tibet Fruitful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, December 17 (Xinhua) -- A three-year desert harnessing
project in the Tibet Autonomous Region, southwest China, has
produced fruitful results.
</P>
<P>
In the pilot zone with an area of 1,600 mu (106 hectares),
the greenery coverage rate has been increased from the original
10-30 percent to the current 30-70 percent.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, experts helped the area to introduce varieties of
cold-resistant watermelon. As a result, per mu (0.066 hectares)
output of the melon reached 3,000 kilograms.
</P>
<P>
Tibet has a combined desert area of 210,000 square kilometers,
the third largest in the country.
</P>
<P>
Xinhua was told that strawberry, tomato, maize and wheat have
also been successfully planted in the project area. Per mu (0.066
hectares) output of maize and wheat reached 400 kilograms and 450
kilograms respectively this year.
</P>
<P>
So far, 12,000 local residents have benefited from the
project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
