<HEADLINE> More American Tourists Expected in Asia Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 16 (Xinhua) -- More Americans, taking
advantage of the exchange rate, are looking to travelling to Asia
next year, according to the American Society of Travel Agents
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Asian destinations have become increasingly hot in the past 18
months as a result of plummeting Asian currencies and tourism
promotion by the governments, said the society.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, the Thai baht has declined 46 percent against
the U.S. dollar, while the South Korean won, 45 percent and both
the Philippines peso and the Malaysian ringgit, 36 percent.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, baby boomers have now reached an age when
they have the money and inclination to explore new places instead
of traditional destinations.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the United Airlines, Northwest Airlines and other
carriers flying between the U.S. and Asia, especially South Korea,
Malaysia, Thailand and the Philippines, expect higher profits next
year, the society added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
