<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, December 17 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton said Tuesday that he
would announce his plan in the next few days on whether to keep
U.S. troops in Bosnia beyond June, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a year-end press conference, Clinton said he will
announce the plan before he flies to Bosnia on Sunday to visit
U.S. troops stationed there. The Clinton administration has been
caught between pressure from many Congressmen who want a timely
pullout and from Europeans who say the peace mission in Bosnia
will collapse if the Americans leave. (Clinton-Bosnia Plan)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto announced
Wednesday a plan to implement special tax cuts of two trillion yen
(about 15.7 billion dollars) in the fiscal 1997 supplementary
budget to stimulate the sagging economy.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at an emergency press conference, Hashimoto said that
the step is designed to prevent the economic problem "originated
in Japan from causing global depression." The government will
issue deficit-covering bonds to finance the tax cuts, which will
be implemented only for one year, he added. (Japan-Tax Cut)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton said Tuesday that the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) would hold a summit in
Washington in the spring of 1999 to welcome Poland, Hungary and
the Czech Republic into the alliance.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a year-end press conference, Clinton said, "the
entry of Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic into the alliance
will make America safer, NATO stronger, and Europe more stable and
united." "The United States has led the way in transforming our
alliance; now we should be among the first to vote yes for NATO's
historic engagement," he added. (US-NATO-New Members)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KIEV -- Ukraine has destroyed 68 SS-19 intercontinental
ballistic missiles (ICBMs) and 107 ICBM launchers, a senior
Ukrainian military official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news briefing, Nikolai Goncharenko, director of
the inspection center of the armed forces, said Ukraine plans to
further destroy 62 such missiles and 20 launching devices for
SS-24 ICBMs, the Ukrainian Interfax News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Under a joint statement signed by Russia, the United States and
Ukraine in 1991, Ukraine should destroy all the 180 SS-19 and 46
SS-24 missiles deployed within its territory by the former Soviet
Union, said the report. (Ukraine-Missiles Destruction) 
</P>
</TEXT>
