<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over 90 Die of Cholera in Zanzibar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The death toll of
cholera victims in Zanzibar has exceeded 90, reports reaching
here today said.
</P>
<P>
However, Zanzibar has reported a steady decline in the number
of patients and deaths in the last 24 hours. Only one was
reported yesterday morning, indicating an improvement of the
situation.
</P>
<P>
Zanzibar's Health Minister Said Bakari Jecha told reporters
that by Tuesday, 79 people had died in several health centers in
Zanzibar town while 12 had died at home.
</P>
<P>
Jecha said the epidemic is an east African affair, having
stretched from Somalia in the north to Mozambique in the south.
He said a regional conference to deliberate on the epidemic will
soon ben held in Nairobi, capital of Kenya.
</P>
<P>
A study, done by the Ministry for Health, has revealed that
the main source of the epidemic was the lack of toilets and waste
disposal pits.
</P>
<P>
The minister named some of the most affected areas as
Makadara, Mwembemakumbi, Mwembeladu and Migombani where most
households do not have latrines. The government will conduct a
house to house inspection to determine which family does not have
a latrine.
</P>
<P>
He said the government has acquired 100 tons of medicine from
businessmen and international organizations, include antibiotics
and drip fluids, which are enough to cope the current situation.
Meanwhile, the government has banned all private hospitals to
treat cholera patients.
</P>
<P>
Zanzibar President Salmin Amour has sent a message of
condolences to relatives and friends of people who have been
killed in the outbreak of cholera during the past two weeks in
the Indian isles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
