<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The following are business
briefs from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- European Airbus Company is trying to persuade
Israel's national carrier El Al to buy its medium-range aircraft,
the Jerusalem Post daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
Airbus representative in Israel Haim Hacham told the daily that
Airbus is considering increasing its purchase of Israeli equipment
as a package deal with El Al.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel increases spending on schooling by 3 to 4
percent per capita each year from 1992 to 1996, the daily said
today.
</P>
<P>
Israel's annual school expenditures reaches 8.9 percent of its
gross domestic product, 2.7 percentage points more than the
average of the other countries of the Organization for Economic
Cooperation and Development.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's industrial exports amounted to 1.65
billion U.S. dollars last November, a 7.2 percent increase over
the same period a year ago, a report on the newspaper said Monday.
</P>
<P>
While the high-tech sector, textile and clothing enterprises
witnessed an increase in export, some other traditional industries
registered a decrease.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey's Petroleum Office will take measures to
regulate the unregistered oil trade along the Turkish-Iraqi
border, local newspapers reported today.
</P>
<P>
Mehmet Gultekin, director general of the office, said that this
move is aimed at reducing Turkey's economic losses estimated at
200 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- Two agreements were signed Monday between the
International Fund for Agricultural Development (IFAD) and the
Yemeni government.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreements, the IFAD will offer Yemen two loans of 24
million U.S. dollars to finance two projects, which will help
improve the living conditions of 54,800 rural families.
</P>
<P>
IFAD has invested some 134 million dollars in 14 projects in
the domains of rural and agricultural development and the
eradication of poverty in Yemen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
