<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 09:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Iranian Women Favor Family Planning Programs: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 17 (Xinhua) -- A research shows that 69
percent of married Iranian women favor family planning programs
in the country, local newspaper Iran Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
The research which was conducted in a four-year span on 8,309
married women aged under 49, shows that 91.8 percent of married
Iranian women agree with family planning programs.
</P>
<P>
About 5.2 percent urban women and 13.5 percent rural women
oppose family planning methods, the research indicated, advising
the government to offer constant training to encourage men to
participate in family planning.
</P>
<P>
The research noted that birth control systems would improve
the living conditions at a macro level and increase hope for a
better life.
</P>
<P>
Small families will find the way to address their needs
and choose a proper way of life while expanded families will
always face a huge spectrum of unmet needs, the newspaper
said.
</P>
<P>
Iran started a policy of family planning programs at the
beginning of the 1990s after the country's population growth rate
boomed up over 3 percent, as a result of birth encouragement
during the Iran-Iraq war from 1980 to 1988.
</P>
<P>
Iran claimed that its population growth rate has dropped down
to 1.6 percent, but some specialists believe it to be around
1.8-2.0 percent.
</P>
<P>
A newspaper warned earlier this year that the population
growth rate in Tehran province around the country's capital
city of Tehran was as high as 5.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
It said that the country, Tehran province in particular,
would face a serious population explosion in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Iran's population was reported in contradictory ways.
U.N. population specialists predicted it at 65 million while the
Iranian government announced that it is less than 60 million at
present. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971217.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 25 Anniversary of Sino-Australian Ties Marked </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SYDNEY, Australia, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Australia will
launch a program of technical cooperation assistance to China as
an effort to cement the Australian-Chinese cooperation, said
Australian Prime Minister John Howard here today.
</P>
<P>
He made the announcement at a reception to mark the 25th
anniversary of the establishment of diplomatic relations between
China and Australia.
</P>
<P>
"It is an appropriate occasion to announce that the Australian
government has agreed with China on a program designed to make
available Australian expertise in public sector management," he
said. "The program will begin next year and will be worth up to 20
million Australian dollars over four years."
</P>
<P>
He said that the program will provide for Chinese governmental
agencies to draw on the technical expertise of a range of
Australian counterpart agencies and institutions.
</P>
<P>
"Wherever Australian approaches are relevant for China, these
will be transferred or adapted as required," Howard added.
</P>
<P>
Li Ruihuan, chairman of the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference (CPPCC) National Committee, attended the
reception.
</P>
<P>
Li expressed his appreciation for the decision, saying that the
program will have a positive impact on the growth of the bilateral
ties.
</P>
<P>
When recalling the development of Sino-Australian relations in
the past 25 years, Li said that thanks to the concerted efforts of
the two countries, encouraging achievements have been scored in
the friendship and cooperation in various fields.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the two countries have been in constant contact with
each other, and steady progress has been made in economic ties and
trade, Li said, adding that the bilateral educational, cultural
and other exchanges have been expanding.
</P>
<P>
He observed that the two sides have enjoyed sound consultations
and cooperation on many major international and regional issues.
The Australian government has always stuck to the "One China"
policy, listed China-Australian relationship as one of its major
important bilateral ties, and supported China's accession to the
World Trade Organization, he added.
</P>
<P>
Li noted that China and Australia share common interests and
common responsibility in safeguarding world peace and promoting
stability and development in the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
Since Australia is an economically developed country in South
Pacific while China is the world's largest developing country, the
two economies are highly complementary, which promises great
potentials and a broad prospect for mutually beneficial
cooperation, Li said.
</P>
<P>
"It can be said that China needs Australia and vice versa," Li
pointed out. "I am convinced that by celebrating the 25th
anniversary of the establishment of diplomatic relations, our
bilateral ties will be promoted to a new phase of development and
a more brilliant chapter will be opened in the coming new
century."
</P>
<P>
Howard said that the Australian-Chinese relationship is built
very firmly under the two pillars of common interests and mutual
respect.
</P>
<P>
Although the two countries are very different societies with
very different histories and political systems, the bilateral
relations have always been "at their very best", he added.
</P>
<P>
Australia and China are "very natural partners" in economic
cooperation, he said, adding "the common participation of the two
countries in the International Monetary Fund's assistance packages
for both Indonesia and Thailand has underlined the character of
our partnership in the Asia-Pacific region."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971217.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
