<HEADLINE> Uganda, Italy Sign Trade Pacts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Uganda and Italy have signed
agreements on trade and investment, "The Monitor" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Martin Aliker, Ugandan state minister for foreign affairs in
charge of international affairs, and Rino Serri, Italian vice
minister for foreign affairs in charge of Africa and development
cooperation, last week signed an agreement on protecting Italian
investment in Uganda and a memorandum of expanding trade between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The agreements were signed on December 12 when Aliker visited
Italy, heading a 10-man delegation, Luigi Scotto, the first
secretary and deputy head of Italian mission accredited in
Uganda, Rwanda and Burundi, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Italy is to send a mission to Uganda next year to study the
possibility of granting Uganda a soft loan for infrastructure
development including roads, telecommunication and energy, and to
boost small and medium scale enterprises, Scotto said.
</P>
<P>
The main commodities exported from Uganda to Italy are coffee
and cotton, and main commodities imported from Italy to Uganda
are motor vehicles, tractors and spares.
</P>
<P>
The trade between the two countries has increased from 10
million U.S. Dollars in 1991/1992 financial year to 20 million
U.S. Dollars in 1994/1995 financial year, the paper said in its
report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
