<HEADLINE> Kenyan Govt Fails to End Nurses'Strike by Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Hopes of resolving the
nurses' strike across Kenya have been dashed after talks between
governmental officials and representatives of the striking nurses
broke up in discord Tuesday, local reports said today.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, under the chairmanship of Chief Nursing Officer
Margaret Ngure, lasted about two hours and ended in a deadlock
when the government said it could only make measures to solve the
crisis after the December 29 general elections.
</P>
<P>
In response, the National All Cadres Nurses Steering Committee
vowed to intensify the strike and called for a demonstration
march in downtown Nairobi today, the 20th day of the strike.
</P>
<P>
The nurses were demanding up to 500-percent pay hike but the
government only agreed a 20-percent increase, saying there is no
money to pay nurses higher salaries under the current economic
situation.
</P>
<P>
But the nurses accused governmental officials of lacking
seriousness in solving their problems because "senior government
officials were busy with the political campaigns."
</P>
<P>
"We have been too lenient in asking for what is our right but
now we have no option other than applying the language which the
government best understands -- demonstrations!" said a strike
leader Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Most public hospitals have been crippled around the country
with patients unattended since the strike were launched on
November 28. 
</P>
