<HEADLINE> High Infant Death, Malnutrition Plague Nepal: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Nepali Prime Minister Surya
Bahadur Thapa said here today that despite the government's
efforts to provide for basic health and nutritional needs of
children, the twin problems of high infant death and malnutrition
continue to plague the country.
</P>
<P>
"Most notable problems are the protein-energy malnutrition in
young children and iron deficiency causing anemia in women," said
the prime minister while addressing a ceremony held by the United
Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF) to release a report called the
State of the World's Children 1998.
</P>
<P>
To improve the situation, the Nepali government has constituted
a very high-level National Women and Children Development Council
for the protection and promotion of the causes of children and
women, he said.
</P>
<P>
And the government has initiated programs for distributing
Vitamin A supplements twice a year to all children under the age
of five and promoting iodization of salt and breast feeding, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Children account for 16 percent of Nepal's total population of
21.6 million, and half of them are malnourished and half stunted,
said the UNICEF report.
</P>
<P>
The report which focuses on the issue of nutrition identifies
protein-energy malnutrition, Vitamin A deficiency, iodine
deficiency disorders, iron deficiency anemia and zinc deficiency
as the main nutritional problems in Nepal.
</P>
<P>
A report released on the occasion by the Nepali government said
that four national studies over the last 20 years reported on the
level of malnutrition in young Nepalese children and there is
little evidence of improvement.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
