<DOCNO> XIE19971217.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 08:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Cabinet Holds Third Session on Pullback, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Cabinet held its
third session this morning to deliberate the further redeployment
and guidelines on permanent talks with the Palestinians, following
Tuesday's session which turned into a shouting game.
</P>
<P>
Today's meeting was the last session held before the Thursday
meeting between Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and
United States Secretary of State Madeleine Albright in Paris.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was held under the shadow of a deepening inner rift
within the government over drawing a final map on the planned
redeployment in the West Bank and the final-status talks with the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA). No final decision was
expected until mid-January.
</P>
<P>
Local media reported today that Tuesday's session turned into
a shouting game between Netanyahu and the hawkish National
Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon, who accused the prime
minister of sacrificing Israeli security interests for the
pullback plan.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu reportedly shouted back at Sharon: "Don't wave your
finger at me."
</P>
<P>
Sharon indicated that he would no longer support the
government if his proposal for the further pullback and
final-status talks is not accepted by the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Sharon proposed creating one 10-15 kilometers security zone
east of the Green Line to divide Israel and the Palestinian
self-rule areas, and another 20-kilometer-zone along the Jordan
Valley. He also called for retaining control over the water
sources and all Jewish settlements in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Under Sharon's proposal, Israel will maintain control over 70
percent of the West Bank in the final settlement. His plan
was supported by Science Minister Michael Eitan, Agriculture
Minister Rafael Eitan, Industry and Trade Minister Natan
Sharansky, and Transportation Minister Yitzhak Levy.
</P>
<P>
But Netanyahu, together with Foreign Minister David Levy, was
reported to favor the plan proposed by Defense Minister Yitzhak
Mordechai, who recommended narrowing the width of the two planned
security zones along the Green Line and Jordan Valley to three to
six kilometers and seven to 10 kilometers respectively. Under
Mordechai's proposal, Israel will retain control over 50-55
percent of the territories in the final settlement.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai and Levy insisted that Israel's holding on to less
territories would help promote the chance of advancing the peace
process. Both of them favored earlier withdrawal in order to win
diplomatic points for Israel to get out of the international
isolation caused by the stalemate in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Levy told Netanyahu if he was not serious in carrying out
the redeployment, he would turn down Netanyahu's invitation to
travel together to Paris to meet Albright.
</P>
<P>
The Prime Minister's Office said Tuesday that Netanyahu would
only update Albright on the latest Israeli internal consultations
when they meet in Paris, without giving a specific percentage
of the second redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reported that Netanyahu would also present
Albright a 12-page report on what is called the PNA's
antisemitism and incitement against Israel in violation of the
signed agreements.
</P>
<P>
The radio said Netanyahu is gaining understanding from the
United States that he needs more time to delay the second
redeployment until mid-January after winning the Knesset
(Parliament) approval of the 1998 Budget, which is facing strong
opposition from both the ruling and opposition camps due to
massive budgetary cuts.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu has to rely on the rightwing parties' support to
get the budget through the Knesset at the end of the month,
otherwise his government will fall. If he pushes hard now for
the approval of the controversial redeployment, the rightists will
take advantage of the budget vote to pressure Netanyahu to
cancel it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971217.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
