<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Economy Growth Rate Expected to Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's gross domestic
product (GDP) is forecast to grow 3.6 percent this year, down
from 4.6 percent last year and 4.8 percent in 1995, local reports
said today.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank of Kenya (CBK) estimated that average annual
inflation stood at 8.5 percent in 1997 from 9.0 percent last year
and annualized month-on-month inflation at 7.3 percent from 10.8
percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Foreign reserves in the eastern African country was expected
to rise slightly to 1.315 billion U.S. Dollars from 1.299 billion
last year, according to the bank's monthly report for December.
</P>
<P>
Some 736 million Dollars, or three months of imports cover,
were official reserves, representing a decline from 855 million
Dollars or 3.6 months imports in official reserves last year.
</P>
<P>
From January to October, tourism incomes dropped by 21 million
Dollars to 428 million Dollars. Tourism is the country's biggest
foreign currency earner.
</P>
<P>
"The decline in tourism earnings was partly due to the ethnic
unrest in major tourist resort areas which scared away potential
tourists and partly due to intense competition from other tourist
destinations," the bank said.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's economy also suffered a shock in July when the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) halted a key aid package worth
205 million Dollars, causing an outflow of investors from the
equity and money markets.
</P>
<P>
The central bank noted the IMF suspension was responsible for
a fall in official long-term capital inflows by 163 million
Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Debt service in the country currently makes up 21.5 percent of
exports of goods and services with external debt totaling 6.3
billion Dollars, official statistics showed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
