</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971217.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Revenue Up 23 Percent For 11-Month Period </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 17 (Xinhua) -- China's fiscal condition
continued to improve in the first 11 months of this year, with
revenues outstripping expenditures by 6.8 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Finance Liu Zhongli told a national financial
meeting today that and both revenues and expenditures of central
and local budgets will exceed budgeted figures, while the deficit
in the central budget will be held within the budgeted figure of
57 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
China's national revenues grew 23.2 percent year-on-year in the
first 11 months, compared with a rise of 16.4 percent for
expenditures during the period, Liu said, explaining that growth
of taxes slowed down in that period, with value-added tax revenues
up 11 percent, consumer tax up 10 percent, and business tax up
28.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the first 11 months of this year, taxes on securities
trading surged 355 percent over the same period of last
year. During that period, personal income tax, private enterprise
income tax, and foreign-funded enterprise income tax grew 36.6,
44.1 and 36.8 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that the slowdown in the growth of the major
taxes was one of the major problems in the fiscal sector, which
include delayed payment of taxes by enterprises and fiscal
pressure caused by bad bank loans to enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Liu told the meeting that China will continue to follow a
moderately tight financial policy next year and will step up
financial reforms.
</P>
<P>
The central government will increase transfer payments to
underdeveloped areas, Liu said, and urged departments to make a
greater effort to improve fiscal and spending controls.  
</P>
</TEXT>
