<DOCNO> XIE19971217.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Come Up With New Explanation For El Nino </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, December 17 (Xinhua) -- A new explanation for the El
Nino phenomenon - that it is the result of hot water flowing in
the oceanic crust - has come from the Geochemical Institute
(GCI) under the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS).
</P>
<P>
Scientists there believe that there is a large amount of water
in the earth's crust that is no less than that contained in the
hydrosphere, or the earth's water envelope and that each year the
amount of water entering the sea from the oceanic crust is a tenth
of the amount of surface runoff.
</P>
<P>
The high temperature water in the crust is very active,
especially under the mid-ocean ridge, and generally accompanies
earthquakes and volcanic activities. This movement is caused by
cool sea water that seeps into the oceanic crust through fissures
along the mid-ocean ridge and is gradually heated by lava flow,
leading to water convection which forces the hot water back into
the sea.
</P>
<P>
Scientists say that about 20 to 25 percent of the earth's heat
is dissipated in this way. GCI researchers explain that the hot
water flow in the eastern Pacific, near the mid-ocean ridge is
more violent than in the western part, causing a great deal of hot
water in the eastern Pacific, and when it reaches a certain
temperature, it affects the atmosphere, producing El Nino.
</P>
<P>
The scientists reached the conclusion after analyzing
environmental effects by monitoring soil temperatures resulting
from hot water flow in the crust. They discovered that soil
temperatures in China's coastal area increase when earthquakes in
the western Pacific occur.
</P>
<P>
This is believed to be the result of intense movement of the
Pacific Plate, which triggers earthquakes and stimulates more
violent hot water flow in oceanic crust as well, which in turn
raises the soil temperature.
</P>
<P>
Scientists have found that floods in China's coastal areas are
closely related to the rise in soil temperature. Flooding usually
occurs six months to a year and a half after the soil temperature
increases.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971217.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Industries Expect Lower Growth: Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Prospects are dim for some
domestic industries next year as high interest rates and a weaker
peso will continue to take their toll on the growth of these
industries, the Philippine News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted a study made by a group of economists of the
Manila-based University of Asia and the Pacific as saying that
construction will particularly slow down as a number of players
decided to postpone their investment plans.
</P>
<P>
The study attributed the slowdown to higher costs of imported
fuel and machinery equipment and higher interest payments on
commercial loans.
</P>
<P>
It said high interest rates and the already perceived softness
in the real estate market will also further pull down sales in
1998.
</P>
<P>
Banks, it said, will be reluctant to expand real-estate loans.
The peso devaluation will also cause construction costs to rise,
another factor that will keep a lid on growth in the sector.
</P>
<P>
Energy is another sector to be hardest hit by the peso
depreciation as some new entrants may slow their investment plans
for the country, the report said.
</P>
<P>
But textile manufacture, footwear and wearing apparel
industries, which experienced deceleration during the past few
years, are all seen to recover due to their lower prices on the
export market.
</P>
<P>
The study, however, warned against the government's plan of
reducing tariffs, which, it said, could affect gains of the
sector.
</P>
<P>
The report further said that car sales which are in a slump
after the peso depreciation, may also dampen the prospects of the
rubber manufacturing industry.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, manufacturing industries are seen to
recover in 1998 with a growth of 4.8 percent, thereby pushing
industrial growth to 5.45 percent.
</P>
<P>
Growth of the services sector will still be high at 6.56
percent in 1997 and 6.69 percent in 1998 despite the slowdown in
real estate, it predicted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
