<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: COMESA's Progress in Trade Promotion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The Common Market for Southern
and Eastern Africa (COMESA) has made considerable progress in
trade development and promotion in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The annual intra-COMESA trade jumped from 834 million U.S.
Dollars in 1985 to 1.7 billion Dollars in 1994 and is expected to
reach 4 billion Dollars soon.
</P>
<P>
Since it was established in December 1994 to replace the
Preferential Trade Area for Eastern and Southern Africa (PTA) set
up in 1981, the COMESA has taken many measures to promote trade
among its member states.
</P>
<P>
COMESA tariffs have been reduced on the average by 70 percent
while some member countries have already reduced their tariffs by
80 percent.
</P>
<P>
The reduction of tariffs will definitely give a big
competitive edge to the products of the sub-region compared to
those from non-COMESA countries.
</P>
<P>
The COMESA member countries have also eliminated all the major
non-tariff barriers to intra-COMESA trade such as restrictive
import licensing, foreign exchange allocation and tax on foreign
exchange.
</P>
<P>
The COMESA rules of origin have been liberalized and
streamlined in order to facilitate preferential trade and
encourage foreign direct investment.
</P>
<P>
Now even products produced by enterprises which are owned and
managed totally by foreigners can enjoy COMESA preferential
tariff treatment provided they qualify under any one of the four
criteria of the COMESA rules of origin.
</P>
<P>
A schedule of common external tariff of zero, five, 15 and 30
percent on capital goods, raw materials, intermediate goods and
final goods respectively have been worked out and a COMESA
customs union will be set up by 2004.
</P>
<P>
The common external tariff will provide the business community
with a level playing ground in the COMESA market for competition.
</P>
<P>
COMESA have also implemented a number of programs to promote
trade, including supply and demand surveys, buyers and sellers
contact meetings, trade information services, enterprise-specific
assistance and trade fairs.
</P>
<P>
These programs have helped some companies identify trade
opportunities and improve their competitiveness. As one of the
outcomes of the programs, five general and two specialized trade
fairs as well as the buyers and sellers meetings have generated
over 800 million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
COMESA has established the PTA Trade and Development Bank to
mobilize financial and technical resources for investors and for
trade financing; the COMESA Clearing House to promote
intra-COMESA trade transacted in member countries; and the COMESA
Re-insurance Company.
</P>
<P>
In order to facilitate trade in the subregion, the Automated
System for Customs Data (ASYCUDA) has been installed in many
member countries.
</P>
<P>
The system accompanied by the simplification and harmonization
of procedures and documents assists in clearing goods faster from
customs, in generating up-to-date and accurate statistics on
international trade, and increasing the revenues of the member
countries because of more efficient and effective assessment and
collection of duties and other taxes on imports.
</P>
<P>
In order to facilitate intra-COMESA trade, the sub-regional
grouping has also installed EUROTRACE in most member countries.
EUROTRACE is computerization of foreign trade statistics.
</P>
<P>
The COMESA decided last month to set up a court of justice to
provide interpretation on the provisions of the COMESA treaty and
ensure that the member countries comply with the COMESA timetable
of program implementation.
</P>
<P>
The formation of the court of justice to be a whipping
institution for backsliders may help COMESA achieve its main
objectives to assist the member states in attaining rapid and
sustainable economic growth and development, and to promote joint
development in all fields of economic activity and the joint
adoption of macro-economic policies and programs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971217.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
