<HEADLINE> Foreign, Joint-Venture Banks Expand in Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Foreign and joint-venture banks
in Vietnam have rapidly expanded their scope of fund mobilization
in both the domestic and international markets, a senior banking
official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Quoted by "Vietnam News," Do Que Luong, acting governor of
Vietnam's State Bank, said the amount of the fund mobilization at
the moment totals 21,000 billion Vietnam dong (about 17.1 million
U.S. dollars), or 19 percent of all funds raised by the banking
system in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Outstanding loans reached 19,000 billion dong (about 15.45
dollars), or 23 percent of the total lending by the banking
system, Luong said.
</P>
<P>
The official noted that the ratio of medium and long-term
credits has increased considerably to 35 percent of outstanding
loans by foreign and joint-venture banks.
</P>
<P>
Many new opportunities are available in Vietnam although
countries in Southeast Asia are experiencing a monetary and
financial crisis, the acting governor said.
</P>
<P>
The laws governing the State Bank and credit institutions
approved by the latest session of Vietnam's National Assembly will
pave the way for a comprehensive legal framework for banking in
the country, he said.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's State Bank also intends to design appropriate
mechanisms for a legal framework to help foreign banks utilize
their own strengths to ensure efficiency and expansion, the
official added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
