<HEADLINE> Human Genes Introduced Into Sheep to Get Insulin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists have
introduced human genes into sheep as a source of insulin from
their milk.
</P>
<P>
The experiment was done in the Nanshan Sheep Bio-technology Lab
and the Hutubi Livestock Bio-engineering Research Center in
China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, which are part of the
Ministry of Agriculture's Livestock Bio-technology Open Lab.
</P>
<P>
Scientists at the two labs injected fragment of human DNA into
sheep sperm and bred sheep using artificial insemination in the
hopes that they could produce sheep carrying human genes.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, they succeeded in breeding 18 sheep from which a
source of insulin could be extracted. A year later, when the sheep
lambed, scientists were able to extract 16 milligrams of human
proinsulin from a liter of the milk, which could further be
refined into insulin, for use in treating diabetes.
</P>
<P>
The two labs have 77 of the genetically altered sheep,
including the 18 that produced the human proinsulin.
</P>
<P>
The gene-transfer technology has made it possible to produce
large amounts of human protein, and insulin, efficiently and
inexpensively. Experts say that because there is no way to
mass-produce protein medicines in China at present, this insulin
extraction method may mean a breakthrough in diabetes treatment in
China.
</P>
<P>
According to WHO statistics, only cardiovascular diseases and
cancer exceed diabetes in the number of occurrences in the world.
</P>
<P>
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971217.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
