<HEADLINE> Clinton to Unveil Plan for Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said today that he would announce his plan in the next few days on
whether to keep U.S. troops in Bosnia beyond June, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a year-end press conference, Clinton said he will
announce the plan before he flies to Bosnia on Sunday to visit
U.S. troops stationed there.
</P>
<P>
"We are discussing now...both within the administration, with
our allies in NATO and our other allies, and with Congress what
should be done," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration has been caught between pressure
from many Congressmen who want a timely pullout and from Europeans
who say the peace mission in Bosnia will collapse if the Americans
leave.
</P>
<P>
Any further deployment of U.S. troops in Bosnia will have to be
approved by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
"I think one of the things that all of our military people
agree on is that we must do more to beef up the civilian police
there and that there must be a distinction between what we expect
our military leaders to do and what we expect the civilian police
to do," Clinton told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Clinton noted that if there is to be a mission after the
withdrawal, "it also must have clear objective components with
some way of knowing whether the mission has been achieved or not."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and its allies currently deploy altogether 30,000
troops in Bosnia, 8,000 from the United States.
</P>
<P>
The mandate of the so-called Stabilization Force (SFOR) expires
in June. 
</P>
</TEXT>
