<HEADLINE> World Bank Approves Assistance for Three Developing Nations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank Tuesday
approved three credits and a loan totaling 123.3 million
U.S. dollars to Egypt, Eritrea and Guinea for their development
projects.
</P>
<P>
A credit of some 15 million dollars and a loan of 20 million
dollars are earmarked for Egypt's Pollution Abatement Project.
</P>
<P>
The objectives of this pilot project are to strengthen the
monitoring and enforcement capabilities of the environmental
institutions and establish technical and financial mechanisms for
pollution abatement investments in Greater Cairo, Alexandria, and
the two Suez Canal cities of Suez and Ismailia.
</P>
<P>
Another credit of some 18.3 million dollars will be used for an
Eritrea health project.
</P>
<P>
The project is designed to contribute to reductions in infant
and under-five mortality rates, maternal mortality ratio, and
total fertility rate as well as prevalence rates of malnutrition
in women and in under-five children, tuberculosis, malaria and
some other diseases.
</P>
<P>
The third credit of some 70 million dollars is to help
Guinea's public expenditure management adjustment.
</P>
<P>
The project is an integral part of the World Bank's strategy to
help Guinea ensure financial sustainability and improve public
service effectiveness in sectors which benefit the majority of the
poor.
</P>
<P>
Another objective is to help this west African country overhaul
the whole management of its budget as a serious first step towards
improving governance.
</P>
<P>
The credits will be channeled through the International
Development Association, the World Bank's concessionary lending
wing for developing countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
