<HEADLINE> Old Chinese Revolutionary Base Uses Oil Industry To Improve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Oil has become a major part of
the economy of Yan'an, the old Communist revolutionary base in
Shaanxi Province in northwestern China.
</P>
<P>
The city is expected to produce 2.8 million tons of crude oil
by the end of this year, an increase of 800,000 tons from 1996,
according to Vice-Mayor Xiao Changhua. Taxes paid by the oil
industry now account for at least 60 percent of the city's
revenues.
</P>
<P>
The Yanchang Oilfield, which has the first oil well drilled on
the Chinese mainland, was transferred to Yan'an's administration
in 1982.
</P>
<P>
The city government has been placing great emphasis on
exploration and has preferential policies to encourage it and
technical improvements. An oil refinery has also been built nearby.
</P>
<P>
Yanchang and the Changqing Oil Exploration Administration have
transferred some old wells or isolated oil-bearing structures to
counties for development, and given full support in technology and
equipment.
</P>
<P>
Ten county-level exploration companies have been established so
far. They have brought in at least 200 retired technical experts
and 100 million yuan in capital, and have produced more than
600,000 tons of crude oil. 
</P>
