<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Timber Industry Accused of Using Soft Money to Keep Road Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- A United States private
environmental group has accused the timber industry of using large
amount of "soft money" in securing funds for constructing logging
roads in national forests this year.
</P>
<P>
"Timber interests tripled their soft-money spending in 1995-96,
a move that seemed to help them gain leverage with Congress," said
Common Cause President Ann McBride Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Soft money is largely unregulated contributions to promote
party-building and other efforts not related directly to
individual candidates.
</P>
<P>
McBride said that senators who voted in September against
cutting off the roads spending received an average of 27,337
dollars in contributions since 1991 from the American Forest &AMP;
Paper Association (AFPA) and the political action committees of
its member companies.
</P>
<P>
The amendment by Senator Richard Bryan failed 51-49. A similar
measure in the House fell short 211-209.
</P>
<P>
The industry gave 1.5 million dollars in soft money to parties
in 1995-1996 -- up from 481,960 dollars in 1993-94 and 345,120
dollars in 1991-92, a Common Cause report said, adding that
environmental groups fighting the logging roads gave no soft money
during the period.
</P>
<P>
Critics of the road program say it amounts to a subsidy to the
timber industry. It reimburses companies for road-building costs
with credits they can use to bid on new timber sales.
</P>
<P>
AFPA spokesman Frank Stewart said Tuesday that the trade group
was reviewing the report.
</P>
<P>
AFPA President W. Henson Moore had said in the past that the
program is the most efficient way to construct roads that are used
for fighting fires, recreation and local traffic as well as
logging.
</P>
<P>
"I'm just wondering if Common Cause is saying the 1.6 million
timber workers and their families that we represent shouldn't have
a voice in Washington?" AFPA spokeswoman Kate Watson said. "We are
playing by the same rules our critics play by."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
