<HEADLINE> Clinton Honors Scientists With National Medals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Tuesday honored 14 leaders in science and technology with the
National Medal of Science and National Medal of Technology.
</P>
<P>
Recipients of the National Medal of Technology include Robert
Ledley for biomedical computing and engineering. He invented the
whole-body CT scanner; Ray Dolby, whose research and technology
helped improve sound recording and reproduction; and Norman
Augustine for his achievements in the aerospace industry.
</P>
<P>
Recipients of the National Medal of Science include James
Watson, co-discoverer of the double-helix structure of DNA;
William Estes of Harvard University for his theories of learning,
memory and decision; Robert Weinberg of the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology for finding cellular oncogenes and their
role in cancer; and Shing-tung Yao of Harvard for math and physics.
</P>
<P>
During a ceremony at the White House, Clinton announced 96
million U.S. dollars in federal funding to promote private
technological research that includes work to develop a new
generation computer chip. 
</P>
</TEXT>
