<HEADLINE> Finland to Merge State-run Energy Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The Finnish government today
decided to merge two state-run energy companies into a new
energy group, the largest of its kind in the country.
</P>
<P>
The merger of the Nes te Oil Company and the Imatra Electric
Power Company, with 80 and 100 percent of their shares controlled
by the government respectively, is aimed at strengthening the
competitiveness and adaptability of the country's state-owned
energy enterprises in the increasingly open North American and
European markets.
</P>
<P>
Nes te and Imatra, which recorded a sales volume of 43.4
Finnish markkas (12.1 billion U.S. dollars) billion and 12.1
billion Finnish markkas (2.28 billion U.S. dollars), respectively,
last year, will be grouped into the country's largest energy
company, with a total workforce of 16,000 people.
</P>
<P>
The new company, analysts say, can take advantage of its highly
internationalized status to explore the international markets of
energy products and technology and consulting service.
</P>
<P>
Finland adopted the policy of reforming its state-owned
companies in 1995 when the current government came to power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
