<HEADLINE> Japanese PM Unveils Drastic Tax Cut Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto announced Wednesday a plan to implement special tax cuts of 2
trillion yen (about 15.7 billion dollars) in the fiscal 1997
supplementary budget to stimulate the sagging economy.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at an emergency press conference, Hashimoto said that the
step is designed to prevent the economic problem "originated in Japan
from causing global depression."
</P>
<P>
He said the government will issue deficit-covering bonds to finance
the tax cuts, which will be implemented only for one year.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto's announcement turned around the sentiment of the Tokyo
stock market. The key Nikkei index, which was lower in the early
morning, responded quickly to the news about Hashimoto's announcement,
briefly soaring more than 800 points.
</P>
<P>
The news also circulated in other financial markets, bolstering the
yen's value against the U.S. dollar and pushing down prices of
long-term Japanese government bonds.
</P>
<P>
At noon, the U.S. dollar was quoted at 127.67-70 yen, down from
131.20-22 yen at 9 a.m. It briefly sank below 127 yen shortly before
noon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
