<DOCNO> XIE19971217.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNICEF Report: Six Million Children Die of Malnutrition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Around six million children die
across the world every year as a direct or indirect result of
malnutrition, the U.N. children's fund UNICEF said.
</P>
<P>
The impact of malnutrition on the world's children was the
center piece of UNICEF's 1998 report, which was released today.
</P>
<P>
The report said that despite the alarming number of children
lacking adequate nourishment, the problem was rarely considered an
emergency.
</P>
<P>
"The children that suffer from malnutrition often don't feel
hunger and they show very few signs of disease," the report said.
"And yet this killer is responsible for over half the annual child
deaths in the world."
</P>
<P>
"Half of southern Asia's child population is malnourished," it
went on to say. "In Africa one in three children was born
underweight and in some areas there were even worse cases of this
kind."
</P>
<P>
Research has shown that malnutrition at an early age is often
linked to chronic illness in adult life, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
