<HEADLINE> 1998 Budget of Sri Lanka Passed in Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The 1998 budget of the Sri
Lankan government was passed in the parliament Tuesday, local
newspaper Daily News reported today.
</P>
<P>
The budget got passed by a margin of 46, with 127 voting for
and 81 against. The parliament has 225 seats.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic People's Liberation Front, the Tamil United
Liberation Front and the Eelam People's Democratic Party voted
with the People's Alliance government for the budget while the
main opposition United National Party voted against, the paper
said.
</P>
<P>
In concluding the voting, Speaker K. B. Ratnayake described the
budget debate as "exhaustive and hectic" and thanked the members
for their support.
</P>
<P>
The fourth budget bill of the ruling People's Alliance
government was presented to the parliament on November 5.
</P>
<P>
The budget anticipates a total revenue and foreign grants of
214.7 billion Rupees (3.58 billion U.S. dollars) as against a
total expenditure of 327.7 billion Rupees (5.5 billion dollars) in
1998, leaving a budget deficit of 113 billion Rupees (1.9 billion
dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
