<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bosnia's Nationality Law to Go into Effect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The European Union's senior
representative to Bosnia Carlos Westendorp announced at Sarajevo
Tuesday that the Nationality Law of the Republic of Bosnia and
Herzegovina will soon become effective.
</P>
<P>
Westendorp made the announcement when the Bosnian parliament
failed to reach an agreement on the law.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time Westendorp has exercised the power
vested in him by the committee for the execution of the Dayton
Peace Agreement. The agreement states that Westendorp can make
decisions when the three Bosnian parties fail to agree on relevant
issues.
</P>
<P>
According to Westendorp's decision, the law will go into effect
on January 1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Bosnian parliamentary conference held at Sarajevo Tuesday
passed the Council of Ministers Law and the Passport Law, but did
not reach an agreement on the issue of dual nationality in the
Nationality Law.
</P>
<P>
Westendorp notified in writing the presidency of the Republic
of Bosnia, which includes Alija Izetbegovic, Kresimir Zubak and
Momcilo Krajisnik, about his decision.
</P>
<P>
He stressed in his letter that it was agreed during the Bonn
meeting that the Bosnian Nationality Law would be passed. His
decision, he said, will continue to be effective until the Bosnian
parliament comes to an agreement concerning the law.
</P>
<P>
Westendorp asked the parliament to make a statement to
acknowledge the Bonn meeting agreement on dual nationality in
compliance with the Constitution of Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Westendorp stresses in his letter that he will continue to make
full use of his power to ensure compliance with the Dayton Peace
Agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971217.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Sets NATO Summit in 1999 for New Members </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said Tuesday that the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO)
would hold a summit in Washington in the spring of 1999 to welcome
Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic into the alliance.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a year-end press conference, Clinton said, "the
entry of Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic into the alliance
will make America safer, NATO stronger, and Europe more stable and
united."
</P>
<P>
"The United States has led the way in transforming our
alliance; now we should be among the first to vote yes for NATO's
historic engagement," he added.
</P>
<P>
In July, the 16-member alliance agreed to invite Poland,
Hungary and the Czech Republic to join by 1999, the NATO's 50th
anniversary. The agreement needs to be ratified by the parliaments
of the members.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the foreign ministers from the alliance signed
formal accession documents to begin the process of accepting these
countries as new members.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Senate will vote early next year on the alliance's
expansion plan. Clinton had promised to seek an approval. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971217.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Ministers' Salaries Cut by 20 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The Thai cabinet Tuesday
approved a 20 percent salary cuts for all of its members,
including the prime minister, ministers and deputy ministers,
according to a Government House press release available today.
</P>
<P>
The salary reduction, to be effective from this month and in
force for 12 months, will save more than a million baht (21,600
U.S. dollars) from public spending.
</P>
<P>
The reduction is part of the government's efforts to cut public
spending to meet the demand of the International Monetary Fund,
which it set for the provision of the 17.2 billion dollar bailout
package.
</P>
<P>
The pre-cut official salary for the prime minister was 64,000
baht, or about 1,385 dollars at the current exchange rate, while a
minister earned 62,000 baht (1,340 dollars).
</P>
<P>
Members of Parliament are also considering a similar move.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the tripartite wage committee Tuesday decided on
increases in the minimum daily wage for next year.
</P>
<P>
A five-baht hike will be effective in Bangkok, Phuket and five
other provinces near the capital, raising the minimum wage for
these seven places from 157 baht to 162 baht.
</P>
<P>
A three-baht increase will be applicable to six provinces,
where the current minimum wages are 137 baht, and a two-baht
increase for the rest 63 provinces of the country to raise the
minimum wage there to 130 baht.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
