<HEADLINE> China Values New Nuclear Technologies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 17 (Xinhua) -- While the world's leading
nuclear power suppliers are muscling their way into the potential
vast Chinese market, China said yesterday it will select partners
through public bidding, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
Tang Zide, deputy director with the nuclear power office under
the State Planning Commission, promised that such bidding will be
"fair, open and just."
</P>
<P>
He told a seminar yesterday in Beijing that the selection of
foreign partners will be based on such principles as the technology
must be safe, advanced and mature; foreign partners must transfer
their technologies; foreign partners must be those with which
China can establish long-term co-relationships; and the
co-operation must be mutually beneficial.
</P>
<P>
Tang said China plans to design its own nuclear technology,
manufacturing , construction and operation through localization of
foreign technologies.
</P>
<P>
He said Chinese nuclear power circles paid great attention to
the progress of the Advanced Boiling Water Reactor(ABWR), developed
by General Electric (GE), Hitachi and Toshiba.
</P>
<P>
Although none of China's existing two nuclear power plants and
the four designed to be constructed in the Ninth Five-year
Plan(1996-2000)adopted boiling water reactor, China does not rule
out the possibility of introducing such reactors in the future, a
GE official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
