<DOCNO> XIE19971217.0284 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Bank Re-imposes Cap on Dollar Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The Bankers' Association of the
Philippines has re-imposed a 2 percent cap on banks' selling rate
of U.S. dollars for over-the-counter (OTC) sales.
</P>
<P>
Local press reports today quoted Deogracias Vistan, president
of the association, as saying that this means banks can not sell
greenbacks OTC at a price 2 percent more than that of the previous
day's weighted average foreign exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
The measure, which took effect on Tuesday, was meant to keep
banks from profiting excessively from the weakening peso, Vistan
said.
</P>
<P>
The move came as some banks had been selling dollars at rates
between 40 to 45 after last Thursday when the peso started sinking
into new record lows.
</P>
<P>
The peso hit a new low of 40.214 to the dollar from an opening
of 39.44 Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
By re-imposing a limit on price spreads, the association hopes
to narrow the gap between banks' buying and selling rates and
thus, help ease speculative pressures against the peso, Vistan
said.
</P>
<P>
The association first implemented a 4 percent ceiling which was
later reduced to only 2 percent upon the central bank's request.
</P>
<P>
The ceiling was totally scrapped in early August when the
initial panic had lost steam and the differential between the
rates at the official markets and the parallel markets narrowed
down.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971217.0285 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibet Stresses Environmental Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The Tibet Autonomous Region has
stepped up environmental protection to ensure the steady
development of its economy.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1990s, the Regional People's Congress has adopted 20
regulations on environmental protection, wildlife protection, land
use and urban construction.
</P>
<P>
The region has taken environmental protection as an important
task in industrial production, building grains production bases,
and infrastructure construction.
</P>
<P>
New regulations prohibit construction of paper mills with
an annual capacity of less than 5,000 tons and heavily-polluting
factories.
</P>
<P>
Existing heavily-polluting enterprises are adopting new
technology and equipment, in order to bring pollution control to
state-set standards within a given time.
</P>
<P>
With the help of the Central Government and other parts of the
country, Tibet has established the Regional Environment Monitoring
Station, and similar stations in Xigaze and Qamdo prefectures. The
stations conduct regular monitoring of air quality, water quality,
noise and polluting sources on the Tibet Plateau.
</P>
<P>
Tibet has established an environment research institute, which
has carried out research into local soil environment, the standard
of natural radioactivity in local environment and industrial
pollution.
</P>
<P>
Experts from the Tibet Regional Bureau of Environmental
Protection said that by the end of this century, some 90 percent
of the region's industrial waste gas will have been treated, and
45 percent of solid waste will have been used for other purposes.
</P>
<P>
They said, by then, climate environmental quality will meet the
first-class standard set by the state and the per-capita green
space will reach eight to 12 square meters.
</P>
<P>
By the end of this century, grass will be planted on a total of
300,000 mu (20,000 hectares) of land and one million mu (some
66,666.66 hectares) of grassy land is expected to be improved, in
a bid to better protect local arable land and ecological
environment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
