<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pre-Inca Cultural Relics Found in Argentina </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Huge dressed stones and
drawings of pre-Inca people were found recently in the town of
Fiambala in the Argentine province of Catamarca, press reports
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The province`s Anthropology Bureau said that the discovery
proves the presence of Tihuanaco culture in the region, which was
believed to be earlier than Inca culture.
</P>
<P>
Researchers in Fiambala said that Tihuanaco culture had been
found in the south coast of the Titicaca Lake in Bolivia, 3,815
meters above sea level.
</P>
<P>
Tihuanaco culture is simultaneous to the culture of Mochaica
and Nazca, the prime time of which dated between 400 to 1000 A.D.
</P>
<P>
After 1000 A.D., this culture spread to Bolivia, Peru,
Northwestern Argentina and Northern Chile till 1300 A.D. 
</P>
</TEXT>
