<HEADLINE> Andean Community Submits Proposal For Tax-Exemption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Countries of the Andean
Community submitted a proposal Tuesday to the Southern Common
Market (Mercosur) for the gradual exemption of tariffs for 15-18
years to help establish a free trade agreement between the two
blocs.
</P>
<P>
The proposal includes a small number of goods and ratifies the
will of Andean countries to create a South American economic bloc,
said Andean Community President Benigno Sotomayor, who is also the
commerce minister of Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
The Andean Community consists of Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador,
Peru and Venezuela, and the Mercosur group is made of include
Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
Under the proposal, the lowering of duties would last for 15-18
years and benefit 50 percent of the current trade.
</P>
<P>
Sotomayor said the duty exemption in the proposal represents
only 25 percent of the total duties of the two blocs.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the transition period, the countries of the two
organizations must render exemptions, which will be included in a
common foreign tariff to be lowered in accordance with a
timetable, added Sotomayor.
</P>
<P>
The list of products included in the proposal can not be
modified or increased after the accord is signed. He said the
motion includes the automobile sector and the results of
controversial measures fixed by the World Trade Organization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
