<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Child Farm Workers' Health Threatened by Pesticides </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Across the United States,
tens of thousands of children work in a sea of toxic chemicals
whose long-term health effects are almost completely unknown.
</P>
<P>
Government standards for pesticide residues in the nation's
food supply are set with special attention to the children who eat
that food. Yet those who work in the fields receive pesticide
doses many times higher than the law allows in American diets.
</P>
<P>
"Everybody stands there with a straight face and talks about
protecting children, and they don't do anything to protect child
workers," The Associated Press quoted Marion Moses, a pediatrician
with the Pesticide Education Center in San Francisco, as saying.
"I don't think that we should be dosing children very early in
life with toxic chemicals."
</P>
<P>
An unreleased U.S. Department of Labor survey shows that
123,000 children between the ages of 14 and 17 work in the U.S.
fields. Uncounted thousands more are under 14, according to an AP
report.
</P>
<P>
"Protecting the health of our children is one of our highest
priorities," Environmental Protection Agency administrator Carol
Browner told a conference of doctors and scientists in September.
</P>
<P>
But until this year, the federal government spent next to
nothing for occupational health and safety research on child farm
workers, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The National Institute of Occupational Safety and Health did
hand out 2.5 million dollars for research on injuries to child
farm workers, but the effort pales next to the 700 million dollars
the Department of Agriculture's Agricultural Research Service
spends each year on crop and livestock studies.
</P>
<P>
Children on farms occasionally suffer severe pesticide
poisoning, sometimes fatally.
</P>
<P>
Such confirmed incidents of acute pesticide poisoning are rare
-- or at least rarely reported. Of greater concern to experts is
long-term, low-level damage that can show up decades after a child
has picked his or her last berry.
</P>
<P>
"Compared to late-in-life exposures, exposures to pesticides
early in life can lead to a greater risk of chronic effects that
are expressed only after long latency periods have elapsed," a
National Academy of Sciences committee said in a 1993 report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971217.0298 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukraine to Adjust Currency Exchange Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The Ukrainian government will in
late December or early January announce a change in the currency
fluctuation band for the second half of 1998, a senior Ukrainian
official said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Sergy Tygypko, first deputy prime minister for economic
reforms, said the range of the band had not yet been agreed with
the International Monetary Fund (IMF), which sent a delegation
last week on a ten-day visit to Kiev to discuss Ukraine's economic
performance, including currency issues.
</P>
<P>
The present currency range in Ukraine is 1.7 to 1.9 hryvnas to
the dollar. The band for the first half of next year will be 1.75
to 1.95 hryvnas to the dollar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
