<HEADLINE> Ukraine's New Parties Gear Up for Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Small political parties in
Ukraine are becoming more aggressive in their campaigns for the
approaching parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
New and relatively unknown parties have successfully qualified
to participate in the race.
</P>
<P>
The Central Electoral Committee said on Tuesday that a number
of new parties, such as Women of Ukraine, The Greens Party and
Reforms and Order, have already gathered the Minimum 200,000
signatures needed to qualify for the parliamentary election
scheduled on March 29-30 next year.
</P>
<P>
"We are hoping that our party, which is clean, non-criminal and
not financed by Western funds, will eventually gain support." said
Alina Komarova, leader of the Women of Ukraine, which was founded
in March 1997.
</P>
<P>
Mykhail Pavlovsky, spokesman for Reforms and Order, a Party
established this fall, said the party had the required number of
signatures. He said it was the names of well-known politicians
topping the party's ticket that convinced people to lend their
support, rather than any particular platform.
</P>
<P>
Reforms and Order's list of candidates includes famous
reformist Viktor Pynzenik, a former deputy prime minister who
resigned earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
"All centrist parties have a similar election program, but
people give their votes to big names, who do not need any
commentary," said Pavlovsky. 
</P>
</TEXT>
