<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia`s Exports Increase 13 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Colombia's export
value went up 13.4 percent over the first nine months of this year
compared with that of the corresponding period last year, the
National Administrative Department of Statistics said today.
</P>
<P>
Exports from January to September reached 8.49 billion
U.S. dollars as compared with 7.67 billion dollars for the same
period in 1996, according to the department.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, imports amounted to 11.1 billion dollars, compared
to 10.13 billion dollars in 1996, which resulted in a trade
deficit of 2.6 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The main export product was coffee, which reached 1.65 billion
dollars from January to September, compared with 1.11 billion
dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
The export of coal accounted for 696 million dollars, while
nickel exports reached 127 million over the referred period, with
increases of 15 and 10 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
The sales of some non-traditional exports, such as sugar and
candies also reached 235 million dollars, 67 million dollars more
than that of the previous year. The export of fruit and plastics
also recorded impressive increases.
</P>
<P>
The most dynamic imports were consumption goods, which grew 28
percent to 2.1 billion dollars, compared to 1.64 billion dollars
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The import of raw material went up 4.92 billion dollars over
January-September as compared to 4.65 billion dollars a year
earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
