<DOCNO> XIE19971217.0304 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vitamin Supplements Better Children's Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Nutrition experts from the
Chinese Academy of Preventive Medicine suggested yesterday that
proper multi-vitamin supplements may help children develop better.
</P>
<P>
The academy presented the results of its research tuesday in
Beijing at a national experts meeting to discuss the relationship
between vitamins and children's development, according to today's
China Daily.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 experts attended the meeting and voiced their
concern over child nutrition, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The experts reached their conclusion after studying 10,000
children aged four to nine in Beijing, 7,000 from the urban area
and the rest from three counties in Pinggu, Huairou and Shunyi
districts.
</P>
<P>
The children investigated were divided into two groups, one
given vitamin supplements, the other only taking vitamins through
meals.
</P>
<P>
A comparison showed that in just two and a half months, the
group with vitamin supplements grew 0.1 to 0.5 centimeters faster
than those not taking supplements.
</P>
<P>
Although there was little difference in weight, the blood
vitamin content was much higher in the supplement group, the paper
said.
</P>
<P>
The results also showed that about 18 percent of the children in
each group suffered from a lack of vitamin C before the research
began. The rate dropped to 0.4 percent in the group with
supplementary vitamins and to 15 percent among children in the
non-supplement group.
</P>
<P>
Fewer children got sick after taking vitamin supplements, said
Yin.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey by the Ministry of Health suggests that most
Chinese, including children, have enough to eat, but malnutrition
still exists due to dietary imbalance.
</P>
<P>
The survey showed that about 35 percent of Chinese children
below the age of five have failed to reach national indices for
physical development such as weight and height. The rate was as
high as 50 percent in some poor areas.
</P>
<P>
A number of children suffered from various malnutrition-related
ailments such as rickets and anaemia, which could impair their
physical health and intelligence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
