<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey Finds Only Child More Able Than Conceived </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, December 17 (Xinhua) -- A recent survey result defies a
generally-held conception that people without siblings are less
able or sociable than those from multi-born families.
</P>
<P>
The survey was conducted by sociologists and population experts
among 1,200 one-child families in Tianjin, one of the most
populous cities in China. The siblingless people surveyed are in
one to 46 age bracket.
</P>
<P>
It found that people from one-child families are better
educated. Each person aged between six to 20 is receiving education
that matches his or her age and 73.5 percent of them aged 21 or
above have received college education.
</P>
<P>
The only child is stereotyped as unable to take care of
themselves in daily life. They are psychologically weaker and less
enterprising and sociable than their peers from multi children
families.
</P>
<P>
The survey, however, shows that these people's ability to handle
daily-life needs are increasing as they grow up. By age 21, little
difference has been observed between them and people with sisters
and brothers in this regard.
</P>
<P>
A total of 34 out of 100 one-child surveyed said that they
would push ahead despite of setbacks and frustrations. 87.6
percent of the parents surveyed said their one-child gets along
quite well with them, their relatives and classmates.
</P>
<P>
Yet the survey found that people from one-child family who are
confident in overcoming setbacks and frustrations outnumbers those
who feel upset by 7.4 percentage points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971217.0309 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
