<HEADLINE> Aids Exhibition Held in Guangzhou </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Many Guangzhou residents are
drawing lessons for preventing themselves from contracting AIDS
from an ongoing exhibition of education about the fatal disease.
</P>
<P>
The 50-day exhibition, the largest of its kind in China,
provides knowledge of AIDS with more than 1,000 pictures and 20
documentary films.
</P>
<P>
"AIDS is a flood of the century. Chinese must build a solid
wall against the flood," said a retiree from the Guangzhou Bureau
of Parks and Gardens.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition is being sponsored by the Guangzhou City
Government and the China Venereal Diseases and Aids Foundation.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that China has detected more than 7,000 Aids
cases so far. However, experts estimated the actual number of
infected people at 160,000 to 200,000.
</P>
<P>
"The number of AIDS cases has at least doubled in recent years
in China," Qian Xinzhong, Chairman of the foundation, said, "We
must teach the people to know more about the disease." 
</P>
</TEXT>
