<HEADLINE> Lipinski Voted USOC's SportsWoman of the Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Olympic Committee
today named Tara Lipinski, the youngest figure skater ever to win
the world and U.S. championship titles, Sportswoman of the Year.
</P>
<P>
The award to Lipinski, who was 14 when she captured the titles
during a spectacular 1997 season, was determined by vote of the
USOC Board of Directors, the Athletes' Advisory Council and
national media.
</P>
<P>
Other top contenders for the award included soccer star Mia
Hamm, world champion sprinter Marion Jones and Olympic swimmer
Jenny Thompson.
</P>
<P>
Lipinski won the 1996-97 Champions Series of Figure Skating
title in February and went on to bag home medals in every
international event she entered last season.
</P>
<P>
The 15-year-old Lipinski becomes the second figure skater to
win the award since 1977 when Linda Fratianne claimed the honor.
</P>
