<HEADLINE> Clinton Not to Favor Lifting Sanctions on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton said
today that he would not favor any proposals for lifting sanctions
against Iraq unless it complied with U.N. resolutions on weapons
inspections.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference at the State Department, Clinton
said, "There are those that would like to lift the sanctions.... I
am not in favor of lifting sanctions until he (Iraqi President
Saddam Hussein) complies."
</P>
<P>
"I am willing to maintain the sanctions as long as he does not
comply with the resolutions," he added.
</P>
<P>
A crisis, which began late in October when Saddam ordered
American weapons inspectors to leave Iraq for their spying, is
still staying in the Gulf as the United States keeps mighty
military forces in the region and Iraq refused U.N. inspectors
access to "presidential areas" for weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
Richard Butler, chief U.N. weapons inspector, failed to
persuade Iraqi officials to enter these sensitive sites on his
four-day trip to Baghdad and returned to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
He will present a report on his Baghdad mission probably on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Mike McCurry called Iraq's refusal "the
latest episode, saying Saddam "has blocked access to sites in the
past."
</P>
<P>
McCurry said the United States would decide how to respond to
Iraq's refusal to the access to those presidential areas after
seeing Butler's report to the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
A State Department spokesman also said the United States would
first "see what the final UNSCOM (U.N. Special Commission) report
to the Security Council is."
</P>
<P>
"The latest Security Council resolution calls for full
unrestricted access to all sites that UNSCOM deems necessary. But
the council has to decide what to do about it," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
