<HEADLINE> Stock Market to Face Correction in 1998: Merrill Lynch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The recent deterioration in
the world's equity markets may be a sign that the post-1994 global
bull market is facing additional correction in 1998, according to
the U.S. consulting firm Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
The firm's chief market analyst Richard McCabe is of the view
that a four year cycle low is likely to occur in 1998 following
those in 1994 and 1990, Merrill Lynch said today in a newswire
service report.
</P>
<P>
McCabe predicted that a correction which could bring the major
averages down as much as 25 percent would likely set the stage for
the next bull market advance to begin in late 1998 or 1999.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. GDP growth is expected to slow to about 2.5 percent
in 1998 after growing nearly 4 percent in 1997, the firm said,
adding that the Asian financial turmoil should reduce U.S. growth
by at least half a percentage point next year.
</P>
<P>
Low inflation, falling interest rates and slower growth will
be the environment for investors globally in 1998, it said.
</P>
<P>
Restructuring and consolidation are seen as major sources of
earning growth for most companies.
</P>
<P>
Merrill Lynch suggested that airlines, financials, selected
energy and capital goods could be among "the industries in the
throes of consolidation." 
</P>
</TEXT>
