<HEADLINE> Sick Leave Costs Metropolitan Police 72 Mln Pounds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Sickness and injury cost
London's Metropolitan Police 72 million pounds (117.4 million US
dollars) last year, according to a National Audit Office study
published today.
</P>
<P>
The report said that on average 1,520 officers out of a total
27,000 were absent due to illness or injury every day last year
and almost 400,000 working days were lost because of sick leave.
</P>
<P>
Officers in the Metropolitan Police took an average of 14.4
days of sick leave last year, compared with a national average of
eight days.
</P>
<P>
The report urged Scotland Yard to examine how its sick-pay
system works, saying that long-term sickness and medical
retirements have been rising throughout the 1990s although
injuries on duty have fallen.
</P>
<P>
The audit office accepted that police officers face additional
strains because of an onerous and occasionally dangerous job, but
said that "high levels of sickness absence tend to reduce
efficiency. They may also lead to declining morale." 
</P>
</TEXT>
