<HEADLINE> New York Stocks Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Stocks in New York extended
their gains for a second day today as investors believe the
lowered inflation rate would convince the Federal Reserve to keep
interest rates unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average rose 53.72 points at 7,976.31.
</P>
<P>
Advancers outnumbered decliners by an 11-to-8 margin on the New
York Stock Exchange, where volume totaled 623.32 million shares as
against 596.39 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list was up 3.06 at 966.45, the
NYSE composite index was up 2.63 at 506.75, and the American Stock
Exchange composite index was up 3.61 at 668.88. The technology
laden Nasdaq composite index was up 16.42 at 552.98.
</P>
<P>
Concerns over the economic impact of the Asian currency crisis
on American businesses have eased in recent days as South Korea
and Japan have outlined plans to solve regional currency problems.
</P>
<P>
The Commerce Department said today that the Consumer Price
Index made its smallest gains in five months in November.
</P>
<P>
The rise held the annualized inflation rate for the first 11
months of the year to 1.8 percent -- the smallest since oil prices
crashed in 1986.
</P>
<P>
The news made investors believe that the Federal Reserve
policy-makers would leave interest rates unchanged, as expected.
</P>
