<HEADLINE> N.Irish Parties Fail to Reach Key Agreements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Northern Ireland's political
parties today failed to reach agreement at their last meeting this
year.
</P>
<P>
The province's Protestant and Catholic leaders could not agree
on a list of key issues. But they said they would resume
broadly-based talks in January.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the multi-party talks and former U.S. senator
George Mitchell said he was disappointed but denied that it meant
the death blow to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
He asserted that pro-British Protestant and pro-Irish Catholic
groups were now even more determined than ever before to move the
peace process forward.
</P>
<P>
"It is not what we hoped. It is disappointing but it is by no
means a disaster, by no means fatal," Mitchell told a news
conference. "The process will go on and I am confident that the
process is going to succeed."
</P>
<P>
The two major rival parties -- the Ulster Unionist Party and
Sinn Fein -- accused each other of failing to agree on issues to
be addressed when the peace talks restart in January.
</P>
<P>
The Ulster Unionist Party, the chief Protestant group, accused
Sinn Fein, the political arm of the outlawed Irish Republican
Army, of refusing to agree to discuss the creation of a Northern
Ireland Assembly.
</P>
<P>
But Sinn Fein countered that it was prepared to discuss
anything that was of relevance to any other party.
</P>
<P>
Britain and Ireland have set a May 1998 deadline for parties to
produce a peace package, and then put the outcome of the talks to
referendums in both parts of the divided island. 
</P>
</TEXT>
