<HEADLINE> Sudan's President Calls For Peace, National Unity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese President Omar
Hassan Ahmed al-Bashir today urged the governors of the 10
southern states to work for national unity and safeguard peace.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the swearing-in ceremony of the 10 governors,
al-Bashir also called on them to liberate the lands under rebel
control and defend liberated territories.
</P>
<P>
He described the present time as a historic phase in Sudan for
building peace and a new country free from foreign interference,
which is not what John Garang dreams of.
</P>
<P>
Garang, leader of the Sudan People's Liberation Army, the major
southern rebel group, has demanded a confederation of northern half
of Muslims and southern half of mostly Christians be set up, which
has been rejected by the Sudanese government.
</P>
<P>
The governors of the southern Sudanese states have been elected
recently as part of the effort to implement the Khartoum peace
agreement signed between the Sudanese government and six minor
southern rebel factions last April.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, a referendum will be held at the end of a
four-year transitional period by the southerners, who will retain
freedom of religion, press and assembly.
</P>
<P>
The agreement also offers a coordination council to the
southern states during the transitional period.
</P>
<P>
Rayak Mashar, chairman of the coordination council, has said
that the governments of the southern states will start to work
after the Christmas. 
</P>
