<HEADLINE> Simitis: Greece to Conditionally Support Turkey's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Greek Prime Minister Costas
Simitis today reiterated that his country would back Turkey's
European orientation if Ankara played by the rules.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after briefing Greek political leaders on EU's
Luxemburg conference, Simitis said that Athens did not want the
exclusion of Turkey or any other country from cooperation with the
Eropean Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
The decisions of the EU, he explained, was that this
cooperation should be based on "rules of the game."
</P>
<P>
He added that the EU was in fact asking Turkey and the other
countries to strengthen their cooperation with the organization in
order to avoid possible problems in the future.
</P>
<P>
As for possible threats by Turkey to escalate tension in the
Aegean Sea or annex the northern part of Cyprus, the premier said
that if Turkey was to take such a step, the country would only be
harming itself and would most likely make its entry into the EU
impossible.
</P>
<P>
He also urged Turkey to intensify its pressure throughout the
process of negotiations for Cyprus' accession to the EU in order
to secure "favorable decisions" for Ankara itself.
</P>
<P>
After its failure to be named candidate for the EU membership
in Luxemburg last week, Ankara accused the EU of discrimination
and threatened to end political talks with EU and integrate the
northern part of Cyprus into Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Greek government spokesman Dimitris Reppas today also warned
that it would be "a terrible mistake" if Turkey further "upgrade"
its relations with northern Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that Ankara's relations with northern Cyprus
were already very advanced, both in the economic and military
sectors.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that his country was ready to confront any
further Turkish initiative in this direction. 
</P>
