<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Homeless Up, Compassion Down, Says Advocacy Group </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Ten years after the signing
of federal homeless assistance legislation, homelessness is on the
increase in the United States, said The National Coalition for the
Homeless.
</P>
<P>
The coalition said that since homelessness is often a temporary
circumstance, rather than a permanent condition, it is difficult
to calculate the number of people affected. A 1996 study estimated
760,000 people are homeless on any given night.
</P>
<P>
A survey of 29 cities released by the U.S. Conference of Mayors
showed 20 percent of all requests for emergency shelter went unmet
due to lack of resources.
</P>
<P>
Mary Ann Gleason, executive director for the coalition, said
the public's anger and fear of those living on the streets is
misplaced, since public policy is forcing people from jails and
foster homes onto the streets and into shelters.
</P>
<P>
Gleason said, "What we do is create the homelessness, and then
we get mad that these people are so visibly poor on our streets."
</P>
<P>
Barbara Duffield, director of education for the coalition,
disputed the notion that many homeless could get jobs if they
wanted to.
</P>
<P>
Duffield said, "Try to get a job when you're homeless. Of ten
times, employers will reject people who don't have a permanent
address, who haven't been able to take a shower, who haven't been
able to print-up their resume. There are some real practical
barriers to employment."
</P>
<P>
Gleason said many homeless are employed, but don't make enough
money to pay rent. She suggested Congress fund job training,
low-cost housing and substance-abuse treatment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
