<HEADLINE> Mandela Slashes Opposition Parties at Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAFIKENG, South Africa, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The outgoing
president of South Africa's ruling African National Congress, Nelson
Mandela, today vented fire on opposition parties at the ANC national
conference.
</P>
<P>
The National Party (NP), the Democratic Party (DP) and the United
Democratic Movement (UDM) received most of his bullets and the Freedom
Front, Pan Africanist Congress and the Azanian People's Organization
were also attacked.
</P>
<P>
In a marathon 53-page presidential speech, Mandela described the
NP, DP and the UDM as "a miserable platoon of opponents" to the ANC.
</P>
<P>
"Throughout its years as the ruling party, and before, the National
Party consistently pursued the strategic goal of the destruction of
our movement and organization," Mandela said.
</P>
<P>
After the ANC came to power, the NP had not abandoned this
objective, he said. "The leopard has not changed its spots."
</P>
<P>
"Its only problem is that it lacks the power it once had, to pursue
this aim. Accordingly, it is involved in a desperate search to find
the ways and means to destroy its historic enemy, to enable it to
discharge its responsibility of defending white privilege."
</P>
<P>
As for the DP, Mandela said the party had sought to present itself
as the most effective parliamentary opposition to the ANC.
</P>
<P>
"The Democratic Party, which has no policy differences with the NP,
has sought to position itself as an implacable enemy of the ANC, and
on this basis, to convince NP supporters to switch allegiance to
itself."
</P>
<P>
"They both believe that their fortunes lie not so much in policies
they can propagate, but in their success in projecting themselves as
tireless fighters for the defeat of the ANC."
</P>
<P>
Mandela laid harsh criticisms on the UDM, led by former ANC leader
Bantu Holomisa and NP leader Roelf Meyer.
</P>
<P>
"The latest political grouping to join the miserable platoon of
opponents of our movement is the United Democratic Movement of Bantu
Holomisa and Roelf Meyer."
</P>
<P>
More vigorously than the DP, it had also sought to convince some NP
supporters that the UDM offered a more credible non-racial political
home than the NP.
</P>
<P>
"Inevitably, it will draw into its ranks some of the most backward
and corrupt elements in our society which have no interest whatsoever
in promoting the interest of the people," Mandela said.
</P>
<P>
The NP fought back today, saying that Mandela's speech was
unstatemsman-like and paranoid.
</P>
<P>
"We would only hope that the paranoia which characterized much of
his speech is not indicative of government thinking," said executive
NP director Renier Schoeman.
</P>
<P>
More attacks from other parties are expected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
