<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two-Million-Year-Old Fossils Found in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Fossilized remains of two
hominid babies believed to be about two-million-year-old have been
found in South Africa's Gauteng Province, South African Press
Association reported today.
</P>
<P>
The discovery was made by South African and French paleontologists
early in August this year, the French Embassy announced today.
</P>
<P>
Research indicated that the remains were those of a child less than
three years old when it died.
</P>
<P>
"This individual belonged to the genus homo and is the first fossil
baby of such high antiquity ever found," the embassy said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The find consisted of both maxillae (frontal facial bones including
jaw and cheek) a permanent tooth and a frontal bone.
</P>
<P>
The remains were those of a baby paranthropus or robust
australopithecine.
</P>
<P>
"Judging from the development of the teeth, this individual was a
tiny baby when it died -- perhaps less than a year old. It is by far
the youngest baby of an early hominid ever found and it will throw a
great deal of light on development of the facial region..."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
