<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pentagon Panel Suggests Separate Barracks for Women </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- A Pentagon advisory panel
today recommended U.S. Army, Navy and Air Force put male and
female recruits in separate barracks and segregate men and women
in their earlier phases of basic training.
</P>
<P>
The 11-member panel also called for toughening basic training
and physical fitness standards for both men and women, and urged
the Pentagon to increase the number of female trainers.
</P>
<P>
The move is to improve morale and curb sexual harassment of
women in the U.S. military following a number of Army male drill
sergeants convicted of harassment and rape of women recruits.
</P>
<P>
The Pentagon stressed that the Army, Navy and Air Force will
continue joint training of men and women.
</P>
<P>
But the panel called on the services to appoint more female
trainers and to provide those trainers with better instruction on
sexual awareness. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
